 = \n| blank_name               = \n| blank_info               = \n| blank1_name              = \n| blank1_info              = \n| website                  = \n| footnotes                =\n}}\n'''Duey Alto''' is a [[Barrios of Puerto Rico|barrio]] in the municipality of [[San Germ\u00e1n, Puerto Rico]]. Its population in 2010 was 1,350.<ref name=\"Pico_1969\">{{cite book |last1=Pic\u00f3 |first1=Rafael |last2=Buitrago de Santiago |first2=Zayda |last3=Berrios |first3=Hector H. |title=Nueva geograf\u00eda de Puerto Rico: f\u00edsica, econ\u00f3mica, y social, por Rafael Pic\u00f3. Con la colaboraci\u00f3n de Zayda Buitrago de Santiago y H\u00e9ctor H. Berrios. |url=https://archive.org/details/nuevageografad00pic/page/247|publisher=San Juan Editorial Universitaria, Universidad de Puerto Rico,1969}}</ref><ref name=\"Law2015\">{{cite book|author=Gwillim Law|title=Administrative Subdivisions of Countries: A Comprehensive World Reference, 1900 through 1998| url =https://books.google.com/books?id=nXCeCQAAQBAJ|accessdate=25 December 2018|date=20 May 2015|publisher=McFarland|isbn=978-1-4766-0447-3|page=300}}</ref><ref name= \"2010 Census\">{{cite book|title=Puerto Rico:2010:population and housing unit counts.pdf | url = https://permanent.access.gpo.gov/gpo35934/cph-2-53.pdf|year=2010|publisher=U.S. Dept. of Commerce, Economics and Statistics Administration, U.S. Census Bureau}}</ref>\n\n==History==\nThe [[United States]] took control of Puerto Rico from [[Spain]] in the aftermath of the [[Spanish-American War]] under the terms of the [[Treaty of Paris (1898)|Treaty of Paris of 1898]]. In 1899, the United States conducted its first census of Puerto Rico, finding that the combined population of Duey Alto and Rosario Pe\u00f1on barrios was 1,100.<ref name=\"OfficeSanger1900\">{{cite book|author1=Joseph Prentiss Sanger|author2=Henry Gannett|author3=Walter Francis Willcox|title=Informe sobre el censo de Puerto Rico, 1899, United States. War Dept. Porto Rico Census Office|url=https://archive.org/details/informesobreelc00joangoog|year=1900|publisher=Imprenta del gobierno|page=[https://archive.org/details/informesobreelc00joangoog/page/n255 164]| language=Spanish}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n{{Portal|Puerto Rico}}\n* [[List of communities in Puerto Rico]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n[[Category:Barrios of San Germ\u00e1n, Puerto Rico]]\n\n\n{{PuertoRico-geo-stub}}\n", "name_user": "The Eloquent Peasant", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eHistory:wikilink", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Duey_Alto,_San_Germ%C3%A1n,_Puerto_Rico"}
{"title_page": "Antiziganism", "text_new": "{{short description|racism against Romanis}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2014}}\n{{Discrimination sidebar}}\n{{Romani people}}\n'''Antiziganism''' (also '''antigypsyism''', '''anti-Romanyism''', '''Romaphobia''', or '''anti-Romani sentiment''') is hostility, [[prejudice]], discrimination or [[racism]] which is specifically directed at [[Romani people]] (Roma, [[Sinti]], [[Iberian Kale]], [[Kale (Welsh Roma)|Welsh Kale]], [[Finnish Kale]] and [[Romanichal]]). Non-Rom [[itinerant groups in Europe]] such as the [[Yenish people|Yenish]] and [[Irish Travellers|Irish]] and [[Scottish Gypsy and Traveller groups|Scottish Travellers]] are often given the misnomer \"gypsy\" and confused with the Romani people. As a result, sentiments which were originally directed at the Romani people are also directed at other traveler groups and they are often referred to as \"'''antigypsy'''\" sentiments.\n\nThe term ''Antigypsyism'' is recognized by the [[European Parliament]] and the [[European Commission]] as well as by a wide cross-section of civil society.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://antigypsyism.eu/wp-content/uploads/2017/07/Antigypsyism-reference-paper-16.06.2017.pdf|title=Antigypsyism: Reference Paper|last=|first=|date=|website=Antigypsyism.eu|access-date=24 January 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Etymology==\n{{see also|Names of the Romani people}}\nThe root ''Zigan'' comes from the term ''Cingane'' (alt. Tsinganoi, Zigar, Zigeuner) which probably derives from ''[[Athinganoi]]'', the name of a Christian sect which the Romani became associated with during the [[Middle Ages]].<ref name=\"White 1999\">{{cite journal|url=http://www.isidore-of-seville.com/goudenhoorn/72karin.html |title=Metal-workers, agriculturists, acrobats, military-people and fortune-tellers: Roma in and around the Byzantine empire |first=Karin |last=White |year=1999 |journal=Golden Horn |volume=7 |issue=2 |accessdate=2007-08-26 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20010320210002/http://www.isidore-of-seville.com/goudenhoorn/72karin.html |archivedate=20 March 2001 }}</ref><ref name=Starr>Starr, J. (1936). An Eastern Christian Sect: the Athinganoi. ''Dumbarton Oaks Papers, Trustees for Harvard University'', 29, 93-106.</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.sca.org/ti/articles/2002/issue144/rom.html |title=A Brief History of the Rom |first=Karina |last=Bates |accessdate=2007-08-26 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070810161445/http://www.sca.org/ti/articles/2002/issue144/rom.html |archivedate=10 August 2007 |url-status=live |df=dmy }}</ref><ref>{{cite journal|url=http://taylorandfrancis.metapress.com/index/9Y2PJM6YAYT1UVHW.pdf|title=Book Reviews|format=PDF|journal=Population Studies|volume=48|issue=2|date=July 1994|pages=365\u2013372|doi=10.1080/0032472031000147856}}</ref> According to Martin Holler, the English term ''anti-Gypsyism'' stems from the mid-1980s, and it became mainstream in the 2000s and 2010s, whereas the term ''antiziganism'' was more recently borrowed from the German ''Antiziganismus''.<ref>{{Cite book |last=Holler |first=Martin |date=2015 |title=Antiziganism: What's in a Word? |chapter=Historical Predecessors of the Term 'Anti-Gypsyism' |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=xl8HCgAAQBAJ&pg=PA82 |location= |publisher=Cambridge Scholars Publishing |page=82 |isbn=9781443878715 |accessdate=8 September 2016}}</ref>\n\n==History==\n{{main|History of the Romani people}}\n===In the Middle Ages===\n[[File:Enfant enlevee par des nomades.JPG|thumb|A French poster depicting a child being [[kidnapping|kidnapped]] by [[nomads]]]]\n{{See also|Slavery in Romania}}\n\nIn the early 13th-century [[Byzantine Empire|Byzantine]] records, the ''Ats\u00ednganoi'' are mentioned as \"wizards ... who are inspired satanically and pretend to predict the unknown\".<ref>George Soulis (1961): ''The Gypsies in the Byzantine Empire and the Balkans in the Late Middle Ages'' (Dumbarton Oaks Papers) Vol.15 pp.146\u2013147, cited in David Crowe (2004): ''A History of the Gypsies of Eastern Europe and Russia'' (Palgrave Macmillan) {{ISBN|0-312-08691-1}} p.1</ref>\n\nEnslavement of Roma, mostly taken as prisoners of war, in the [[Danubian Principalities]] is first documented in the late 15th century. In these countries extensive legislation was developed that classified Roma into different groups, according to their tasks as slaves.<ref name=\"Achim2004\">{{cite book|title=The Roma in Romanian History|last=Achim|first=Viorel|publisher=[[Central European University Press]]|place=Budapest|date=2004|isbn=9639241849}}</ref>\n\nBy the 16th century, many Romani who lived in [[Eastern Europe|Eastern]] and [[Central Europe]] worked as musicians, metal craftsmen, and soldiers.<ref>David Crowe (2004): ''A History of the Gypsies of Eastern Europe and Russia'' (Palgrave Macmillan) {{ISBN|0-312-08691-1}} p.XI</ref> As the [[Ottoman Empire]] expanded, it relegated the Romani, who were seen as having \"no visible permanent professional affiliation\", to the lowest rung of the social ladder.<ref>Crowe (2004) p.2</ref>\n\n===16th & 17th centuries===\nIn [[Royal Hungary]] in the 16th century at the time of the Turkish occupation, the Crown developed strong anti-Romani policies, as these people were considered suspect as Turkish spies or as a [[fifth column]]. In this atmosphere, they were expelled from many locations and increasingly adopted a nomadic way of life.<ref>Crowe (2004) p.1, p.34</ref>\n\nThe first anti-Romani legislation was issued in the [[March of Moravia]] in 1538, and three years later, [[Ferdinand I of Germany|Ferdinand I]] ordered that Romani in his realm be expelled after a series of fires in [[Prague]].\n\nIn 1545, the [[Diet of Augsburg]] declared that \"whosoever kills a Gypsy (Romani), will be guilty of no murder\".<ref>Crowe (2004) p.34</ref> The subsequent massive killing spree which took place across the empire later prompted the government to step in to \"forbid the drowning of Romani women and children\".<ref>Crowe (2004) p.35</ref>\n\nIn England, the [[Egyptians Act 1530]] banned Romani from entering the country and required those living in the country to leave within 16 days. Failure to do so could result in confiscation of property, imprisonment and deportation. The act was amended with the [[Egyptians Act 1530#Egyptians Act 1554|Egyptians Act 1554]], which directed that they abandon their \"naughty, idle and ungodly life and company\" and adopt a settled lifestyle. For those who failed to adhere to a sedentary existence, the [[Privy council]] interpreted the act to permit execution of non-complying Romani \"as a warning to others\".<ref>{{cite book|last= Mayall|first=David|title=English gypsies and state policies|publisher=Univ of Hertfordshire Press|year=1995|series=f Interface collection Volume 7 of New Saga Library|volume=7|pages=21, 24|isbn= 978-0-900458-64-4|url=https://books.google.com/?id=XVh8mB-7n7wC&pg=PA21|accessdate=28 February 2010}}</ref>\n\nIn 1660, the Romani were prohibited from residing in [[France]] by [[Louis XIV]].<ref name=\"romahistory.com\">{{cite web|url=http://www.romahistory.com/en/2-5-4.htm|title=The History of the Roma: 2.5.4: 1647 to 1714|publisher=Romahistory.com|first=Marko D.|last=Knudsen|accessdate=24 December 2014|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131017082735/http://www.romahistory.com/en/2-5-4.htm|archivedate=17 October 2013|df=dmy}}</ref>\n\n===18th century===\n\nIn 1710, [[Joseph I, Holy Roman Emperor|Joseph I]], Holy Roman Emperor, issued an edict against the Romani, ordering \"that all adult males were to be hanged without trial, whereas women and young males were to be flogged and banished forever.\" In addition, in the [[kingdom of Bohemia]], Romani men were to have their right ears cut off; in the [[March (territory)|March]] [[March of Moravia|of Moravia]], the left ear was to be cut off. In other parts of Austria, they would be branded on the back with a [[branding iron]], representing the [[gallows]]. These mutilations enabled authorities to identify the individuals as Romani on their second arrest. The edict encouraged local officials to hunt down Romani in their areas by levying a fine of 100 [[Reichsthaler]] on those who failed to do so. Anyone who helped Romani was to be punished by doing [[forced labor]] for half a year. The result was mass killings of Romani across the Holy Roman empire. In 1721, [[Charles VI, Holy Roman Emperor|Charles VI]] amended the decree to include the execution of adult female Romani, while children were \"to be put in hospitals for education\".<ref>Crowe (2004) p.36-37</ref>\n\nIn 1774, [[Maria Theresa]] of [[Habsburg Monarchy|Austria]] issued an edict forbidding marriages between Romani. When a Romani woman married a non-Romani, she had to produce proof of \"industrious household service and familiarity with [[Catholic]] tenets\", a male Rom \"had to prove his ability to support a wife and children\", and \"Gypsy children over the age of five were to be taken away and brought up in non-Romani families.\"<ref>Crowe (2004) p.75</ref>\n\nIn 2007 the [[Romania]]n government established a panel to study the 18th- and 19th-century period of [[Slavery in Romania|Romani slavery]] by Princes, local landowners, and [[monasteries]]. This officially legalized practice was first documented in the 15th century.<ref name=\"Achim2004\"/> Slavery of Romani was outlawed in the Romanian Principalities of [[Moldavia]] and [[Wallachia]] in around 1856.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nasdaq.com/aspxcontent/NewsStory.aspx?cpath=20070220%5cACQDJON200702201414DOWJONESDJONLINE000608.htm& |title=Company News Story |publisher=Nasdaq.com |accessdate=17 May 2012}}</ref>\n\n===19th century===\nGovernments regularly cited petty theft committed by Romani as justification for regulating and persecuting them. In 1899, the {{ill|Nachrichtendienst f\u00fcr die Sicherheitspolizei in Bezug auf Zigeuner|de}} ({{translation|i=yes}} ''Intelligence service for the security police concerning gypsies'') was set up in [[Munich]] under the direction of {{ill|Alfred Dillmann|de}}, and catalogued data on all Romani individuals throughout the German-speaking lands. It did not officially close down until 1970. The results were published in 1905 in Dillmann's ''Zigeuner-Buch'',<ref name=\"Dillmann 1905\">{{cite book|first=Alfred|last=Dillmann|title=Zigeuner-Buch|location=Munich|publisher=Wildsche|year=1905|language=German}}</ref> which was used in the following years as justification for the [[Porajmos]]. It described the Romani people as a \"plague\" and a \"menace\", but almost exclusively characterized \"Gypsy crime\" as trespassing and the theft of food.<ref name=\"Dillmann 1905\"/>\n\nIn the [[United States]] during Congressional debate in 1866 over the [[Fourteenth Amendment to the United States Constitution]] which would subsequently [[Jus soli|grant citizenship]] to all persons born within U.S. territory, an objection raised was that a consequence of enacting the amendment would be to grant citizenship to Gypsies and other groups perceived by some as undesirable.<ref><!-- \u2588 DO NOT \u2588 replace this citation text with a Wikipedia template, especially not \"cite web\": this is the actual citation format recommended by the Library of Congress, which is not reproduced by any Wikipedia template --> ''[[Congressional Globe]]'', 1st Session, [[39th United States Congress|39th Congress]], [http://memory.loc.gov/cgi-bin/ampage?collId=llcg&fileName=073/llcg073.db&recNum=12 p. 2891] (1866)</ref>\n\n[[Pennsylvania]] Senator [[Edgar Cowan]] stated, {{quote|...I am as liberal as anybody toward the rights of all people, but I am unwilling, on the part of my State, to give up the right that she claims, and that she may exercise, and exercise before very long, of expelling a certain number of people who invade her borders; who owe her no allegiance; who pretend to owe none; who recognize no authority in her government; who have a distinct, independent government of their own\u2014an ''[[State within a state|imperium in imperio]]''; who pay no taxes; who never perform military service; who do nothing, in fact, which becomes a citizen, and perform none of the duties which devolve upon him, but, on the other hand, have no homes, pretend to own no land, live nowhere, settle as trespassers where ever they go, and whose sole merit is a universal swindle; who delight in it, who boast of it, and whose adroitness and cunning is of such a transcendent character that no skill can serve to correct or punish it; I mean the Gypsies.  They wander in gangs in my State... These people live in the country and are born in the country.  They infest society.}}\n\nIn response Senator [[John Conness]] of [[California]] observed, {{quote|I have lived in the United States now many a year, and really I have heard more about Gypsies within the last two or three months than I have heard before in my life.  It cannot be because they have increased so much of late.  It cannot be because they have been felt to be particularly oppressive in this or that locality.  It must be that the Gypsy element is to be added to our political agitation, so that hereafter the negro alone shall not claim our entire attention.}}\n\n===Porajmos===\n[[File:Brown triangle svg.jpg|150px|thumb|The brown [[Nazi concentration camp badges|inverted triangle on their prison uniforms]] that the Romani prisoners in concentration camps such as [[Auschwitz concentration camp|Auschwitz]] were forced to wear to distinguish them from other inmates.<ref>{{cite web |title=Questions: Triangles |url=http://www.holocaust-history.org/questions/triangles.shtml |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080914095332/http://www.holocaust-history.org/questions/triangles.shtml |archivedate=2008-09-14 |date=2000-05-16 |website=The Holocaust History Project }}</ref>]]\n[[File:Bundesarchiv R 165 Bild-244-47, Asperg, Deportation von Sinti und Roma.jpg|thumb|right|250px|German Nazi deportation of Sinti and Roma from [[Asperg]], 1940]]\n{{Main|Romani genocide}}\nPersecution of Romani people reached a peak during [[World War II]] in the [[Romani genocide|Porajmos]] (literally, ''the devouring''), a descriptive neologism for the Nazi genocide of Romanis during [[the Holocaust]]. Because the Romani communities in Central and Eastern Europe were less organized than the [[Jew]]ish communities and the [[Einsatzgruppen]], mobile killing squads, who travelled from village to village massacring the Romani inhabitants where they lived typically left few to no records of the number of Roma killed in this way, although in a few cases, significant documentary evidence of mass murder was generated.<ref>{{cite book |last=Headland |first=Ronald |year=1992 |title=Messages of Murder: A Study of the Reports of the Einsatzgruppen of the Security Police and the Security Service, 1941\u20131943 |publisher=Fairleigh Dickinson Univ Press |page=63 |isbn= 978-0-8386-3418-9 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=Mue8a5Rwyi0C&pg=PA63&dq=einsatzgruppen+gypsy&cd=3#v=snippet&q=824&f=false |accessdate=17 February 2010 }}</ref> it is more difficult to assess the actual number of victims. Historians estimate that between 220,000 and 500,000 Romani were killed by the Germans and their collaborators\u201425% to over 50% of the slightly fewer than 1 million Roma in Europe at the time.<ref name=USHMM_2>{{cite web |title=Holocaust Encyclopedia \u2013 Genocide of European Roma (Gypsies), 1939\u20131945 |publisher=United States Holocaust Memorial Museum (USHMM) |url=http://www.ushmm.org/wlc/en/article.php?ModuleId=10005219 |accessdate=9 August 2011 }}</ref> A more thorough research by [[Ian Hancock]] revealed the death toll to be at about 1.5 million.<ref name=Milton_estimates>{{Citation |chapter=True Romanies and the Holocaust: A Re-evaluation and an overview |chapter-url=http://www.radoc.net/radoc.php?doc=art_e_holocaust_porrajmos&lang=en&articles= |author=Hancock, Ian |title=The Historiography of the Holocaust |isbn=978-1-4039-9927-6 |pages=383\u2013396 |year=2005 |publisher=[[Palgrave Macmillan]] }}{{dead link|date=March 2018 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref>\n\nNazi racial ideology put [[Romani people|Romani]], Jews, Slavs and blacks at the bottom of the racial scale.<ref name=\"Simone Gigliotti 2005. Pp. 14\">Simone Gigliotti, Berel Lang. ''The Holocaust: a reader''. Malden, Massachusetts, USA; Oxford, England, UK; Carlton, Victoria, Australia: Blackwell Publishing, 2005. Pp. 14.</ref> The German [[Nuremberg Laws]] of 1935 stripped Jews of citizenship, confiscated property and criminalized sexual relationship and marriage with Aryans. These laws were extended to Romani as Nazi policy towards Roma and Sinti was complicated by pseudo-historic racialist theories, which could be contradictory, namely that the Romani were of Egyptian ancestry. While they considered Romani grossly inferior, they believed the Roma people had some distant \"Aryan\" roots that had been corrupted. The Romani are actually a distinctly European people of considerable Northwestern Indian descent, or what is literally considered to be Aryan. Similarly to European Jews, specifically the Ashkenazi, the Romani people quickly acquired European genetics via enslavement and intermarriage upon their arrival in Europe 1,000 years ago.\n\nIn the [[Protectorate of Bohemia and Moravia]], the Nazi genocide of the Romani was so thorough that it exterminated the majority of [[Bohemian Romani]] speakers, eventually leading to the language's extinction in 1970 with the death of its last known speaker, Hana \u0160ebkov\u00e1. In Denmark, Greece and a small number of other countries, resistance by the native population thwarted planned Nazi deportations and extermination of the Romani. In most conquered countries (e.g., the Baltic states), local cooperation with the Nazis expediated the murder of almost all local Romani. In [[Independent State of Croatia|Croatia]], the Croatian collaborators of the [[Usta\u0161e]], were so vicious only a minor remnant of Croatian Romani (and Jews) survived the killings.\n\n[[File:Bundesarchiv Bild 146-1986-044-08, Stein-Pfalz, Eva Justin bei Sch\u00e4delmessung.jpg|thumb|[[Eva Justin]] checking the facial characteristics of a Romani woman as part of her \"racial studies\"]]\n\nIn 1982, [[West Germany]] formally recognized that genocide had been committed against the Romani.<ref>{{cite book |last=Barany |first=Zoltan D. |year=2002 |title=The East European gypsies: regime change, marginality, and ethnopolitics |publisher=Cambridge University Press |pages=265\u20136 |isbn=978-0-521-00910-2 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=yTylND961ZMC&q=Herzog#v=snippet&q=Herzog&f=false }}</ref> Before this they had often claimed that, unlike Jews, Roma and Sinti were not targeted for racial reasons, but for \"criminal\" reasons, invoking antiziganist stereotype. In modern Holocaust scholarship the Porajmos has been increasingly recognized as a genocide committed simultaneously with the Shoah.<ref>{{cite book |last=Duna |first=William A. |date=1985 |title=Gypsies: A Persecuted Race |publisher=Duna Studios }} Full text in  [http://chgs.umn.edu/histories/victims/romaSinti/gypsies.html Center for Holocaust and Genocide Studies], University of Minnesota.</ref>\n\n===Catholic Church takes responsibility===\nOn March 12, 2000, Pope [[John Paul II]] issued a formal public apology to, among other groups of people affected by Catholic persecution, the Romani people and begged God for forgiveness.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.latimes.com/archives/la-xpm-2000-mar-13-mn-8338-story.html|title=Pope Apologizes for Catholic Sins Past and Present|date=13 March 2000|via=LA Times}}</ref> On June 2, 2019, [[Pope Francis]] acknowledged during a meeting with members of the Romanian Romani community the Catholic Church's history of promoting \"discrimination, segregation and mistreatment\" against [[Romani people]] throughout the world, apologized, and asked the Romani people for forgiveness.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-europe-48490942|title=Pope apologises to Roma for Catholic discrimination|date=2 June 2019|via=www.bbc.com}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|author=Claire Giangrav\u00e8 |url=https://cruxnow.com/pope-in-romania/2019/06/02/pope-apologizes-to-gypsies-for-discrimination-and-segregation/ |title=Pope apologizes to gypsies for 'discrimination and segregation' |publisher=Cruxnow.com |date=2019-06-02 |accessdate=2019-07-01}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.channelnewsasia.com/news/world/pope-francis-asks-forgiveness-for-historical-mistreatment-of-11589638|title=Pope Francis asks forgiveness for historical mistreatment of Roma people|website=CNA}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://apnews.com/4bc86fcdd6f1426fb551ff9e954dbb57|title=Pope apologizes for history of discrimination against Roma|first1=Nicolae|last1=Dumitrache|first2=Nicole|last2=Winfield|date=2 June 2019|website=AP News}}</ref>\n\n==Contemporary anti-Romanyism==\nA report issued by [[Amnesty International]] in 2011 claims that \"systematic discrimination is taking place against up to 10 million Roma across Europe. The organization has documented the failures of governments across the continent to live up to their obligations.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.amnesty.org/en/documents/eur01/005/2011/en/|title=Amnesty International \u2013 International Roma Day 2011 Stories, Background Information and video material|date=7 April 2011|publisher=Amnesty International|accessdate=15 May 2011|location=AI Index: EUR 01/005/2011}}</ref>\n \nAnti-Romanyism has continued well into the 2000s, particularly in [[Slovakia]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://web.amnesty.org/wire/February2002/Europe_Roma |title=Amnesty International |publisher=Web.amnesty.org |accessdate=17 May 2012 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20071012191514/http://web.amnesty.org/wire/February2002/Europe_Roma |archivedate=12 October 2007 |df=dmy }}</ref> [[Hungary]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.csmonitor.com/2008/0213/p07s02-woeu.html|title=Hungary's anti-Roma militia grows|author=The Christian Science Monitor|work=The Christian Science Monitor}}</ref> [[Slovenia]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.humanrightspoint.si/node/12 |title=roma &#124; Human Rights Press Point |publisher=Humanrightspoint.si |accessdate=17 May 2012 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120310074602/http://www.humanrightspoint.si/node/12 |archivedate=10 March 2012 }}</ref> and [[Kosovo]].<ref>{{cite web|author=Gesellschaft fuer bedrohte Voelker \u2013 Society for Threatened Peoples |url=http://www.gfbv.de/inhaltsDok.php?id=612 |title=Roma and Ashkali in Kosovo: Persecuted, driven out, poisoned |publisher=Gfbv.de |accessdate=17 May 2012 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070806163105/http://www.gfbv.de/inhaltsDok.php?id=612 |archivedate=6 August 2007 |df=dmy }}</ref> In Bulgaria, Professor Ognian Saparev has written articles stating that 'Gypsies' are culturally inclined towards theft and use their [[ethnic minority|minority]] status to 'blackmail' the majority.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bghelsinki.org/en/news/bg/single/mp-publishes-inflammatory-article-against-the-roma/|title=MP publishes inflammatory article against the Roma|work=bghelsinki.org}}</ref> [[European Union]] officials censured both the Czech Republic and Slovakia in 2007 for forcibly segregating Romani children from regular schools.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.iht.com/articles/ap/2007/11/15/europe/EU-GEN-EU-Roma-Discrimination.php |title=IHT.com |publisher=IHT.com |date=29 March 2009 |accessdate=17 May 2012}}</ref>\n\nThe Council of Europe [[Commissioner for Human Rights]], [[Thomas Hammarberg]], has been an outspoken critic of anti-Romanyism. In August 2008, Hammarberg noted that \"today's rhetoric against the Roma is very similar to the one used by [[Nazis]] and fascists before the mass killings started in the thirties and forties. Once more, it is argued that the Roma are a threat to safety and public health. No distinction is made between a few criminals and the overwhelming majority of the Roma population. This is shameful and dangerous\".<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.coe.int/t/commissioner/Viewpoints/080818_en.asp |title=Viewpoints by Council of Europe Commissioner for Human Rights |publisher=Coe.int |accessdate=17 May 2012 |archive-url=https://archive.is/20120630002157/www.coe.int/t/commissioner/Viewpoints/080818_en.asp |archive-date=30 June 2012 |url-status=dead |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n\nAccording to the latest [[Human Rights First]] [[Hate Crime]] Survey, Romanis routinely suffer assaults in city streets and other public places as they travel to and from homes and markets. In a number of serious cases of violence against them, attackers have also sought out whole families in their homes or whole communities in settlements predominantly housing Romanis. The widespread patterns of violence are sometimes directed both at causing immediate harm to Romanis, without distinction between adults, the elderly, and small children and physically eradicating the presence of Romani people in towns and cities in several European countries.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.humanrightsfirst.org/discrimination/pages.aspx?id=85 |title=Human Rights First Report on Roma |publisher=Humanrightsfirst.org |accessdate=17 May 2012}}</ref>\n\n=== Public opinion ===\nThe extent of negative attitudes towards Romani people varies across different parts of Europe.\n{{bar box\n|title=Unfavorable views of Roma, 2019<ref>{{cite news |title=European Public Opinion Three Decades After the Fall of Communism \u2014 6. Minority groups |url=https://www.pewresearch.org/global/2019/10/14/minority-groups/ |work=Pew Research Center |date=14 October 2019}}</ref>\n|titlebar=#ddd\n|left1='''Country'''\n|right1='''Percent'''\n|width=400px\n|bars=\n{{bar percent|[[Romania]]|peru|94}}\n{{bar percent|[[Italy]]|peru|83}}\n{{bar percent|[[Slovakia]]|peru|76}}\n{{bar percent|[[Greece]]|peru|72}}\n{{bar percent|[[Bulgaria]]|peru|68}}\n{{bar percent|[[Czech Republic]]|peru|66}}\n{{bar percent|[[Lithuania]]|peru|61}}\n{{bar percent|[[Hungary]]|peru|61}}\n{{bar percent|[[Ukraine]]|peru|54}}\n{{bar percent|[[Russia]]|peru|52}}\n{{bar percent|[[Poland]]|peru|51}}\n{{bar percent|[[France]]|darkorange|44}}\n{{bar percent|[[Spain]]|darkorange|40}}\n{{bar percent|[[Germany]]|gold|37}}\n}}\n\n===European Union===\n[[File:Prejudice against Roma, Trans and Muslim people (EU, 2015).svg|thumb|upright=2|According to a survey conducted by the [[European Commission]] in 2015 20% of the respondents would be completely uncomfortable about working with a Roma person ({{legend-inline|#cab2d6|violet}}), compared with 17% with a [[transgender]] or [[transsexual]] person ({{legend-inline|#b2df8a|green}}) and 13% with a [[Muslim]] person ({{legend-inline|#fdbf6f|orange}}). This puts Roma people as the most discriminated minority in Europe.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Bona |first1=Marzia |title=How widespread is anti-Roma prejudice? |url=https://www.europeandatajournalism.eu/eng/News/Data-news/How-widespread-is-anti-Roma-prejudice |accessdate=29 August 2018 |work=OBC Transeuropa/EDJNet |date=2 August 2018}}</ref>]]\nThe practice of placing Romani students in segregated schools or classes remains widespread in countries across Europe.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.errc.org/cikk.php?cikk=2743|title=The Impact of Legislation and Policies on School Segregation of Romani Children |year=2007|publisher=European Roma Rights Centre|page=8|accessdate=21 July 2009| archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20090729181110/http://www.errc.org/cikk.php?cikk=2743| archivedate= 29 July 2009 | url-status= live}}</ref> Many Romani children have been channeled into all-Romani schools that offer inferior quality education and are sometimes in poor physical condition or into segregated all-Romani or predominantly Romani classes within mixed schools.<ref name=\"eumap\">{{cite web\n| year = 2007\n| format = PDF\n| url = http://www.eumap.org/topics/minority/reports/roma_education/report/vol1.pdf\n| archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070407092622/http://www.eumap.org/topics/minority/reports/roma_education/report/vol1.pdf\n| archivedate=7 April 2007\n| title = Equal access to quality education for Roma, Volume 1\n| pages = 18\u201320, 187, 212\u2013213, 358\u2013361\n| publisher = Open Society Institute \u2013 EU Monitoring and Advocacy Program (EUMAP)\n}}</ref> Many Romani children are sent to classes for pupils with learning disabilities. They are also sent to so-called \"delinquent schools\", with a variety of human rights abuses.<ref name=\"eumap\" />\n\nRomani in European cities are often accused of crimes such as [[pickpocketing]]. In 2009, a documentary by the [[BBC]] called ''Gypsy Child Thieves'' showed Romani children being kidnapped and abused by Romani gangs from Romania. The children were often held locked in sheds during the nights and sent to steal during the days.<ref name=\"BBC Gypsy Gangs\" /> However, ''[[Chachipe]]'', a charity which works for the human rights of Romani people, has claimed that this programme promoted \"popular stereotypes against Roma which contribute to their marginalisation and provide legitimacy to racist attacks against them\" and that in suggesting that [[begging]] and [[child exploitation]] was \"intrinsic to the Romany culture\", the programme was \"highly damaging\" for the Romani people. However, the charity accepted that some of the incidents that were detailed in the programme in fact took place.<ref name=IRR1>{{cite web|title=BBC documentary about Roma children sparks outrage|url=http://www.irr.org.uk/news/bbc-documentary-about-roma-children-sparks-outrage/|publisher=Institute for Race Relations|accessdate=2 May 2015|date=17 December 2009|author=Miranda Wilson}}</ref>\n\nThe documentary speculated that in [[Milan]], [[Italy]] a single Romani child was able to steal as much as \u20ac12,000 in a month; and that there were as many as 50 of such abused Romani children operating in the city. The film went on to describe the link between poverty, discrimination, crime and exploitation.<ref name=\"BBC Gypsy Gangs\">{{cite news| url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/8226580.stm | work=BBC News | first=Sam | last=Bagnall | title=How Gypsy gangs use child thieves | date=2 September 2009}}</ref>\n\nA United Nations study<ref>{{cite book|title=Avoiding the Dependence Trap: A Regional Human Development Report|url=http://roma.undp.sk/online.php|isbn=92-1-126153-8|publisher=United Nations Development Programme|date=December 2002|first=Andrey|last=Ivanov|chapter=7|chapterurl=http://roma.undp.sk/reports_contents.php?parent_id=1&id=229|access-date=29 December 2008|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20081205182000/http://roma.undp.sk/online.php|archive-date=5 December 2008|url-status=dead|df=dmy-all}}</ref> found that Romani people living in European countries are arrested for robbery much more often than other groups. [[Amnesty International]]<ref>{{cite web|title=Anti-Roma racism in Europe |first=Julie |last=Denesha |publisher=Amnesty International |url=http://web.amnesty.org/wire/February2002/Europe_Roma |date=February 2002 |accessdate=26 August 2007 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20071012191514/http://web.amnesty.org/wire/February2002/Europe_Roma |archivedate=12 October 2007 |df=dmy }}</ref> and Romani rights groups such as the ''Union Romani'' blame widespread [[institutionalised racism]] and persecution.<ref>{{cite web|title=Rromani People: Present Situation in Europe|url=http://www.unionromani.org/pueblo_in.htm#situacion|publisher=Union Romani|accessdate=26 August 2007| archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20070820014003/http://www.unionromani.org/pueblo_in.htm| archivedate= 20 August 2007 | url-status= live}}</ref> In July 2008, a [[Business Week]] feature found the region's Romani population to be a \"missed economic opportunity\".<ref>{{cite web|author=S. Adam Cardais |url=http://www.businessweek.com/globalbiz/content/jul2008/gb20080728_953451.htm?chan=globalbiz_europe+index+page_top+stories |title=Businessweek.com |publisher=Businessweek.com |date=28 July 2008 |accessdate=17 May 2012}}</ref> Hundreds of people from [[Ostravice]], in the [[Beskydy]] mountains in Czech Republic, signed a petition against a plan to move Romani families from [[Ostrava]] city to their home town, fearing the Romani invasion as well as their schools not being able to cope with the influx of Romani children.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://zpravy.aktualne.cz/village-rallies-against-roma-influx/r~i:article:619339/|title=Village rallies against Roma influx &#124; Aktu\u00e1ln\u011b.cz|date=15 October 2008|website=Aktu\u00e1ln\u011b.cz - V\u00edte, co se pr\u00e1v\u011b d\u011bje}}</ref>\n\nIn 2009, the UN's anti-racism panel charged that \"Gypsies suffer widespread racism in European Union\".<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2009/apr/23/eu-roma-racism-discrimination|title=Gypsies suffer widespread racism in European Union|date=23 April 2009|newspaper=Guardian |accessdate=26 August 2010 | location=London | first=Ian | last=Traynor| archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20100809025320/http://www.guardian.co.uk/world/2009/apr/23/eu-roma-racism-discrimination| archivedate= 9 August 2010 | url-status= live}}</ref> The EU has launched a program entitled [[Decade of Roma Inclusion]] to combat this and other problems.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.romadecade.org/|title=\u671f\u9593\u5de5\u30d0\u30a4\u30d6\u30eb\u3010\u30d0\u30a4\u30c8\u30fb\u8ee2\u8077\u6c42\u4eba\u691c\u7d22\u306e\u30b3\u30da\u30eb\u3011|website=Romadecade.org|accessdate=24 January 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20051126163332/http://www.romadecade.org/|archive-date=26 November 2005|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\n====Austria====\nOn 5 February 1995, [[Franz Fuchs]] killed four Romani in [[Oberwart]] with a [[pipe bomb]] [[improvised explosive device]] which was attached to a sign that read \"Roma zur\u00fcck nach Indien\" (\"Romani back to [[India]]\"). It was the worst racial terror attack in post-war Austria, and was Fuchs's first fatal attack.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1995/02/21/world/attack-on-austrian-gypsies-deepens-fear-of-neo-nazis.html|title=Attack on Austrian Gypsies Deepens Fear of Neo-Nazis|first=Alan|last=Cowell|date=21 February 1995|via=NYTimes.com}}</ref>\n\n====Bulgaria====\n[[File:Sap34.jpg|thumb|left|Antiziganist protests in [[Sofia]], 2011]]\n\nIn 2011 in Bulgaria, the widespread anti-Romanyism culminated in [[2011 Bulgaria antiziganist protests|anti-Roma protests]] in response to the murder of Angel Petrov on the orders of Kiril Rashkov, a Roma leader in the village of [[Katunitsa]]. In the subsequent trial, the killer, Simeon Yosifov, was sentenced to 17 years in jail.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/SB10001424052970204226204576599331889606992 |title=Anti-Roma Protests Escalate - WSJ.com |publisher=Online.wsj.com |date=29 September 2011 |accessdate=17 May 2012}}</ref> As of May 2012, an appeal was under way.\n\nProtests continued on 1 October in Sofia, with 2000 Bulgarians marching against the Romani and what they viewed to be the \"impunity and the corruption\" of the political elite in the country.<ref name=\"BBC10-1\">{{cite news|title=Bulgarian rally links Roma to organised crime|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-europe-15140291|work=[[BBC News]]|date=1 October 2011|accessdate=2 October 2011}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Boyko Borisov EPP 2014.jpg|thumb|Bulgarian prime minister [[Boyko Borissov|Borissov]] referred to Roma as \"bad human material\"<ref name=\"ndt1.com\">[http://www.ndt1.com/article.php/20090205212634848 \u0418\u0437\u043a\u0430\u0437\u0432\u0430\u043d\u0435 \u043d\u0430 \u0411\u043e\u0439\u043a\u043e \u0411\u043e\u0440\u0438\u0441\u043e\u0432 \u0432 \u0427\u0438\u043a\u0430\u0433\u043e&nbsp;\u2013 \u0435\u043c\u0438\u0433\u0440\u0430\u043d\u0442\u0441\u043a\u0430 \u0432\u0435\u0440\u0441\u0438\u044f] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110714162327/http://www.ndt1.com/article.php/20090205212634848 |date=14 July 2011 }} Chicago press conference transcription in Bulgarian</ref><ref name=\"Chicago audio record\">[http://www.segabg.com/data/BBorisovChicago.mp3 Chicago audio record] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110906034411/http://www.segabg.com/data/BBorisovChicago.mp3 |date=6 September 2011 }} ('''Dead Link''')</ref><ref name=\"telegraph.co.uk\">[https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/worldnews/europe/bulgaria/4531391/Mayor-of-Sofia-brands-Roma-Turks-and-retirees-bad-human-material.html Mayor of Sofia brands Roma, Turks and retirees 'bad human material'], Telegraph.co.uk, 6 February 2009</ref><ref name=\"novinite.com\">[http://www.novinite.com/view_news.php?id=100987 Sofia Mayor to Bulgarian Expats: We Are Left with Bad Human Material Back Home] Sofia Mayor to Bulgarian Expats: We Are Left with Bad Human Material Back Home</ref>]]\n[[Volen Siderov]], leader of the far-right [[National Union Attack|Ataka]] party and presidential candidate, spoke to a crowd at the Presidential Palace in Sofia, calling for the death penalty to be reinstated as well as Romani ghettos to be dismantled.<ref name=\"BBC10-1\"/>\n\nMany of the organized protests were accompanied by ethnic clashes and racist violence against Romani. The protesters shouted racist slogans like \"Gypsies into soap\" and \"Slaughter the Turks!\"<ref name=\"nytimes.com\">[https://www.nytimes.com/2011/09/28/world/europe/anti-roma-demonstrations-spread-across-bulgaria.html?_r=0 Anti-Roma Demonstrations Spread Across Bulgaria], The New York Times</ref> Many protesters were arrested for public order offenses.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.dnevnik.bg/bulgaria/2011/09/27/1163572_mvr_za_protestite_za_katunica_sred_nai-agresivnite/|title=\u0411\u044a\u043b\u0433\u0430\u0440\u0438\u044f - \u041c\u0412\u0420 \u0437\u0430 \u043f\u0440\u043e\u0442\u0435\u0441\u0442\u0438\u0442\u0435 \u0437\u0430 \u041a\u0430\u0442\u0443\u043d\u0438\u0446\u0430: \u0421\u0440\u0435\u0434 \u043d\u0430\u0439-\u0430\u0433\u0440\u0435\u0441\u0438\u0432\u043d\u0438\u0442\u0435 \u0431\u044f\u0445\u0430 12-13-\u0433\u043e\u0434\u0438\u0448\u043d\u0438 - Dnevnik.bg|work=www.dnevnik.bg}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.trud.bg/Article.asp?ArticleId=1055699|title=\u0422\u0440\u0443\u0434|website=\u0422\u0440\u0443\u0434|access-date=13 July 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131224111208/http://www.trud.bg/Article.asp?ArticleId=1055699|archive-date=24 December 2013|url-status=dead|df=dmy-all}}</ref> The news media labelled the protests as anti-Romani [[Pogroms]].<ref name=\"nytimes.com\"/>\n\nFurthermore, in 2009, Bulgarian prime minister [[Boyko Borissov|Borissov]] referred to Roma as \"bad human material\".<ref name=\"ndt1.com\"/><ref name=\"Chicago audio record\"/><ref name=\"telegraph.co.uk\"/><ref name=\"novinite.com\"/> The vice-president of the [[Party of European Socialists]], [[Jan Marinus Wiersma]] claimed that he \"has already crossed the invisible line between [[right-wing populism]] and extremism\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.socialistgroup.eu/gpes/public/detail.htm?id=116844&section=NER&category=NEWS |title=Challenge to EPP over leader's statement on bad human material |publisher=Socialistgroup.eu |date=6 February 2009 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120323050511/http://www.socialistgroup.eu/gpes/public/detail.htm?id=116844&section=NER&category=NEWS |archivedate=23 March 2012 }}</ref>\n\nIn 2019 pogroms against the Roma community in [[Gabrovo]] broke out after 3 young Romani have been caught stealing in a shop<ref>https://intellinews.com/bulgarian-pm-s-intervention-fails-to-stop-anti-roma-protests-in-gabrovo-159595/</ref>. The following wave of riots saw incidents of violence and arson of two houses where Roma people were living, leading to the majority of the towns Roma community fleeing over night leaving behind their homes to be lynched. Roma rights NGO said that gendarmerie were deployed near places where there were Roma houses, but the police had \u201cshown frustration, urging more Gabrovo Roma to spend the next few days with relatives in other municipalities\u201d. Many Roma have never returned as their homes were burned down and their property destroyed.<ref>https://sofiaglobe.com/2019/04/13/many-roma-have-fled-gabrovo-as-bulgarian-town-braces-for-another-no-to-aggression-protest/</ref>\n\n====Czech Republic====\n[[File:Z\u00e1kaz vstupu potuln\u00fdch cik\u00e1n\u016f a tul\u00e1k\u016f.jpg|thumb|Sign banning entry of itinerant Gypsies and rovers, 1920s]]\n{{Further|Romani people in the Czech Republic}}\nRoma make up 2\u20133% of population in the [[Czech Republic]]. According to \u0158\u00ed\u010dan (1998), Roma make up more than 60% of Czech prisoners and about 20\u201330% earn their livelihood in illegal ways, such as procuring prostitution, trafficking and other property crimes.<ref>{{cite book|last=\u0158\u00ed\u010dan|first=Pavel|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=qtgmAAAAMAAJ&q=pavel+%C5%99%C3%AD%C4%8Dan+s+romy+%C5%BE%C3%ADt+budeme&dq=pavel+%C5%99%C3%AD%C4%8Dan+s+romy+%C5%BE%C3%ADt+budeme&hl=cs&ei=9V52TcqJK5SI4Aac0tyCCA&sa=X&oi=book_result&ct=result&resnum=1&ved=0CCgQ6AEwAA|title=S Romy \u017e\u00edt budeme \u2013 jde o to jak: d\u011bjiny, sou\u010dasn\u00e1 situace, ko\u0159eny probl\u00e9m\u016f, nad\u011bje spole\u010dn\u00e9 budoucnosti|publisher=Port\u00e1l|year=1998|isbn=80-7178-250-5|location=Praha|pages=58\u201363}}</ref> Roma are thus more than 20 times overrepresented in Czech prisons than their population share would suggest.\n\nAccording to 2010 survey, 83% of Czechs consider Roma asocial and 45% of Czechs would like to expel them from the Czech Republic.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://zpravy.idnes.cz/cesi-propadaji-anticikanismu-kazdy-druhy-tu-romy-nechce-zjistil-pruzkum-1qx-/domaci.asp?c=A101209_161615_domaci_js|title=\u010ce\u0161i propadaj\u00ed anticik\u00e1nismu, ka\u017ed\u00fd druh\u00fd tu Romy nechce, zjistil pr\u016fzkum|author=Ji\u0159\u00ed \u0160\u0165astn\u00fd|date=8 February 2012|publisher=Zpravy.idnes.cz|accessdate=17 May 2012}}</ref> A 2011 poll, which followed after a number of brutal attacks by Romani perpetrators against majority population victims, revealed that 44% of Czechs are afraid of Roma people.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.tyden.cz/rubriky/domaci/romsky-bloger-nekteri-romove-se-chovaji-jako-blazni_216270.html|title=Romsky bloger nekteri romove se chovaji jako blazni|language=Czech|accessdate=1 November 2011}}</ref> The majority of the [[Czech people]] do not want to have Romanis as neighbours (almost 90%, more than any other group<ref>{{cite web|url=https://translate.google.com/translate?u=http%3A%2F%2Fwww.romea.cz%2Findex.php%3Fid%3Dservis%2Fz2005_0318&hl=cs&ie=UTF8&sl=cs&tl=en|title=Czech don't want Roma as neighbours|language=Czech|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120201133920/http://translate.google.com/translate?u=http%3A%2F%2Fwww.romea.cz%2Findex.php%3Fid%3Dservis%2Fz2005_0318&hl=cs&ie=UTF8&sl=cs&tl=en|archive-date=1 February 2012|accessdate=15 April 2007|df=dmy-all}}</ref>) seeing them as thieves and social parasites. In spite of long waiting time for a child adoption, Romani children from orphanages are almost never adopted by Czech couples.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.radio.cz/en/article/88089|title=What is keeping children in orphanages when so many people want to adopt? \u2013 07-02-2007 \u2013 Radio Prague|publisher=Radio.cz|accessdate=17 May 2012}}</ref> After the [[Velvet Revolution]] in 1989 the jobs traditionally employing Romanis either disappeared or were taken over by immigrant workers.\n\nThe Romanis are at the centre of the agenda of far-right groups in the Czech Republic, which spread anti-Romanyism. Among highly publicized cases was the [[V\u00edtkov arson attack of 2009]], in which four right-wing extremists seriously injured a three-year-old Romani girl. The public responded by donating money as well as presents to the family, who were able to buy a new house from the donations, while the perpetrators were sentenced to 18 and 22 years in prison.\n \nIn January 2010, Amnesty International launched a report titled ''Injustice Renamed: Discrimination in Education of Roma persists in the Czech Republic''.<ref>[https://www.amnesty.org/en/documents/eur71/003/2009/en/ ''Injustice Renamed: Discrimination in Education of Roma persists in the Czech Republic''] Amnesty International report, January 2010</ref> According to the [[BBC]], it was Amnesty's view that while cosmetic changes had been introduced by the authorities, little genuine improvement in addressing discrimination against Romani children has occurred over recent years.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/europe/8456882.stm|title=Amnesty says Czech schools still fail Roma Gypsies|date=13 January 2010|work=BBC News|accessdate=14 January 2010|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100114052029/http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/europe/8456882.stm|archivedate=14 January 2010}}</ref>\n\nThe 2019 [[Pew Research Center|Pew Research poll]] poll found that 66% of Czechs held unfavorable views of Roma.\n\n====Denmark====\nIn [[Denmark]], there was much controversy when the city of [[Helsing\u00f8r]] decided to put all Romani students in special classes in its [[Public school (government funded)|public school]]s. The classes were later abandoned after it was determined that they were discriminatory, and the Romanis were put back in regular classes.<ref>{{cite web\n| date = 18 January 2006\n| url = http://www.dr.dk/Regioner/Kbh/Nyheder/Politik/20060118073049.htm\n| title = Roma-politik igen i s\u00f8gelyset\n| publisher = DR Radio P4\n| language = Danish\n}}</ref>\n\n====France====\n{{Further|French Romani repatriation}}\nFrance has come under criticism for its treatment of Roma. In the summer of 2010, French authorities demolished at least 51 illegal Roma camps and began the process of repatriating their residents to their countries of origin.<ref>{{cite news | url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-europe-11020429|title=France sends Roma Gypsies back to Romania | date=20 August 2010 | publisher=BBC |accessdate=22 August 2010| archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20100821223510/http://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-europe-11020429| archivedate= 21 August 2010 | url-status= live}}</ref> The French government has been accused of perpetrating these actions to pursue its political agenda.<ref>{{cite news|title=France Begins Controversial Roma Deportations |date=19 August 2010 |url=http://www.spiegel.de/international/europe/0,1518,712701,00.html |work=Der Spiegel |accessdate=20 August 2010 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100820123925/http://www.spiegel.de/international/europe/0%2C1518%2C712701%2C00.html |archivedate=20 August 2010 |url-status=live }}</ref>  In July 2013, [[Jean-Marie Le Pen]], a very controversial far-right politician and founder of the [[National Front (France)|National Front]] party, had a lawsuit filed against him by the European Roma and Travellers Forum, SOS Racisme and the French Union of Travellers Association after he publicly called France's Roma population \"smelly\" and \"rash-inducing\", claiming his comments violated French law on inciting racial hatred.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.ibtimes.co.uk/roma-travellers-group-sue-far-right-leader-491937|title=Jean-Marie Le Pen Sued for Calling Roma Gypsies 'Smelly'|newspaper=International Business Times|author=Gianluca Mezzofiore|date=18 July 2013|accessdate=20 July 2014}}</ref>\n\n====Germany====\nAfter 2005 Germany deported some 50,000 people, mainly Romanis, to Kosovo. They were asylum seekers who fled the country during the [[Kosovo War]]. The people were deported after living more than 10 years in Germany. The deportations were highly controversial: many were children and obtained education in Germany, spoke German as their primary language and considered themselves to be Germans.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2005/05/19/international/europe/19kosovo.html|title=Germany Sending Gypsy Refugees Back to Kosovo|work=[[The New York Times]]|date=19 May 2005}}</ref>\n\n====Hungary====\nHungary has seen escalating violence against the Romani people. On 23 February 2009, a Romani man and his five-year-old son were shot dead in [[Tat\u00e1rszentgy\u00f6rgy]] village southeast of [[Budapest]] as they were fleeing their burning house which was set alight by a petrol bomb. The dead man's two other children suffered serious burns. Suspects were arrested and are currently on trial.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://index.hu/belfold/2011/03/25/egy_megdobbento_gyilkossagsorozat_reszletei/|title=Egy megd\u00f6bbent\u0151 gyilkoss\u00e1gsorozat r\u00e9szletei|date=25 March 2011|accessdate=25 March 2011|publisher=Index}}</ref>\n\nIn 2012, [[Vikt\u00f3ria Moh\u00e1csi]], 2004\u20132009 Hungarian [[Member of European Parliament]] of Romani ethnicity, asked for asylum in Canada after previously requesting police protection at home from serious threats she was receiving from hate groups.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.romea.cz/english/index.php?id=detail&detail=2007_3142|title=Hungarian Roma activist, former member of European Parliament emigrates to Canada|work=romea.cz}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.politics.hu/20130616/hungarian-mep-to-canada-asylum-seeker-a-romas-long-trek/|title=Hungarian MEP to Canada asylum seeker: A Roma\u2019s long trek|work=Politics.hu|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131230234856/http://www.politics.hu/20130616/hungarian-mep-to-canada-asylum-seeker-a-romas-long-trek/|archive-date=30 December 2013|access-date=28 December 2013}}</ref>\n\n====Italy====\n{{see also|Anti-Roma sentiment in Italy}}\nIn 2007 and 2008, following the brutal rape and subsequent murder of a woman in Rome at the hands of a young man from a local Romani encampment,<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2007/nov/02/italy.international |title=Italian woman's murder prompts expulsion threat to Romanians |newspaper=The Guardian |date=2 November 2007 | location=London | first=John | last=Hooper}}</ref> the Italian government started a crackdown on illegal Roma and Sinti campsites in the country.\n\nIn May 2008 Romani camps in Naples were attacked and set on fire by local residents.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/low/world/europe/7423165.stm |title=Italy condemned for 'racism wave'|first=Unknown|last=Unknown|date=28 May 2008|work=BBC News|publisher=BBC}}</ref> In July 2008, a high court in Italy overthrew the conviction of defendants who had publicly demanded the expulsion of Romanis from [[Verona]] in 2001 and reportedly ruled that \"it is acceptable to discriminate against Roma on the grounds that they are thieves\".<ref name=\"legalpredj\">[https://www.theguardian.com/world/2008/jul/01/italy Italy: Court inflames Roma discrimination row] ''[[The Guardian]]'' Retrieved 17 July 2008</ref> One of those freed was [[Flavio Tosi]], Verona's mayor and an official of the anti-immigrant [[Lega Nord]].<ref name=\"legalpredj\" /> The decision came during a \"nationwide clampdown\" on Romanis by Italian prime minister [[Silvio Berlusconi]]. The previous week, Berlusconi's interior minister [[Roberto Maroni]] had declared that all Romanis in Italy, including children, would be fingerprinted.<ref name=\"legalpredj\" />\n\nIn 2011 the development of a National Inclusion Strategy Rom Dei Sinti and Caminanti <ref>{{cite web|url=http://ec.europa.eu/justice/discrimination/files/roma_italy_strategy_it.pdf|format=PDF|title=Strategia Nazionale D'Inclusione Dei Rom, Dei Sinti e Dei Caminanti Attuazione Comunicazione Commissione Europea N.173/2011|website=Ec.europa.eu|accessdate=24 January 2018}}</ref> under the supervision of European Commission has defined the presence of Romani camps as an unacceptable condition.\nAs already underlined by many international organizations, the prevalent positioning of the RSC communities in the c.d \"nomad camps\" fuels segregation and hinders every process of social integration / inclusion; but even where other more stable housing modalities have been found, forms of ghettoization and self-segregation are found, which hinder the process of integration / social inclusion.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://ec.europa.eu/justice/discrimination/files/roma_italy_strategy_it.pdf|page=15|format=PDF|title=Strategia Nazionale D'Inclusione Dei Rom, Dei Sinti e Dei Caminanti Attuazione Comunicazione Commissione Europea N.173/2011|website=Ec.europa.eu|accessdate=24 January 2018}}</ref>\n\n====Romania====\n{{Further|Romani people in Romania|Slavery in Romania}}\nRoma make up 3.3% of population in [[Romania]]. Prejudice against Romanis is common amongst the Romanians, who characterize them as thieves, dirty and lazy.<ref name=\"enar\">Delia-Luiza Nit\u0103, [http://cms.horus.be/files/99935/MediaArchive/national/Romania%20-%20SR%202008.pdf ENAR Shadow Report 2008: Racism in Romania], [[European Network Against Racism]]</ref> A 2000 EU report about Romani said that ''in Romania... the continued high levels of discrimination are a serious concern...and progress has been limited to programmes aimed at improving access to education''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://ec.europa.eu/employment_social/fundamental_rights/pdf/pubst/roma04_en.pdf |title=The Situation of Roma in an Enlarged European Union |publisher=European Commission |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090305133536/http://ec.europa.eu/employment_social/fundamental_rights/pdf/pubst/roma04_en.pdf |archivedate=5 March 2009 |df=dmy }}</ref> A survey of the Pro Democra\u0163ia association in Romania revealed that 94% of the questioned persons believe that the [[Romanian nationality law|Romanian citizenship]] should be revoked to the ethnic Romani who commit crimes abroad.<ref>[http://www.evz.ro/detalii/stiri/romii-vor-fapte-nu-vorbe-891619.html Evenimentul Zilei. 7 April 2010]. Evz.ro. Retrieved on 2012-01-15.</ref>\n\nIn 2009-2010, a media campaign followed by a parliamentarian initiative asked the Romanian Parliament to accept a proposal to change back the official name of country's Roma (adopted in 2000) to ''\u021aigan'', the traditional and colloquial [[Romanian language|Romanian]] name for Romani, in order to avoid the possible confusion among the international community between the words Roma, which refers to the Romani ethnic minority, and Romania.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://jurnalul.ro/campaniile-jurnalul/tigan-in-loc-de-rom/propunere-jurnalul-national-tigan-in-loc-de-rom-145427.html|title=Propunere Jurnalul Na\u0163ional:|website=Jurnalul.ro|accessdate=24 January 2018}}</ref> The Romanian government supported the move on the grounds that many countries in the European Union use a [[names of the Romani people|variation of the word ''\u021aigan'']] to refer to their Gypsy populations. The Romanian upper house, the Senate, rejected the proposal.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://content.time.com/time/world/article/0,8599,2035862,00.html|title=Romania's Government Moves to Rename the Roma|first=Rupert Wolfe|last=Murray|date=8 December 2010|website=Content.time.com|accessdate=24 January 2018|via=content.time.com}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.balkaninsight.com/en/article/disputes-over-proper-word-for-romania-s-minority|title=Romania Declines to Turn Roma Into 'Gypsies'|website=Balkaninsight.com|accessdate=24 January 2018}}</ref>\n\nSeveral anti-Romani [[riot]]s occurred in recent decades, notable of which being the [[H\u0103d\u0103reni riots]] of 1993, in which a mob of Romanians and Hungarians, in response to the killing of a Romanian by a Gypsy, burnt down 13 houses belonging to the Gypsies, lynched three Gypsies and forced 130 people to flee the village.<ref name=\"hadareni\">[https://query.nytimes.com/gst/fullpage.html?res=9F0CE6D8133AF934A15753C1A965958260&sec=&spon=&pagewanted=all \"Hadareni Journal; Death Is a Neighbor, and the Gypsies Are Terrified\"], in ''[[The New York Times]]'', 27 October 1993</ref>\n\nIn [[Baia Mare]], Mayor [[C\u0103t\u0103lin Chereche\u0219]] announced the building of a 3 metre high, 100 metre long concrete wall to divide the buildings in which the Gypsy community lives from the rest of the city and bring \"order and discipline\" into the area.<ref>[http://www.setimes.com/cocoon/setimes/xhtml/en_GB/features/setimes/features/2011/07/18/feature-04 \"Roma community segregation still plaguing Romania\"], ''Setimes'', 18 July 2011</ref>\n\nThe [[manele]], their modern music style, was prohibited in some cities of Romania in public transport<ref>{{cite web|title=Prim\u0103ria de decis: Manelele lui Gu\u0163\u0103 \u015fi Salam sunt interzise la Gala\u0163i|url=http://www.adevarul.ro/locale/galati/Manelele_lui_Guta_si_Salam-interzise_la_Galati_0_216578447.html|work=Stiri din Galati|publisher=Adev\u0103rul Holding|accessdate=29 July 2012|author=Corina Mis\u0103il\u0103, Vali Trufa\u015fu|date=28 February 2010}}</ref> and taxis,<ref>{{cite web|title=Interzis la manele \u00een taxi!|url=http://www.libertatea.ro/detalii/articol/interzis-la-manele-in-taxi-282232.html|work=Liber Tatea|publisher=Ringier Romania Toate|accessdate=29 July 2012|language=Romanian|date=31 March 2010}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Fumatul \u015fi manelele, interzise \u00een taxiurile bra\u015fovene|url=http://www.adevarul.ro/life/Fumatul-manelele-interzise-taxiurile-brasovene_0_42595952.html|work=Adev\u0103rul.ro|publisher=Adev\u0103rul Holding|accessdate=29 July 2012|author=Sebastian Dan|language=Romanian|date=14 March 2007}}</ref> that action being justified by bus and taxi companies as being for passengers' comfort and a neutral ambience, acceptable for all passengers. However, those actions had been characterised by Speranta Radulescu, a professor of ethno-musicology at the [[Bucharest Conservatory]], as \"a defect of Romanian society\".<ref>{{cite news|title=\"Manele\", the Most Contested Music of Today|url=http://www.rri.ro/art.shtml?lang=1&sec=27&art=217582|accessdate=23 June 2012|newspaper=Radio Romania International|date=6 February 2012|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120624063402/http://www.rri.ro/art.shtml?lang=1&sec=27&art=217582|archive-date=24 June 2012|url-status=dead}}</ref> There were also a few criticisms of Professor Dr. Ioan Bradu Iamandescu's experimental study, which linked the listening of \"manele\" to an increased level of aggressiveness and low self-control and suggested a correlation between preference for that music style and low cognitive skills.<ref>{{cite web|title=Prof. dr. Ioan Bradu Iamandescu: \"Pe muzic\u0103 baroc\u0103, neuronii cap\u0103t\u0103 un ritm specific geniilor\"|url=http://www.adevarul.ro/life/sanatate/Prof-_dr-_Ioan_Bradu_Iamandescu-_-Pe_muzica_baroca-neuronii_capata_un_ritm_specific_geniilor_0_551345213.html|work=Adev\u0103rul.ro|publisher=Adev\u0103rul Holding|accessdate=29 July 2012|author=Mariana Minea|language=Romanian|date=10 September 2011}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Cum se comporta creierul cand asculta manele|url=http://stirileprotv.ro/stiri/social/cum-se-comporta-creierul-cand-asculta-manele.html|work=Stirileprotv.ro|publisher=Stirileprotv.ro|accessdate=29 July 2012|language=Romanian}}</ref>\n\nIn 2009, pop singer [[Madonna (entertainer)|Madonna]] defended Romani people during her [[concert]] in Bucharest.<ref>[http://www.mtv.com/news/1619705/madonna-booed-after-standing-up-for-gypsies-in-romania/ Madonna Booed After Standing Up For Gypsies in Romania]</ref>\n\n====Sweden====\nRoma are one of the five official national minorities in Sweden.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://sweden.se/society/national-minorities-in-sweden/|title=National Minorities in Sweden|publisher=Swedish Institute|website=sweden.se|accessdate=8 April 2020}}</ref>\n\nIn a survey commissioned by the [[Equality Ombudsman]] in 2002/2003, Roma described the discrimination they experience in their daily lives. 90 percent stated that they perceive Sweden to a certain or high degree as a racist country. The same amount agreed to a certain or high degree to the statement that the country has a attitude view towards Roma. 25 percent did neither feel as a part of the Swedish population nor accepted in the Swedish society. And 60 percent said that they have been called derogatory or discriminatory terms related to their ethnic background at least once in the last two years.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.do.se/globalassets/publikationer/rapport-diskriminering-romer-sverige.pdf|date=2004|title=Diskriminering av Romer i Sverige. Rapport fr\u00e5n DO:s projekt \u00e5ren 2002 och 2003 om \u00e5tg\u00e4rder f\u00f6r att f\u00f6rebygga och motverka etnisk diskriminering av Romer|publisher=Ombudsmannen mot etnisk diskriminering|website=do.se|accessdate=8 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n====Slovakia====\n{{Further|Romani people in Slovakia}}\n\nAccording to the last census from 2011, Roma make up 2.0% of the population in [[Slovakia]].\n\nThree Slovakian Romani women have come before the [[European Court of Human Rights]] on grounds of having been forcefully sterilised in Slovakian hospitals. The sterilisations were performed by [[tubal ligation]] after the women gave birth by Caesarean section. The court awarded two of the women costs and damages while the third case was dismissed because of the woman's death.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.hrlc.org.au/forced-sterilisation-of-roma-women-is-inhuman-and-degrading-but-not-discriminatory|title=Forced sterilisation of Roma women is inhuman and degrading but not discriminatory|last=Kinsella|first=Naomi|website=Hrlc.org.au|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://archive.is/20130405150900/http://www.hrlc.org.au/forced-sterilisation-of-roma-women-is-inhuman-and-degrading-but-not-discriminatory|archive-date=5 April 2013|accessdate=10 February 2013}}</ref> A report by the [[Center for Reproductive Rights]] and the Centre for Civil and Human Rights has compiled more than 100 cases of Roma women in Slovakia who have been sterilised without their [[informed consent]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://reproductiverights.org/en/document/body-and-soul-forced-sterilization-and-other-assaults-on-roma-reproductive-freedom|title=Body and Soul: Forced Sterilization and Other Assaults on Roma Reproductive Freedom|publisher=Center for Reproductive Rights|accessdate=11 February 2013}}</ref>\n\nRoma people suffer serious discrimination in Slovakia. Roma children are segregated in school and do not receive the level of education as other Slovakian children. Some are sent to schools for children with mild mental disabilities. As a result, their attainment level is far below average. Amnesty International\u2019s report \"Unfulfilled promises: Failing to end segregation of Roma pupils in Slovakia\" describes the failure of the Slovak authorities to end the discrimination of Roma children on the grounds of their ethnicity in education. According to a 2012 United Nations Development Programme survey, around 43 per cent of Roma in mainstream schools attended ethnically segregated classes.\n\nRoma people are the victims of ethnically driven violence and crime in Slovakia. According to monitoring and reports provided by the European Roma Rights Center (ERRC), racist violence, evictions, threats, and more subtle forms of discrimination have increased over the past years in Slovakia. Although today the situation is a little better as of now (2020), the ERRC considers the situation in Slovakia to be one of the worst in Europe. The 2019 [[Pew Research Center|Pew Research]] poll found that 76% of Slovaks held unfavorable views of Roma.\n\nRomani people receive new housing from municipalities and regional administrations for free every year, however people complain that some of them end up being destroyed by Romani people themselves. After the destruction, in some cases it has happened that the residents receive new housing, without being criminally prosecuted for destroying state property.{{Citation needed|date=March 2020|reason=This claim needs a reliable source; Claims follow typical antiziganism stereotypes without evidence or research. Sus.}}\n====United Kingdom====\nAccording to the LGBT rights organisation and charity [[Stonewall (charity)|''Stonewall'']], anti-Romanyism is prevalent in the UK, with a distinction made between Romani people and [[Irish Travellers]] (both of whom are commonly known by the [[exonym]] \"[[Gypsy (term)|gypsies]]\" in the UK), and the so-called \"travellers [and] modern Gypsies\".<ref>{{cite book|author1=[[Gill Valentine]]|author2=Ian McDonald|title=Understanding Prejudice: Attitudes towards minorities|publisher=[[Stonewall (charity)|Stonewall]]|page=14|url=http://www.stonewall.org.uk/documents/pdf_cover__content.pdf|accessdate=10 January 2015|format=PDF|quote=\"They were also criticised in cultural terms for not belonging to a community and allegedly having a negative impact on the environment: for example, they are unsightly, dirty or unhygienic. A clear distinction was also made between Romany Gypsies, respected for their history and culture, and travellers or modern Gypsies.\"}}</ref> In 2008, the media reported that Gypsies experience a higher degree of racism than any other group in the UK, including asylum-seekers. A Mori poll indicated that a third of UK residents admitted openly to being prejudiced against Gypsies.<ref name=\"shields1\">{{cite news| url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/home-news/no-blacks-no-dogsno-gypsies-860873.html | location=London | work=The Independent | first=Rachel | last=Shields | title=No blacks, no dogs, no Gypsies | date=6 July 2008}}</ref>\n\nThousands of retrospective planning permissions are granted in Britain in cases involving non-Romani applicants each year, and that statistics showed that 90% of planning applications by Romanis and travellers were initially refused by [[Local government in the United Kingdom|local councils]] compared with a national average of 20% for other applicants, disproving claims of preferential treatment favouring Romanis.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cre.gov.uk/gdpract/g_and_t_facts.html |title=Gypsies and Irish Travellers: The facts |publisher=Commission for Racial Equality|url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20071011112335/http://cre.gov.uk/gdpract/g_and_t_facts.html |archivedate=11 October 2007 |df=dmy }}</ref>\nTravellers argued that the root of the problem was that many traditional stopping places had been barricaded off and that legislation passed by the previous Conservative government had effectively criminalised their community. For example, removing local authorities' responsibility to provide sites leaves the travellers with no option but to purchase unregistered new sites themselves.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/insideout/southeast/series8/week_three.shtml|work=[[Inside Out (2002 TV programme)|Inside Out]] \u2013 South East|date=19 September 2005|title=Gypsies|publisher=BBC}}</ref>\n\nIn August 2012, Slovakian television network [[TV JOJ]] ran a report about cases of Romani immigrant families with Slovakian or Czech citizenship, whose children were forcibly taken away by the British authorities. It has sparked Romani protests in towns such as [[Nottingham]]. The authorities refused to explain the reasons for their actions to the Slovak reporters. One of the mothers alleged that she was allowed visitation with her newborn baby only in an empty room; as there was no furniture, she was forced to change her baby's dirty nappies on the floor, which was reflected negatively in a social workers' report. Then, when she would not change the diapers on a subsequent occasion following this experience, failure to change them was reflected negatively in the report as well. TV JOJ also alleged that in another case, a biological mother suffered a nervous breakdown because her children were being taken away, which was seen as proof that she was not able to take care for them and they were then put up for adoption.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.novinky.cz/zahranicni/evropa/276852-britske-urady-udajne-bez-priciny-odebiraji-deti-ceskym-a-slovenskym-romum.html|work=novinky.cz|date=23 August 2005|title=Britsk\u00e9 \u00fa\u0159ady \u00fadajn\u011b bez p\u0159\u00ed\u010diny odeb\u00edraj\u00ed d\u011bti \u010desk\u00fdm a slovensk\u00fdm Rom\u016fm [British authorities allegedly take away children from Czech and Slovak Romanis without any reason]|publisher=novinky.cz|language=Czech}}</ref> The problem was further escalated after reports that some Slovak children would be put up for adoption either in the UK or elsewhere, especially after a British court rejected the request of a grandmother, living in Slovakia, for legal custody of her grandchildren.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://blogs.wsj.com/emergingeurope/2012/09/19/slovak-government-challenges-u-k-foster-care-ruling/|work=Wall Street Journal|date=19 September 2012|title=Slovak Government Challenges U.K. Foster-Care Ruling|publisher=Wall Street Journal}}</ref> This dispute has sparked protests in front of the British embassy in Bratislava, with protesters holding signs such as \"Britain \u2013 Thief of Children\" and \"Stop Legal Kidnappers\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.teraz.sk/fotodennik/protest-pred-britskou-ambasadou-v-brati/24557-fotografia.html#/fotodennik/fotografia/24557|work=teraz.sk|date=18 September 2012|title=Protest pred britskou ambas\u00e1dou v Bratislave|publisher=teraz.sk|language=Slovak}}</ref> According to Slovak media, over 30 Romani children were taken from their parents in Britain. The Slovak government voiced its \"serious concern\" over the readiness of British authorities to remove children from their \"biological parents\" for \"no sound reason\" and further stated its readiness to challenge the policy in front of the [[European Court of Human Rights]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/comment/9545361/Foreign-government-may-take-UK-to-European-court-over-its-illegal-child-snatching.html|work=Daily Telegraph|date=15 September 2012|title=Foreign government may take UK to European court over its 'illegal' child-snatching|publisher=Daily Telegraph|location=London|first=Christopher|last=Booker}}</ref>\n\n=====England=====\nIn 2002 [[Conservative Party (UK)|Conservative Party]] politician, and Member of Parliament (MP) for [[Bracknell (UK Parliament constituency)|Bracknell]] [[Andrew MacKay]] stated in a [[House of Commons of the United Kingdom|House of Commons]] debate on unauthorised encampments of Gypsies and other Travelling groups in the UK, \"They [Gypsies and Travellers] are scum, and I use the word advisedly. People who do what these people have done do not deserve the same human rights as my decent constituents going about their ordinary lives\".<ref>The Gypsy Debate: Can Discourse Control? Joanna Richardson 2006 Imprint academic ch 1 p1.</ref><ref>{{cite book|last=Craig|first=Gary|title=Understanding 'Race' and Ethnicity: Theory, History, Policy, Practice|year=2012|publisher=The Policy Press|isbn=9781847427700|page=153|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=0XTCfyKHqC0C&pg=PA153 |author2=Karl Atkin |author3=Ronny Flynn |author4=Sangeeta Chattoo}}</ref> MacKay subsequently left politics in 2010.<ref>{{cite web|title=Andrew MacKay Former Conservative MP for Bracknell|url=https://www.theyworkforyou.com/mp/andrew_mackay/bracknell|work=[[They Work For You]]|publisher=[[mySociety]]|accessdate=29 July 2012}}</ref>\n\nIn 2005, [[Doncaster Borough Council]] discussed in chamber a Review of Gypsy and Traveller Needs<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.doncaster.gov.uk/db/chamber/default.asp?Nav=Report&ReportID=6091 |title=introduction 2.22 |publisher=Doncaster.gov.uk |date=1 December 2006 |accessdate=17 May 2012 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120901022623/http://www.doncaster.gov.uk/db/chamber/default.asp?Nav=Report&ReportID=6091 |archive-date=1 September 2012 |url-status=dead }}</ref> and concluded that Gypsies and Irish Travellers are among the most vulnerable and marginalised ethnic minority groups in Britain.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.doncaster.gov.uk/db/chamber/default.asp?Nav=Report&ReportID=6091 |title=The Council Chamber |publisher=Doncaster.gov.uk |date=1 December 2006 |accessdate=17 May 2012 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120901022623/http://www.doncaster.gov.uk/db/chamber/default.asp?Nav=Report&ReportID=6091 |archive-date=1 September 2012 |url-status=dead }}</ref><ref>Gypsies and Travellers: A strategy for the CRE, 2004 \u2013 2007</ref>\n\nA Gypsy and Traveller support centre in [[Leeds]], [[West Yorkshire]], was vandalised in April 2011 in what the police suspect was a [[hate-crime]]. The fire caused substantial damage to a centre that is used as a base for the support and education of gypsies and travellers in the community.<ref>{{cite web|last=Bellamy |first=Alison |url=http://www.yorkshireeveningpost.co.uk/news/latest-news/central-leeds/month_closure_for_leeds_traveller_arson_attack_centre_1_3320995 |title=Month closure for Leeds traveller arson attack centre |work=[[Yorkshire Evening Post]] |date=25 April 2011 |accessdate=17 May 2012}}</ref>\n\n=====Scotland=====\nThe Equal Opportunities Committee of the [[Scottish Parliament]] in 2001<ref>{{cite journal|last=Clark|first=Colin|title=Defining Ethnicity in a Cultural and Socio-Legal Context: The Case of Scottish Gypsy-Travellers|journal=[[Scottish Affairs]] Scotland's Longest Running Journal on Contemporary Political and Social Issues|date=Winter 2006|issue=54|pages=39\u201367|url=http://www.scottishaffairs.org/onlinepub/sa/clark_sa54_winter06.html|accessdate=26 December 2012|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131113070454/http://www.scottishaffairs.org/onlinepub/sa/clark_sa54_winter06.html|archive-date=13 November 2013|url-status=dead}}</ref> and in 2009<ref>{{cite web|title=Ethnic Status|url=http://www.scotland.gov.uk/Topics/People/Equality/gypsiestravellers/ethnic|work=The Scottish Government|publisher=The Scottish Government|accessdate=26 December 2012|date=22 January 2010}}</ref> confirmed that widespread marginalisation and discrimination persists in Scottish society against gypsy and traveller groups. A 2009 survey conducted by the Scottish Government also concludes that Scottish gypsy and travellers had been largely ignored in official policies. A similar survey in 2006 found discriminatory attitudes in Scotland towards gypsies and travellers,<ref name=\"scotland.gov.uk\">{{cite web|title=Attitudes to Discrimination in Scotland 2006: Scottish Social Attitudes Survey \u2013 Research Findings|url=http://www.scotland.gov.uk/Publications/2007/12/04093547/1|work=The Scottish Government|publisher=The Scottish Government|accessdate=26 December 2012|author=Scottish Government Social Research|date=4 December 2007}}</ref> and showed 37 percent of those questioned would be unhappy if a relative married a gypsy or traveller while 48 percent found it unacceptable if a member of the gypsy or traveller minorities became primary school teachers.<ref name=\"scotland.gov.uk\"/>\n\nA report by the [[University of the West of Scotland]] found that both Scottish and UK governments had failed to safeguard the rights of the Roma as a recognized ethnic group and did not raise awareness of Roma rights within the UK.<ref>{{cite web|title=Report on the Situation of the Roma Community in Govanhill, Glasgow|url=http://www.bemis.org.uk/resources/gt/scotland/report%20on%20the%20situation%20of%20the%20roma%20community%20in%20govanhill,%20Glasgow.pdf|work=Report on the Situation of the Roma Community in Govanhill, Glasgow|publisher=University of the West of Scotland|accessdate=26 December 2012|author=Lynne Poole|author2=Kevin Adamson|format=PDF|year=2008}}</ref> Additionally, an Amnesty International report published in 2012 stated that Gypsy Traveller groups in Scotland routinely suffer widespread discrimination in society,<ref name=\"amnesty.org.uk\">{{cite web|title=Caught in the Headlines \u2013 Scottish Media Coverage of Scottish Gypsy Travellers|url=http://amnesty.org.uk/uploads/documents/doc_22449.pdf|work=Caught in the Headlines \u2013 Scottish Media Coverage of Scottish Gypsy Travellers|publisher=Amnesty International in Scotland|accessdate=26 December 2012|author=Amnesty International in Scotland|author2=Napier University MSc Journalism|format=PDF|date=2 April 2012}}</ref> as well as a disproportionate level of scrutiny in the media.<ref>{{cite web|title=Gypsies/Travellers in Scotland: The Twice Yearly Count \u2013 No. 16: July 2009|url=http://www.scotland.gov.uk/Publications/2010/08/18105029/9|work=The Scottish Government|publisher=The Scottish Government|accessdate=26 December 2012|format=PDF|date=30 August 2010}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Gypsy/Traveller Numbers in the UK \u2013 A General Overview|url=http://www.article12.org/pdf/GYPSY%20TRAVELLER%20NUMBERS%20IN%20THE%20UK.pdf|work=Article12.org|publisher=YGTL \u2013 Article 12 in Scotland|accessdate=26 December 2012|author=Beth Cadger|year=2009|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131217221614/http://www.article12.org/pdf/GYPSY%20TRAVELLER%20NUMBERS%20IN%20THE%20UK.pdf|archive-date=17 December 2013|url-status=dead}}</ref> Over a four-month period as a sample 48 per cent of articles showed Gypsy Travellers in a negative light, while 25\u201328 per cent of articles were favourable, or of a neutral viewpoint.<ref name=\"amnesty.org.uk\"/> Amnesty recommended journalists adhere to ethical codes of conduct when reporting on Gypsy Traveller populations in Scotland, as they face fundamental human rights concerns, particularly with regard to health, education, housing, family life and culture.<ref name=\"amnesty.org.uk\"/>\n\nTo tackle the widespread prejudices and needs of Gypsy/Traveller minorities, in 2011, the Scottish Government set up a working party to consider how best to improve community relations between Gypsies/Travellers and Scottish society.<ref>{{cite web|title=Working Party Strategy|url=http://www.scotland.gov.uk/Topics/Built-Environment/Housing/16342/management/gt/wpstrategy|publisher=The Scottish Government|accessdate=26 December 2012|date=22 March 2011}}</ref> Including young Gypsies/Travellers to engage in an on-line positive messages campaign, contain factually correct information on their communities.<ref>{{cite web|title=Finance and Sustainable Growth|url=http://www.scottish.parliament.uk/S4_ChamberDesk/WA20110727.pdf|work=Scottish Parliament \u2013 Scottish Executive|publisher=Scottish Parliament|accessdate=26 December 2012|format=PDF|date=27 July 2011}}</ref>\n\n=====Wales=====\nIn 2007 a study by the newly formed [[Equality and Human Rights Commission]] found that negative attitudes and prejudice persists against Gypsy/Traveller communities in Wales.<ref name=\"equalityhumanrights.com\">{{cite web|title=Who Do You See? \u2013 Living together in Wales|url=http://www.equalityhumanrights.com/uploaded_files/download_who_do_you_see_publication_english.pdf|work=Equality and Human Rights Commission|publisher=Equality and Human Rights Commission|accessdate=26 December 2012|format=PDF|year=2008|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120610021426/http://equalityhumanrights.com/uploaded_files/download_who_do_you_see_publication_english.pdf|archive-date=10 June 2012|url-status=dead}}</ref> Results showed that 38 percent of those questioned would not accept a long-term relationship with, or would be unhappy if a close relative married or formed a relationship with, a Gypsy Traveller. Furthermore, only 37 percent found it acceptable if a member of the Gypsy Traveller minorities became primary school teachers, the lowest score of any group.<ref name=\"equalityhumanrights.com\"/> An advertising campaign to tackle prejudice in Wales was launched by the [[Equality and Human Rights Commission|Equality and Human Rights Commission (EHRC)]] in 2008.<ref>{{cite web|title=Kirby faces up to anti-Gypsy feeling in Wales|url=http://www.travellerstimes.org.uk/list.aspx?c=00619ef1-21e2-40aa-8d5e-f7c38586d32f&n=f52bed58-5368-408f-b50f-b543344a1b60|work=Travellers' Times|publisher=The Rural Media Company|accessdate=26 December 2012|author=Jake Bowers|format=Audio upload and article|date=21 October 2008|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130607110214/http://www.travellerstimes.org.uk/list.aspx?c=00619EF1-21E2-40AA-8D5E-F7C38586D32F&n=F52BED58-5368-408F-B50F-B543344A1B60|archive-date=7 June 2013|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\n=====Northern Ireland=====\nIn June 2009, having had their windows broken and deaths threats made against them, 20 Romanian Romani families were forced from their homes in [[Lisburn Road]], [[Belfast]], in [[Northern Ireland]]. Up to 115 people, including women and children, were forced to seek refuge in a local [[church hall]] after being attacked. They were later moved by the authorities to a safer location.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.irishtimes.com/newspaper/opinion/2009/0618/1224249058810.html|title=Racist attacks on Roma are latest low in North's intolerant history|date=18 June 2009|publisher=irishtimes.com|accessdate=18 June 2009}}</ref> An [[Anti-racism|anti-racist]] rally in the city on 15 June to support Romani rights was attacked by youths chanting [[neo-Nazi]] slogans. The attacks were condemned by [[Amnesty International]]<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.amnesty.org.uk/news_details.asp?NewsID=18257 |title=Amnesty International |publisher=Amnesty.org.uk |date=17 June 2009 |accessdate=17 May 2012}}</ref> and political leaders from both the [[Unionism in Ireland|Unionist]] and [[Irish nationalism|Nationalist]] traditions in Northern Ireland.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.google.com/hostednews/ap/article/ALeqM5iDji7_Kp0M1B_ADrZ0T9-dBi-xpwD98SI4HG0|title=Romanian Gypsies attacked inIreland|last=Morrison|first=Peter|last2=Lawless|first2=Jill|first3=Meera |last3=Selva |first4=Nardine |last4=Saad |first5=Alina |last5=Wolfe Murray|date=17 June 2009|agency=Associated Press|accessdate=18 June 2009| archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20090623081024/https://www.google.com/hostednews/ap/article/ALeqM5iDji7_Kp0M1B_ADrZ0T9-dBi-xpwD98SI4HG0| archivedate= 23 June 2009 | url-status= live}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/uk_news/northern_ireland/8110950.stm|title=Protest held over racist attacks|date=20 June 2009|work=BBC News|accessdate=20 June 2009| archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20090622034016/http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/uk_news/northern_ireland/8110950.stm| archivedate= 22 June 2009 | url-status= live}}</ref>\n\nFollowing the arrest of three local youths in relation to the attacks, the church where the Romanis had been given shelter was badly vandalised. Using 'emergency funds', Northern Ireland authorities assisted most of the victims to return to Romania.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/uk/2009/jun/23/belfast-church-vandalised-racist-attacks-romanians|title=Vandals attack Belfast church that sheltered Romanian victims of racism|last= McDonald|first=Henry|date=23 June 2009|work=guardian.co.uk|accessdate=23 June 2009 | location=London| archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20090626063353/http://www.guardian.co.uk/uk/2009/jun/23/belfast-church-vandalised-racist-attacks-romanians| archivedate= 26 June 2009 | url-status= live}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/uk_news/northern_ireland/8114234.stm|title=Romanians leave NI after attacks|date=23 June 2009|publisher=BBC News website|accessdate=23 June 2009| archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20090624091208/http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/uk_news/northern_ireland/8114234.stm| archivedate= 24 June 2009 | url-status= live}}</ref>\n\n===Non-EU countries===\n\n====Canada====\nWhen Romani [[refugee]]s were allowed into Canada in 1997, a protest was staged by 25 people, including [[neo-Nazi]]s, in front of the motel where the refugees were staying. The protesters held signs that included, \"Honk if you hate Gypsies\", \"Canada is not a Trash Can\", and \"G.S.T. \u2013 Gypsies Suck Tax\". (The last is a reference to Canada's unpopular [[Goods and Services Tax (Canada)|Goods and Services Tax]], also known as GST.) The protesters were charged with promoting hatred, and the case, called ''[[R. v. Krymowski]]'', reached the [[Supreme Court of Canada]] in 2005.<ref>''[[R. v. Krymowski]]'' [2005] 1 S.C.R. 101.</ref>\n\nOn 5 September 2012, prominent Canadian conservative commentator [[Ezra Levant]] broadcast a commentary \"The Jew vs. the Gypsies\" on ''[[J-Source (website)|J-Source]]'' in which he accused the [[Romani people]] of being a group of criminals: \"These are gypsies, a culture synonymous with swindlers. The phrase gypsy and cheater have been so interchangeable historically that the word has entered the English language as a verb: he [[:wikt:gyp|gypped]] me. Well the gypsies have gypped us. Too many have come here as false refugees. And they come here to gyp us again and rob us blind as they have done in Europe for centuries.\u2026 They\u2019re gypsies. And one of the central characteristics of that culture is that their chief economy is theft and begging.\"<ref name=jsource>{{cite news|title=Hate crime investigation launched surrounding Ezra Levant's Roma broadcast|url=http://j-source.ca/article/hate-crime-investigation-launched-surrounding-ezra-levant%E2%80%99s-roma-broadcast|accessdate=25 October 2012|newspaper=J-Source (website)|publisher=[[The Canadian Journalism Foundation]]|date=24 October 2012}}</ref>\n\n====Kosovo====\nFrom the end of the [[Kosovo War]] in June 1999, about 80% of [[Kosovo]]'s{{ref label|status|a|}} Romanis were expelled, amounting to approximately 100,000 expellees.<ref name=cahn>{{Citation|author=Claude Cahn |year=2007 |title=Birth of a Nation: Kosovo and the Persecution of Pariah Minorities |journal=[[German Law Journal]] |volume=8 |issue=1 |issn=2071-8322 |url=http://www.germanlawjournal.org/pdfs/Vol08No01/PDF_Vol_08_No_01_81-94_SI_Cahn.pdf |mode=cs1 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150215183028/http://www.germanlawjournal.org/pdfs/Vol08No01/PDF_Vol_08_No_01_81-94_SI_Cahn.pdf |archivedate=15 February 2015 |df=dmy }}</ref>{{rp|82}} For the 1999\u20132006 period, the [[European Roma Rights Centre]] documented numerous crimes perpetrated by Kosovo's ethnic Albanians with the purpose to purge the region of its Romani population along with other non-Albanian ethnic communities. These crimes included murder, abduction and illegal detention, torture, rape, arson, confiscation of houses and other property and forced labour. Whole Romani settlements were burned to the ground by Albanians.<ref name=cahn/>{{rp|82}} Romanis remaining in Kosovo are reported to be systematically denied fundamental human rights. They \"live in a state of pervasive fear\"<ref name=cahn/>{{rp|83}} and are routinely intimidated, verbally harassed and periodically attacked on racist grounds by Albanians.<ref name=cahn/>{{rp|83}} The Romani community of Kosovo is regarded to be, for the most part, annihilated.<ref name=cahn/>{{rp|93}}\n\nAt [[Roma in United Nations refugee camps, Kosovska Mitrovica|UN internally displaced persons' camps in Kosovska Mitrovica for Romanis]], the refugees were exposed to lead poisoning.<ref>{{cite web |author=Gesellschaft fuer bedrohte Voelker \u2013 Society for Threatened Peoples |url=http://www.gfbv.de/inhaltsDok.php?id=435&stayInsideTree=1 |title=Lead Poisoning of Roma in Idp Camps in Kosovo |publisher=Gfbv.de |accessdate=17 May 2012 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110719033156/http://www.gfbv.de/inhaltsDok.php?id=435&stayInsideTree=1 |archive-date=19 July 2011 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\n====Norway====\nIn [[Norway]], many Romani people were forcibly sterilized by the state until 1977.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.newint.org/features/2008/01/01/roma/|title=The eternal minority|publisher=New Internationalist|first=Eleanor|last=Harding|date=January 2008|accessdate=15 April 2008| archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20080430212911/http://www.newint.org/features/2008/01/01/roma/| archivedate= 30 April 2008 | url-status= live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/?id=j5TdqodY_QwC&pg=PA173&lpg=PA173&dq=Norway+roma+sterilisation|title=The Nordic peace|contribution=The non-autonomous minority groups in the Nordic countries|last=Hannikainen|first=Lauri|last2=\u00c5kermark|first2=Sia Spiliopoulou|pages=171\u2013197|editor-last=Clive|editor-first=Archer|editor2-last=Joenniemi|editor2-first=Pertti|year=2003|location=Aldershot|isbn=978-0-7546-1417-3|publisher=Ashgate|postscript=<!--None-->}}</ref>\n\nAnti-Romanyism in Norway flared up in July 2012, when roughly 200 Romani people settled outside [[:no:Sofienberg kirke|Sofienberg church]] in Oslo and were later relocated to a building site at [[\u00c5rvoll]], in northern Oslo. The group was subjected to [[hate crime]]s in the form of stone throwing and fireworks being aimed at and fired into their camp. They, and Norwegians trying to assist them in their situation, also received [[death threat]]s.<ref>{{cite web|title=Folk er folk-leder sier han har f\u00e5tt flere drapstrusler|url=http://www.aftenposten.no/nyheter/iriks/Folk-er-folk-leder-sier-han-har-fatt-flere-drapstrusler-6943346.html|accessdate=31 July 2012}}</ref> [[Siv Jensen]], the leader of the right-wing [[Progress Party (Norway)|Progress Party]], also advocated the expulsion of the Romani people resident in Oslo.<ref>{{cite news|title=Jensen: \u2013 Nok er nok, sett opp buss, send dem ut|url=http://www.nrk.no/nyheter/norge/1.8244413|accessdate=26 December 2012|newspaper=NRK|date=15 July 2012|last1=Solvang|first1=Fredrik|last2=Haga Honnings\u00f8y|first2=Kirsti|language=Norwegian}}</ref>\n\n====Switzerland====\nA Swiss right-wing magazine, Weltwoche, published a photograph of a gun-wielding Roma child on its cover in 2012, with the title \"The Roma are coming: Plundering in Switzerland\". They claimed in a series of articles of a growing trend in the country of \"criminal tourism for which eastern European Roma clans are responsible\", with professional gangs specializing in burglary, thefts, organized begging and street prostitution.<ref name=\"irishtimes1\">{{cite news|author=Email Us |url=https://www.irishtimes.com/newspaper/world/2012/0412/1224314639219.html |title=Magazine under fire for racist Roma cover \u2013 The Irish Times \u2013 Thu, 12 April 2012 |newspaper=The Irish Times |date=12 April 2012 |accessdate=17 May 2012}}</ref> The magazine immediately came under criticism for its links to the right-wing populist [[Swiss People's Party|People's Party (SVP)]], as being deliberately provocative and encouraged racist stereotyping by linking ethnic origin and criminality.<ref name=\"irishtimes1\"/> Switzerland's Federal Commission against Racism is considering legal action after complaints in Switzerland, Austria and Germany that the cover breached antiracism laws.\n\nThe Berlin newspaper ''[[Tagesspiegel]]'' investigated the origins of the photograph taken in the slums of [[Gjakova]], [[Kosovo]], where Roma communities were displaced during the [[Kosovo War]] to hovels built on a toxic landfill.<ref>{{cite web|author=von Andrea Dernbach |url=http://www.tagesspiegel.de/medien/streit-um-roma-reportage-raubzuege-beim-fotografen/6498056.html |title=Streit um Roma-Reportage: Raubz\u00fcge beim Fotografen \u2013 Medien \u2013 Tagesspiegel |language=de |publisher=Tagesspiegel.de |accessdate=17 May 2012}}</ref> The Italian photographer, Livio Mancini, denounced the abuse of his photograph, which was originally taken to demonstrate the plight of Roma families in Europe.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.presseurop.eu/en/content/news-brief/1799581-anti-roma-front-page-provokes-controversy |title=Anti-Roma front page provokes controversy &#124; Presseurop (English) |publisher=[[Presseurop]] |accessdate=17 May 2012}}</ref>\n\n==== New Zealand ====\n''The Great Replacement'' manifesto by [[Christchurch mosque shootings|Christchurch mosques shooter]] [[Brenton Harrison Tarrant]] described [[Roma people|Roma/Gypsies]] as one of the non-Europeans alongside [[Black people|African]], [[Indian people|Indian]], [[Turkish people|Turkish]], and [[Semitic people|Semitic]] ([[Jews|Jewish]] and [[Arabs|Arab]]) peoples that the shooter wanted to be removed from [[Europe]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.ilfogilo.it/userUpload/The_Great_Replacementconvertito.pdf|title=The Great Replacement|quote=\"The invaders must be removed from European soil, regardless whether they came or when they came. Roma, African, Indian, Turkish, Semitic, or other\"|access-date=March 24, 2019|date=March 15, 2019}}</ref>\n\n==== United States ====\n=====Elsie Paroubek Affair (1911)=====\nIn [[Chicago]] in 1911, the highly-publicised disappearance of the five-year old [[Elsie Paroubek]] was immediately blamed on \"Gypsy child kidnappers\". The public was alerted to reports that \"Gypsies were seen with a little girl\" and many such reports came in. Police raided a \"Gypsy\" encampment near 18th and South Halstead in Chicago itself and they later expanded the searches and raids to encampments throughout the state of [[Illinois]], to locations as widespread as [[Round Lake, Illinois|Round Lake]], [[McHenry, Illinois|McHenry]], [[Volo, Illinois|Volo]] and [[Cherry Valley, Illinois|Cherry Valley]] - but they found no trace of the missing girl. The police attributed her capture to \"the natural love of the wandering people for blue-eyed, yellow-haired children\".<ref name=\"romanyrye\">{{Citation |newspaper=Los Angeles Times |page=I6 |title=Think Gypsies Have His Girl: Father & A Policeman on the Trail of Nomads.  |url=https://pqasb.pqarchiver.com/latimes/access/348133382.html?dids=348133382:348133382&FMT=ABS&FMTS=ABS:AI&type=historic&date=Apr+15%2C+1911&author=&pub=Los+Angeles+Times&desc=THINK+GYPSIES+HAVE+HIS+GIRL.&pqatl=google |date=April 15, 1911}}</ref> Lillian Wulff, age 11 - who had actually been kidnapped by some Romanis four years earlier - came forward to offer his assistance, leading the police to conduct further fruitless raids, as well as convincing them to detain the supposed \"King of the Gypsies\", Elijah George - who, however,\"failed to give them the desired information\", and was released. Elijah George was detained in [[Argyle, Wisconsin]], and this served to spread the anti-Romani hysteria outside Illinois.\n\nThe police finally abandoned this line of investigation. Still, when the girl's body was finally found, her distraught father Frank Paroubek charged: \"I am sure the gypsies stole my girl and then when they knew we were after them, they killed her and threw her body into the canal.\" The anti-Romani agitation might have been exacerbated by the fact that the missing girl was a [[Czech Americans|Czech American]], and the Czech American community massively mobilized to participate in the searches and support her family. This might have had the inadvertent result of importing the prejudices which were prevalent in Czech society to America.\n\n=====Present Situation=====\nAt the present time, because the Roma population in the [[United States]] has quickly assimilated and Roma people are not often portrayed in US popular culture, the term \"Gypsy\" is typically associated with a trade or lifestyle instead of being associated with the Romani ethnic group. While many Americans consider ethnic costumes offensive (such as [[blackface]]), many Americans continue to dress up as gypsy characters for [[Halloween]] or other events. Additionally, some small businesses, particularly those in the [[fortune-telling]] and psychic reading industry,<ref>{{cite web|title=Real Stories From Victims Who've Been Scammed |url=http://www.gypsypsychicscams.com/realstories.html |publisher=gypsypsychicscams.com |accessdate=26 August 2007 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070826075723/http://www.gypsypsychicscams.com/realstories.html |archivedate=26 August 2007 |url-status=dead }}</ref> use the term \"Gypsy\" to describe themselves or their enterprises, even though they have no ties to the Roma people. Some do, however, as perhaps up to a million Americans, have Romani ancestry (see [[Romani Americans]]), but they are usually of partial Romani descent.\n\nWhile some scholars argue that appropriation of the Roma identity in the United States is based on misconceptions and ignorance rather than anti-Romanyism,<ref>{{cite book |last=Sutherland |first=Anne |year=1986 |title=Gypsies: The Hidden Americans |publisher=Waveland Press |page=86 |isbn=978-0-88133-235-3}}</ref> Romani advocacy groups decry the practice.<ref>{{cite web |website=Voice of Roma |title=Breaking 'Gypsy' Stereotypes |date=23 March 2010 |url=http://www.voiceofroma.com/culture/gyp_vs_rom.shtml}}</ref>\n\n==Environmental struggles==\n{{More citations needed section|date=December 2012}}\n{{see also|Environmental racism in Europe}}\n\nEnvironmental issues which were caused by [[Cold War]]-era industrial development have disproportionately impacted the Roma, particularly those Roma who live in Eastern Europe. Most often, the traditional nomadic lifestyle of the Roma causes them to settle on the outskirts of towns and cities, where amenities, employment and educational opportunities are often inaccessible. As of 1993, [[Hungary]] has been identified as one country where this issue exists: \"While the economic restructuring of a command economy into a western style market economy created hardships for most Hungarians, with the national unemployment rate heading toward 14 percent and per capita real income falling, the burdens which are imposed on Romanis are disproportionately great.\"<ref name=\"Feher, 1993\">Feher, Gyorgy. 1993. ''Struggling for Ethnic Identity: The Gypsies of Hungary''. Library of Congress Card Catalogue: USA.</ref>\n\nPanel buildings ([[panel\u00e1k]]) in the Chanov ghetto near [[Most (Most District)|Most]], [[Czech Republic]] were built in the 1970s for a high-income clientele, the authorities introduced a model plan, whereby Roma were relocated to these buildings, from poorer areas, to live among Czech neighbors. However, with the rising proportion of Roma moving in, the Czech clients gradually moved out in a kind of [[white flight]], eventually leaving a district in which the vast majority of residents were Roma.<ref name=\"janousek\">{{Citation\n| last = Janou\u0161ek\n| first = Artur\n| author-link =\n| publication-date =\n| date =  18 September 2007\n| title = Hr\u016fza \u00dasteck\u00e9ho kraje: s\u00eddli\u0161t\u011b Chanov\n| periodical = iDnes.cz\n| series =\n| publication-place =\n| place =\n| publisher =\n| volume =\n| issue =\n| pages =\n| page =\n| at =\n| url = http://zpravy.idnes.cz/hruza-usteckeho-kraje-sidliste-chanov-dx9-/domaci.asp?c=A070918_090742_domaci_itu\n| issn =\n| pmid =\n| pmc =\n| doi =\n| oclc =\n| accessdate =13 March 2011\n| ref =\n|language=cs}}</ref> A poll in 2007 marked the district as the worst place in the [[\u00dast\u00ed nad Labem Region]].<ref name=\"janousek\"/> Buildings were eventually stripped of any valuable materials and torn down. The removal of materials was blamed on the Roma who had last inhabited the building.<ref>{{Citation\n| last = \u010cTK\n| first =\n| author-link = Czech News Agency\n| date = 23 June 2006\n| title = V Chanov\u011b se bude bourat i druh\u00fd vybydlen\u00fd panel\u00e1k\n| periodical = ceskenoviny.cz\n| series =\n| publication-place =\n| place =\n| publisher = Czech News Agency\n| volume =\n| issue =\n| pages =\n| page =\n| at =\n| url = http://www.ceskenoviny.cz/zpravy/v-chanove-se-bude-bourat-i-druhy-vybydleny-panelak/494893&id_seznam=\n| issn =\n| pmid =\n| pmc =\n| doi =\n| oclc =\n| accessdate =13 March 2011\n| ref =\n|language=cs}}</ref> Despite a total rental debt in excess of \u20ac3.5 million, all of the tenants in the remaining buildings continue to be provided with water and electricity,<ref>{{Citation\n| last = Sl\u00ed\u017eov\u00e1\n| first = Radka\n| author-link =\n| publication-date = 25 February 2010\n| title = Chanov jde do lep\u0161\u00edch \u010das\u016f\n| periodical = sedmicka.cz\n| series =\n| publication-place =\n| place =\n| publisher =\n| volume =\n| issue =\n| pages =\n| page =\n| at =\n| url = http://www.sedmicka.cz/chomutov-jirkov-litvinov-most/clanek?id=130307\n| issn =\n| pmid =\n| pmc =\n| doi =\n| oclc =\n| accessdate =13 March 2011\n| ref =\n|language=cs}}</ref> unlike the situation in many other European countries.\n[[File:LunikIX.jpeg|thumb|Roma settlement [[Lun\u00edk IX]] near [[Ko\u0161ice]], Slovakia.]] When newly built in the 1980s, some flats in this settlement were assigned to Roma who had relocated from poverty-stricken locations in a government effort to integrate the Roma population. Other flats were assigned to families of military and law-enforcement personnel. However, the military and police families gradually moved out of the residences and the living conditions for the Roma population deteriorated. Ongoing failures to pay bills led to the disconnection of the water supply and an emergency plan was eventually created to provide running water for two hours per day to mitigate against the bill payment issue. Similarly to Chanov, some of these buildings were stripped of their materials and were eventually torn down; again, the Roma residents were identified as the culprits who were to blame for the theft of the materials.<ref>{{cite web\n| last = Prokop\n| first = Dan\n| authorlink =\n| title = Ko\u0161ice zbouraj\u00ed \"vybydlen\u00e9\" panel\u00e1ky na romsk\u00e9m s\u00eddli\u0161ti Lun\u00edk\n| work = idnes.cz\n| publisher =\n| date = 28 September 2008\n| url = http://zpravy.idnes.cz/kosice-zbouraji-vybydlene-panelaky-na-romskem-sidlisti-lunik-p6p-/zahranicni.asp?c=A080805_163403_zahranicni_dp\n| doi =\n| accessdate =13 March 2011|language=cs}}</ref><ref>\n{{cite web\n| title = LUN\u00cdK IX.: B\u00fdvanie na s\u00eddlisku je kritick\u00e9, obyvate\u013eom zriadili konto na pomoc\n| work = tvnoviny.sk\n| date = 18 March 2010\n| url = http://tvnoviny.sk/spravy/krimi/lunik-ix-byvanie-na-sidlisku-je-kriticke-obyvatelom-zriadili-konto-na-pomoc.html\n| accessdate = 13 March 2011\n| language = sk\n| archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20110725105554/http://tvnoviny.sk/spravy/krimi/lunik-ix-byvanie-na-sidlisku-je-kriticke-obyvatelom-zriadili-konto-na-pomoc.html\n| archive-date = 25 July 2011\n| url-status = dead\n}}\n</ref><ref>{{cite web\n| last = Teichmanov\u00e1\n| first = Ladislava\n| authorlink =\n| title = Na Lun\u00edku IX a v Demeteri dlhuj\u00fa za vodu 133 000 \u20ac\n| work = webnoviny.sk\n| publisher =\n| url = http://www.webnoviny.sk/slovensko/na-luniku-ix-a-v-demeteri-dlhuju-za-vo/21765-clanok.html\n| doi =\n| accessdate =13 March 2011|language=sk}}</ref><ref>{{cite web\n| last = \u010cTK\n| authorlink = Czech News Agency\n| title = Na ko\u0161ick\u00e9m romsk\u00e9m s\u00eddli\u0161ti Lun\u00edk IX. zase te\u010de voda\n| work = romove.radio.cz\n| date = 5 May 2005\n| url = http://romove.radio.cz/cz/clanek/20588\n| accessdate =13 March 2011| archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20110306005122/http://romove.radio.cz/cz/clanek/20588| archivedate= 6 March 2011 | url-status= live|language=cs}}</ref>\n\nThe various legal hindrances to their traditional nomadic lifestyle have forced many travelling Roma to move into unsafe areas, such as ex-industrial areas, former landfills or other waste areas where pollutants have affected rivers, streams or groundwater. Consequently, Roma are often unable to access clean water or sanitation facilities, rendering the Roma people more vulnerable to health problems, such as [[disease]]s. Based in [[Belgium]], the Health & Environment Alliance has included a statement with regard to the Roma on one of its pamphlets: \"Denied environmental benefits such as water, sewage treatment facilities, sanitation and access to natural resources, and suffer from exposure to environmental hazards due to their proximity to hazardous waste sites, incinerators, factories, and other sources of pollution.\"<ref name=\"Environmental Health\">{{cite web|title= Environmental Justice: Listening to Women and Children|publisher=Environmental Health|url= http://www.env-health.org/IMG/pdf/cepl_final-2.pdf}}</ref> Since the [[Revolutions of 1989|fall of communism]] and the privatisation of the formerly state owned water-supply companies in many areas of central and eastern Europe, the provision of decent running water to illegal buildings which are often occupied by Roma became a particularly sensitive issue, because the new international owners of the water-supply companies are unwilling to make contracts with the Roma population and as a result, \"water-borne diseases, such as [[diarrhoea]] and [[dysentery]]\" became \"an almost constant feature of daily life, especially for children\".\n\nAccording to a study that was conducted by the [[United Nations Development Program]], the percentage of Roma with access to running water and sewage treatment within Romania and the Czech Republic is well below the national average in those countries. Consequently, a proliferation of skin diseases among these populations, due to the low quality of housing standards, including [[scabies]], [[pediculosis]], [[pyoderma]], [[mycosis]] and [[ascariasis]], has occurred; respiratory health problems also affect the majority of the inhabitants of these areas, in addition to increasing rates of [[hepatitis]] and [[tuberculosis]].{{Citation needed|date=December 2012}}\n\nAdditionally, the permanent settlement of Roma in residential areas is often met with hostility by non-Roma or the exodus of non-Roma, a reaction which is similar to [[white flight]] in the [[United States]].<ref name=\"Harper, 2009\">{{cite web|title=Environmental Justice and Roma Communities in Central and Eastern Europe|url=http://works.bepress.com/cgi/viewcontent.cgi?article=1001&context=krista_harper|work=Environmental Justice and Roma Communities in Central and Eastern Europe|publisher=University of Massachusetts \u2013 Amherst|accessdate=26 December 2012|author=Krista M. Harper PhD|author2=Tamara Steger, PhD|author3=Richard Fil\u010d\u00e1k, PhD|format=PDF|date=July 2009}}</ref> Moreover, local councils have issued bans against Roma, who are frequently evicted.{{Citation needed|date=December 2012}}\n\n==In popular culture==\n\n* In \"The Big Clan\" episode of the television show \"[[Dragnet (1967 TV series)|Dragnet]],\" originally broadcast on February 8, 1968, Sgt. Friday (Jack Webb) indicates the gypsies are a criminal organization.\n* In the 2006 mockumentary ''[[Borat]]'', [[Sacha Baron Cohen]]'s character explains that his home town has \"a tall fence for keeping out Gypsies and Jews\"; the scene featuring this town was filmed in [[Moroeni|Glod]], a Roma village in central Romania. He makes many more anti-Romani statements throughout the film.\n* ''[[The Adventures of Tintin]]'' comic ''[[The Castafiore Emerald]]'' criticises anti-Romanyism.  After [[Captain Haddock]] invites a group of Roma to move onto his property, they are falsely accused of stealing [[Bianca Castafiore]]'s priceless [[emerald]]. [[Tintin (character)|Tintin]] objects to other characters who express their suspicion and uncovers the real culprit to have been a [[magpie]].\n* In several adaptations of [[Victor Hugo]]'s ''[[The Hunchback of Notre Dame]]'' such as the [[The Hunchback of Notre Dame (1996 film)|1996 Disney version]], [[Claude Frollo]] is portrayed as having a strong, genocidal hatred of gypsies, although this characteristic is not so evident in the original novel.\n* Many instances of Anti-Romanyism are described in Kristian Novak's 2016 novel ''Ziganin but the most beautiful''.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Krmpoti\u0107|first1=Marinko|title=\"Ciganin al' najljep\u0161i\" Kristijana Novaka: Mra\u010dna tema za \u010ditateljsko u\u017eivanje / Novi list|url=http://www.novilist.hr/Kultura/Knjizevnost/Ciganin-al-najljepsi-Kristijana-Novaka-Mracna-tema-za-citateljsko-uzivanje|website=[[Novi list]]|accessdate=3 May 2018|language=hr-HR|date=1 August 2017}}</ref>\n*The 2000 [[Guy Ritchie]] crime drama [[Snatch (film)|''Snatch'']] shows anti-[[Irish Travellers|Irish Traveller]] sentiment among Britons.\n\n==See also==<!-- Please respect alphabetical order -->\n* [[Afrophobia]]\n* [[\u00c0 la zingara]]\n* [[Antisemitism]]\n* [[Aporophobia]]\n* [[Caste]]\n* [[Cultural assimilation]]\n* [[Discrimination]]\n* [[Discrimination law]]\n* [[Environmental racism in Europe]]\n* [[Human Rights]]\n* [[Institutionalized discrimination]]\n* [[Indophobia]]\n* [[Racism]]\n* [[Second-class citizen]]\n* [[Sinophobia]]\n\n==Notes==\n{| style=\"margin-left:13px; line-height:150%\"\n|align=\"right\" valign=\"top\"|a.&nbsp;&nbsp;\n|{{note|status}}{{Kosovo-note}}\n|}\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n* [http://www.humanrightsfirst.org/discrimination/pages.aspx?id=85 Human Rights First Report on Violence Against Roma]\n* [http://www.coe.int/t/dg3/romatravellers/documentation/discrimination/knudsen_en.asp Council of Europe webpage on anti-Romanyism]\n* [http://www.ezaf.org/ European Centre for Antiziganism Research]\n* [http://www.osce.org/odihr/18148.html OSCE/ODIHR portal on Roma and Sinti issues]\n* [http://www.errc.org/ European Roma Rights Centre]\n\n{{Anti-cultural sentiment}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Anti-national sentiment]]\n[[Category:Anti-Romanyism| ]]\n[[Category:Genocides]]\n[[Category:Romani]]\n[[Category:Racism in the United Kingdom]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|racism against Romanis}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2014}}\n{{Discrimination sidebar}}\n{{Romani people}}\n'''Antiziganism''' (also '''antigypsyism''', '''anti-Romanyism''', '''Romaphobia''', or '''anti-Romani sentiment''') is hostility, [[prejudice]], discrimination or [[racism]] which is specifically directed at [[Romani people]] (Roma, [[Sinti]], [[Iberian Kale]], [[Kale (Welsh Roma)|Welsh Kale]], [[Finnish Kale]] and [[Romanichal]]). Non-Rom [[itinerant groups in Europe]] such as the [[Yenish people|Yenish]] and [[Irish Travellers|Irish]] and [[Scottish Gypsy and Traveller groups|Scottish Travellers]] are often given the misnomer \"gypsy\" and confused with the Romani people. As a result, sentiments which were originally directed at the Romani people are also directed at other traveler groups and they are often referred to as \"'''antigypsy'''\" sentiments.\n\nThe term ''Antigypsyism'' is recognized by the [[European Parliament]] and the [[European Commission]] as well as by a wide cross-section of civil society.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://antigypsyism.eu/wp-content/uploads/2017/07/Antigypsyism-reference-paper-16.06.2017.pdf|title=Antigypsyism: Reference Paper|last=|first=|date=|website=Antigypsyism.eu|access-date=24 January 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Etymology==\n{{see also|Names of the Romani people}}\nThe root ''Zigan'' comes from the term ''Cingane'' (alt. Tsinganoi, Zigar, Zigeuner) which probably derives from ''[[Athinganoi]]'', the name of a Christian sect which the Romani became associated with during the [[Middle Ages]].<ref name=\"White 1999\">{{cite journal|url=http://www.isidore-of-seville.com/goudenhoorn/72karin.html |title=Metal-workers, agriculturists, acrobats, military-people and fortune-tellers: Roma in and around the Byzantine empire |first=Karin |last=White |year=1999 |journal=Golden Horn |volume=7 |issue=2 |accessdate=2007-08-26 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20010320210002/http://www.isidore-of-seville.com/goudenhoorn/72karin.html |archivedate=20 March 2001 }}</ref><ref name=Starr>Starr, J. (1936). An Eastern Christian Sect: the Athinganoi. ''Dumbarton Oaks Papers, Trustees for Harvard University'', 29, 93-106.</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.sca.org/ti/articles/2002/issue144/rom.html |title=A Brief History of the Rom |first=Karina |last=Bates |accessdate=2007-08-26 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070810161445/http://www.sca.org/ti/articles/2002/issue144/rom.html |archivedate=10 August 2007 |url-status=live |df=dmy }}</ref><ref>{{cite journal|url=http://taylorandfrancis.metapress.com/index/9Y2PJM6YAYT1UVHW.pdf|title=Book Reviews|format=PDF|journal=Population Studies|volume=48|issue=2|date=July 1994|pages=365\u2013372|doi=10.1080/0032472031000147856}}</ref> According to Martin Holler, the English term ''anti-Gypsyism'' stems from the mid-1980s, and it became mainstream in the 2000s and 2010s, whereas the term ''antiziganism'' was more recently borrowed from the German ''Antiziganismus''.<ref>{{Cite book |last=Holler |first=Martin |date=2015 |title=Antiziganism: What's in a Word? |chapter=Historical Predecessors of the Term 'Anti-Gypsyism' |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=xl8HCgAAQBAJ&pg=PA82 |location= |publisher=Cambridge Scholars Publishing |page=82 |isbn=9781443878715 |accessdate=8 September 2016}}</ref>\n\n==History==\n{{main|History of the Romani people}}\n===In the Middle Ages===\n[[File:Enfant enlevee par des nomades.JPG|thumb|A French poster depicting a child being [[kidnapping|kidnapped]] by [[nomads]]]]\n{{See also|Slavery in Romania}}\n\nIn the early 13th-century [[Byzantine Empire|Byzantine]] records, the ''Ats\u00ednganoi'' are mentioned as \"wizards ... who are inspired satanically and pretend to predict the unknown\".<ref>George Soulis (1961): ''The Gypsies in the Byzantine Empire and the Balkans in the Late Middle Ages'' (Dumbarton Oaks Papers) Vol.15 pp.146\u2013147, cited in David Crowe (2004): ''A History of the Gypsies of Eastern Europe and Russia'' (Palgrave Macmillan) {{ISBN|0-312-08691-1}} p.1</ref>\n\nEnslavement of Roma, mostly taken as prisoners of war, in the [[Danubian Principalities]] is first documented in the late 15th century. In these countries extensive legislation was developed that classified Roma into different groups, according to their tasks as slaves.<ref name=\"Achim2004\">{{cite book|title=The Roma in Romanian History|last=Achim|first=Viorel|publisher=[[Central European University Press]]|place=Budapest|date=2004|isbn=9639241849}}</ref>\n\nBy the 16th century, many Romani who lived in [[Eastern Europe|Eastern]] and [[Central Europe]] worked as musicians, metal craftsmen, and soldiers.<ref>David Crowe (2004): ''A History of the Gypsies of Eastern Europe and Russia'' (Palgrave Macmillan) {{ISBN|0-312-08691-1}} p.XI</ref> As the [[Ottoman Empire]] expanded, it relegated the Romani, who were seen as having \"no visible permanent professional affiliation\", to the lowest rung of the social ladder.<ref>Crowe (2004) p.2</ref>\n\n===16th & 17th centuries===\nIn [[Royal Hungary]] in the 16th century at the time of the Turkish occupation, the Crown developed strong anti-Romani policies, as these people were considered suspect as Turkish spies or as a [[fifth column]]. In this atmosphere, they were expelled from many locations and increasingly adopted a nomadic way of life.<ref>Crowe (2004) p.1, p.34</ref>\n\nThe first anti-Romani legislation was issued in the [[March of Moravia]] in 1538, and three years later, [[Ferdinand I of Germany|Ferdinand I]] ordered that Romani in his realm be expelled after a series of fires in [[Prague]].\n\nIn 1545, the [[Diet of Augsburg]] declared that \"whosoever kills a Gypsy (Romani), will be guilty of no murder\".<ref>Crowe (2004) p.34</ref> The subsequent massive killing spree which took place across the empire later prompted the government to step in to \"forbid the drowning of Romani women and children\".<ref>Crowe (2004) p.35</ref>\n\nIn England, the [[Egyptians Act 1530]] banned Romani from entering the country and required those living in the country to leave within 16 days. Failure to do so could result in confiscation of property, imprisonment and deportation. The act was amended with the [[Egyptians Act 1530#Egyptians Act 1554|Egyptians Act 1554]], which directed that they abandon their \"naughty, idle and ungodly life and company\" and adopt a settled lifestyle. For those who failed to adhere to a sedentary existence, the [[Privy council]] interpreted the act to permit execution of non-complying Romani \"as a warning to others\".<ref>{{cite book|last= Mayall|first=David|title=English gypsies and state policies|publisher=Univ of Hertfordshire Press|year=1995|series=f Interface collection Volume 7 of New Saga Library|volume=7|pages=21, 24|isbn= 978-0-900458-64-4|url=https://books.google.com/?id=XVh8mB-7n7wC&pg=PA21|accessdate=28 February 2010}}</ref>\n\nIn 1660, the Romani were prohibited from residing in [[France]] by [[Louis XIV]].<ref name=\"romahistory.com\">{{cite web|url=http://www.romahistory.com/en/2-5-4.htm|title=The History of the Roma: 2.5.4: 1647 to 1714|publisher=Romahistory.com|first=Marko D.|last=Knudsen|accessdate=24 December 2014|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131017082735/http://www.romahistory.com/en/2-5-4.htm|archivedate=17 October 2013|df=dmy}}</ref>\n\n===18th century===\n\nIn 1710, [[Joseph I, Holy Roman Emperor|Joseph I]], Holy Roman Emperor, issued an edict against the Romani, ordering \"that all adult males were to be hanged without trial, whereas women and young males were to be flogged and banished forever.\" In addition, in the [[kingdom of Bohemia]], Romani men were to have their right ears cut off; in the [[March (territory)|March]] [[March of Moravia|of Moravia]], the left ear was to be cut off. In other parts of Austria, they would be branded on the back with a [[branding iron]], representing the [[gallows]]. These mutilations enabled authorities to identify the individuals as Romani on their second arrest. The edict encouraged local officials to hunt down Romani in their areas by levying a fine of 100 [[Reichsthaler]] on those who failed to do so. Anyone who helped Romani was to be punished by doing [[forced labor]] for half a year. The result was mass killings of Romani across the Holy Roman empire. In 1721, [[Charles VI, Holy Roman Emperor|Charles VI]] amended the decree to include the execution of adult female Romani, while children were \"to be put in hospitals for education\".<ref>Crowe (2004) p.36-37</ref>\n\nIn 1774, [[Maria Theresa]] of [[Habsburg Monarchy|Austria]] issued an edict forbidding marriages between Romani. When a Romani woman married a non-Romani, she had to produce proof of \"industrious household service and familiarity with [[Catholic]] tenets\", a male Rom \"had to prove his ability to support a wife and children\", and \"Gypsy children over the age of five were to be taken away and brought up in non-Romani families.\"<ref>Crowe (2004) p.75</ref>\n\nIn 2007 the [[Romania]]n government established a panel to study the 18th- and 19th-century period of [[Slavery in Romania|Romani slavery]] by Princes, local landowners, and [[monasteries]]. This officially legalized practice was first documented in the 15th century.<ref name=\"Achim2004\"/> Slavery of Romani was outlawed in the Romanian Principalities of [[Moldavia]] and [[Wallachia]] in around 1856.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nasdaq.com/aspxcontent/NewsStory.aspx?cpath=20070220%5cACQDJON200702201414DOWJONESDJONLINE000608.htm& |title=Company News Story |publisher=Nasdaq.com |accessdate=17 May 2012}}</ref>\n\n===19th century===\nGovernments regularly cited petty theft committed by Romani as justification for regulating and persecuting them. In 1899, the {{ill|Nachrichtendienst f\u00fcr die Sicherheitspolizei in Bezug auf Zigeuner|de}} ({{translation|i=yes}} ''Intelligence service for the security police concerning gypsies'') was set up in [[Munich]] under the direction of {{ill|Alfred Dillmann|de}}, and catalogued data on all Romani individuals throughout the German-speaking lands. It did not officially close down until 1970. The results were published in 1905 in Dillmann's ''Zigeuner-Buch'',<ref name=\"Dillmann 1905\">{{cite book|first=Alfred|last=Dillmann|title=Zigeuner-Buch|location=Munich|publisher=Wildsche|year=1905|language=German}}</ref> which was used in the following years as justification for the [[Porajmos]]. It described the Romani people as a \"plague\" and a \"menace\", but almost exclusively characterized \"Gypsy crime\" as trespassing and the theft of food.<ref name=\"Dillmann 1905\"/>\n\nIn the [[United States]] during Congressional debate in 1866 over the [[Fourteenth Amendment to the United States Constitution]] which would subsequently [[Jus soli|grant citizenship]] to all persons born within U.S. territory, an objection raised was that a consequence of enacting the amendment would be to grant citizenship to Gypsies and other groups perceived by some as undesirable.<ref><!-- \u2588 DO NOT \u2588 replace this citation text with a Wikipedia template, especially not \"cite web\": this is the actual citation format recommended by the Library of Congress, which is not reproduced by any Wikipedia template --> ''[[Congressional Globe]]'', 1st Session, [[39th United States Congress|39th Congress]], [http://memory.loc.gov/cgi-bin/ampage?collId=llcg&fileName=073/llcg073.db&recNum=12 p. 2891] (1866)</ref>\n\n[[Pennsylvania]] Senator [[Edgar Cowan]] stated, {{quote|...I am as liberal as anybody toward the rights of all people, but I am unwilling, on the part of my State, to give up the right that she claims, and that she may exercise, and exercise before very long, of expelling a certain number of people who invade her borders; who owe her no allegiance; who pretend to owe none; who recognize no authority in her government; who have a distinct, independent government of their own\u2014an ''[[State within a state|imperium in imperio]]''; who pay no taxes; who never perform military service; who do nothing, in fact, which becomes a citizen, and perform none of the duties which devolve upon him, but, on the other hand, have no homes, pretend to own no land, live nowhere, settle as trespassers where ever they go, and whose sole merit is a universal swindle; who delight in it, who boast of it, and whose adroitness and cunning is of such a transcendent character that no skill can serve to correct or punish it; I mean the Gypsies.  They wander in gangs in my State... These people live in the country and are born in the country.  They infest society.}}\n\nIn response Senator [[John Conness]] of [[California]] observed, {{quote|I have lived in the United States now many a year, and really I have heard more about Gypsies within the last two or three months than I have heard before in my life.  It cannot be because they have increased so much of late.  It cannot be because they have been felt to be particularly oppressive in this or that locality.  It must be that the Gypsy element is to be added to our political agitation, so that hereafter the negro alone shall not claim our entire attention.}}\n\n===Porajmos===\n[[File:Brown triangle svg.jpg|150px|thumb|The brown [[Nazi concentration camp badges|inverted triangle on their prison uniforms]] that the Romani prisoners in concentration camps such as [[Auschwitz concentration camp|Auschwitz]] were forced to wear to distinguish them from other inmates.<ref>{{cite web |title=Questions: Triangles |url=http://www.holocaust-history.org/questions/triangles.shtml |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080914095332/http://www.holocaust-history.org/questions/triangles.shtml |archivedate=2008-09-14 |date=2000-05-16 |website=The Holocaust History Project }}</ref>]]\n[[File:Bundesarchiv R 165 Bild-244-47, Asperg, Deportation von Sinti und Roma.jpg|thumb|right|250px|German Nazi deportation of Sinti and Roma from [[Asperg]], 1940]]\n{{Main|Romani genocide}}\nPersecution of Romani people reached a peak during [[World War II]] in the [[Romani genocide|Porajmos]] (literally, ''the devouring''), a descriptive neologism for the Nazi genocide of Romanis during [[the Holocaust]]. Because the Romani communities in Central and Eastern Europe were less organized than the [[Jew]]ish communities and the [[Einsatzgruppen]], mobile killing squads, who travelled from village to village massacring the Romani inhabitants where they lived typically left few to no records of the number of Roma killed in this way, although in a few cases, significant documentary evidence of mass murder was generated.<ref>{{cite book |last=Headland |first=Ronald |year=1992 |title=Messages of Murder: A Study of the Reports of the Einsatzgruppen of the Security Police and the Security Service, 1941\u20131943 |publisher=Fairleigh Dickinson Univ Press |page=63 |isbn= 978-0-8386-3418-9 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=Mue8a5Rwyi0C&pg=PA63&dq=einsatzgruppen+gypsy&cd=3#v=snippet&q=824&f=false |accessdate=17 February 2010 }}</ref> it is more difficult to assess the actual number of victims. Historians estimate that between 220,000 and 500,000 Romani were killed by the Germans and their collaborators\u201425% to over 50% of the slightly fewer than 1 million Roma in Europe at the time.<ref name=USHMM_2>{{cite web |title=Holocaust Encyclopedia \u2013 Genocide of European Roma (Gypsies), 1939\u20131945 |publisher=United States Holocaust Memorial Museum (USHMM) |url=http://www.ushmm.org/wlc/en/article.php?ModuleId=10005219 |accessdate=9 August 2011 }}</ref> A more thorough research by [[Ian Hancock]] revealed the death toll to be at about 1.5 million.<ref name=Milton_estimates>{{Citation |chapter=True Romanies and the Holocaust: A Re-evaluation and an overview |chapter-url=http://www.radoc.net/radoc.php?doc=art_e_holocaust_porrajmos&lang=en&articles= |author=Hancock, Ian |title=The Historiography of the Holocaust |isbn=978-1-4039-9927-6 |pages=383\u2013396 |year=2005 |publisher=[[Palgrave Macmillan]] }}{{dead link|date=March 2018 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref>\n\nNazi racial ideology put [[Romani people|Romani]], Jews, Slavs and blacks at the bottom of the racial scale.<ref name=\"Simone Gigliotti 2005. Pp. 14\">Simone Gigliotti, Berel Lang. ''The Holocaust: a reader''. Malden, Massachusetts, USA; Oxford, England, UK; Carlton, Victoria, Australia: Blackwell Publishing, 2005. Pp. 14.</ref> The German [[Nuremberg Laws]] of 1935 stripped Jews of citizenship, confiscated property and criminalized sexual relationship and marriage with Aryans. These laws were extended to Romani as Nazi policy towards Roma and Sinti was complicated by pseudo-historic racialist theories, which could be contradictory, namely that the Romani were of Egyptian ancestry. While they considered Romani grossly inferior, they believed the Roma people had some distant \"Aryan\" roots that had been corrupted. The Romani are actually a distinctly European people of considerable Northwestern Indian descent, or what is literally considered to be Aryan. Similarly to European Jews, specifically the Ashkenazi, the Romani people quickly acquired European genetics via enslavement and intermarriage upon their arrival in Europe 1,000 years ago.\n\nIn the [[Protectorate of Bohemia and Moravia]], the Nazi genocide of the Romani was so thorough that it exterminated the majority of [[Bohemian Romani]] speakers, eventually leading to the language's extinction in 1970 with the death of its last known speaker, Hana \u0160ebkov\u00e1. In Denmark, Greece and a small number of other countries, resistance by the native population thwarted planned Nazi deportations and extermination of the Romani. In most conquered countries (e.g., the Baltic states), local cooperation with the Nazis expediated the murder of almost all local Romani. In [[Independent State of Croatia|Croatia]], the Croatian collaborators of the [[Usta\u0161e]], were so vicious only a minor remnant of Croatian Romani (and Jews) survived the killings.\n\n[[File:Bundesarchiv Bild 146-1986-044-08, Stein-Pfalz, Eva Justin bei Sch\u00e4delmessung.jpg|thumb|[[Eva Justin]] checking the facial characteristics of a Romani woman as part of her \"racial studies\"]]\n\nIn 1982, [[West Germany]] formally recognized that genocide had been committed against the Romani.<ref>{{cite book |last=Barany |first=Zoltan D. |year=2002 |title=The East European gypsies: regime change, marginality, and ethnopolitics |publisher=Cambridge University Press |pages=265\u20136 |isbn=978-0-521-00910-2 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=yTylND961ZMC&q=Herzog#v=snippet&q=Herzog&f=false }}</ref> Before this they had often claimed that, unlike Jews, Roma and Sinti were not targeted for racial reasons, but for \"criminal\" reasons, invoking antiziganist stereotype. In modern Holocaust scholarship the Porajmos has been increasingly recognized as a genocide committed simultaneously with the Shoah.<ref>{{cite book |last=Duna |first=William A. |date=1985 |title=Gypsies: A Persecuted Race |publisher=Duna Studios }} Full text in  [http://chgs.umn.edu/histories/victims/romaSinti/gypsies.html Center for Holocaust and Genocide Studies], University of Minnesota.</ref>\n\n===Catholic Church takes responsibility===\nOn March 12, 2000, Pope [[John Paul II]] issued a formal public apology to, among other groups of people affected by Catholic persecution, the Romani people and begged God for forgiveness.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.latimes.com/archives/la-xpm-2000-mar-13-mn-8338-story.html|title=Pope Apologizes for Catholic Sins Past and Present|date=13 March 2000|via=LA Times}}</ref> On June 2, 2019, [[Pope Francis]] acknowledged during a meeting with members of the Romanian Romani community the Catholic Church's history of promoting \"discrimination, segregation and mistreatment\" against [[Romani people]] throughout the world, apologized, and asked the Romani people for forgiveness.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-europe-48490942|title=Pope apologises to Roma for Catholic discrimination|date=2 June 2019|via=www.bbc.com}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|author=Claire Giangrav\u00e8 |url=https://cruxnow.com/pope-in-romania/2019/06/02/pope-apologizes-to-gypsies-for-discrimination-and-segregation/ |title=Pope apologizes to gypsies for 'discrimination and segregation' |publisher=Cruxnow.com |date=2019-06-02 |accessdate=2019-07-01}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.channelnewsasia.com/news/world/pope-francis-asks-forgiveness-for-historical-mistreatment-of-11589638|title=Pope Francis asks forgiveness for historical mistreatment of Roma people|website=CNA}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://apnews.com/4bc86fcdd6f1426fb551ff9e954dbb57|title=Pope apologizes for history of discrimination against Roma|first1=Nicolae|last1=Dumitrache|first2=Nicole|last2=Winfield|date=2 June 2019|website=AP News}}</ref>\n\n==Contemporary anti-Romanyism==\nA report issued by [[Amnesty International]] in 2011 claims that \"systematic discrimination is taking place against up to 10 million Roma across Europe. The organization has documented the failures of governments across the continent to live up to their obligations.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.amnesty.org/en/documents/eur01/005/2011/en/|title=Amnesty International \u2013 International Roma Day 2011 Stories, Background Information and video material|date=7 April 2011|publisher=Amnesty International|accessdate=15 May 2011|location=AI Index: EUR 01/005/2011}}</ref>\n \nAnti-Romanyism has continued well into the 2000s, particularly in [[Slovakia]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://web.amnesty.org/wire/February2002/Europe_Roma |title=Amnesty International |publisher=Web.amnesty.org |accessdate=17 May 2012 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20071012191514/http://web.amnesty.org/wire/February2002/Europe_Roma |archivedate=12 October 2007 |df=dmy }}</ref> [[Hungary]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.csmonitor.com/2008/0213/p07s02-woeu.html|title=Hungary's anti-Roma militia grows|author=The Christian Science Monitor|work=The Christian Science Monitor}}</ref> [[Slovenia]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.humanrightspoint.si/node/12 |title=roma &#124; Human Rights Press Point |publisher=Humanrightspoint.si |accessdate=17 May 2012 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120310074602/http://www.humanrightspoint.si/node/12 |archivedate=10 March 2012 }}</ref> and [[Kosovo]].<ref>{{cite web|author=Gesellschaft fuer bedrohte Voelker \u2013 Society for Threatened Peoples |url=http://www.gfbv.de/inhaltsDok.php?id=612 |title=Roma and Ashkali in Kosovo: Persecuted, driven out, poisoned |publisher=Gfbv.de |accessdate=17 May 2012 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070806163105/http://www.gfbv.de/inhaltsDok.php?id=612 |archivedate=6 August 2007 |df=dmy }}</ref> In Bulgaria, Professor Ognian Saparev has written articles stating that 'Gypsies' are culturally inclined towards theft and use their [[ethnic minority|minority]] status to 'blackmail' the majority.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bghelsinki.org/en/news/bg/single/mp-publishes-inflammatory-article-against-the-roma/|title=MP publishes inflammatory article against the Roma|work=bghelsinki.org}}</ref> [[European Union]] officials censured both the Czech Republic and Slovakia in 2007 for forcibly segregating Romani children from regular schools.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.iht.com/articles/ap/2007/11/15/europe/EU-GEN-EU-Roma-Discrimination.php |title=IHT.com |publisher=IHT.com |date=29 March 2009 |accessdate=17 May 2012}}</ref>\n\nThe Council of Europe [[Commissioner for Human Rights]], [[Thomas Hammarberg]], has been an outspoken critic of anti-Romanyism. In August 2008, Hammarberg noted that \"today's rhetoric against the Roma is very similar to the one used by [[Nazis]] and fascists before the mass killings started in the thirties and forties. Once more, it is argued that the Roma are a threat to safety and public health. No distinction is made between a few criminals and the overwhelming majority of the Roma population. This is shameful and dangerous\".<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.coe.int/t/commissioner/Viewpoints/080818_en.asp |title=Viewpoints by Council of Europe Commissioner for Human Rights |publisher=Coe.int |accessdate=17 May 2012 |archive-url=https://archive.is/20120630002157/www.coe.int/t/commissioner/Viewpoints/080818_en.asp |archive-date=30 June 2012 |url-status=dead |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n\nAccording to the latest [[Human Rights First]] [[Hate Crime]] Survey, Romanis routinely suffer assaults in city streets and other public places as they travel to and from homes and markets. In a number of serious cases of violence against them, attackers have also sought out whole families in their homes or whole communities in settlements predominantly housing Romanis. The widespread patterns of violence are sometimes directed both at causing immediate harm to Romanis, without distinction between adults, the elderly, and small children and physically eradicating the presence of Romani people in towns and cities in several European countries.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.humanrightsfirst.org/discrimination/pages.aspx?id=85 |title=Human Rights First Report on Roma |publisher=Humanrightsfirst.org |accessdate=17 May 2012}}</ref>\n\n=== Public opinion ===\nThe extent of negative attitudes towards Romani people varies across different parts of Europe.\n{{bar box\n|title=Unfavorable views of Roma, 2019<ref>{{cite news |title=European Public Opinion Three Decades After the Fall of Communism \u2014 6. Minority groups |url=https://www.pewresearch.org/global/2019/10/14/minority-groups/ |work=Pew Research Center |date=14 October 2019}}</ref>\n|titlebar=#ddd\n|left1='''Country'''\n|right1='''Percent'''\n|width=400px\n|bars=\n{{bar percent|[[Romania]]|peru|94}}\n{{bar percent|[[Italy]]|peru|83}}\n{{bar percent|[[Slovakia]]|peru|76}}\n{{bar percent|[[Greece]]|peru|72}}\n{{bar percent|[[Bulgaria]]|peru|68}}\n{{bar percent|[[Czech Republic]]|peru|66}}\n{{bar percent|[[Lithuania]]|peru|61}}\n{{bar percent|[[Hungary]]|peru|61}}\n{{bar percent|[[Ukraine]]|peru|54}}\n{{bar percent|[[Russia]]|peru|52}}\n{{bar percent|[[Poland]]|peru|51}}\n{{bar percent|[[France]]|darkorange|44}}\n{{bar percent|[[Spain]]|darkorange|40}}\n{{bar percent|[[Germany]]|gold|37}}\n}}\n\n===European Union===\n[[File:Prejudice against Roma, Trans and Muslim people (EU, 2015).svg|thumb|upright=2|According to a survey conducted by the [[European Commission]] in 2015 20% of the respondents would be completely uncomfortable about working with a Roma person ({{legend-inline|#cab2d6|violet}}), compared with 17% with a [[transgender]] or [[transsexual]] person ({{legend-inline|#b2df8a|green}}) and 13% with a [[Muslim]] person ({{legend-inline|#fdbf6f|orange}}). This puts Roma people as the most discriminated minority in Europe.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Bona |first1=Marzia |title=How widespread is anti-Roma prejudice? |url=https://www.europeandatajournalism.eu/eng/News/Data-news/How-widespread-is-anti-Roma-prejudice |accessdate=29 August 2018 |work=OBC Transeuropa/EDJNet |date=2 August 2018}}</ref>]]\nThe practice of placing Romani students in segregated schools or classes remains widespread in countries across Europe.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.errc.org/cikk.php?cikk=2743|title=The Impact of Legislation and Policies on School Segregation of Romani Children |year=2007|publisher=European Roma Rights Centre|page=8|accessdate=21 July 2009| archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20090729181110/http://www.errc.org/cikk.php?cikk=2743| archivedate= 29 July 2009 | url-status= live}}</ref> Many Romani children have been channeled into all-Romani schools that offer inferior quality education and are sometimes in poor physical condition or into segregated all-Romani or predominantly Romani classes within mixed schools.<ref name=\"eumap\">{{cite web\n| year = 2007\n| format = PDF\n| url = http://www.eumap.org/topics/minority/reports/roma_education/report/vol1.pdf\n| archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070407092622/http://www.eumap.org/topics/minority/reports/roma_education/report/vol1.pdf\n| archivedate=7 April 2007\n| title = Equal access to quality education for Roma, Volume 1\n| pages = 18\u201320, 187, 212\u2013213, 358\u2013361\n| publisher = Open Society Institute \u2013 EU Monitoring and Advocacy Program (EUMAP)\n}}</ref> Many Romani children are sent to classes for pupils with learning disabilities. They are also sent to so-called \"delinquent schools\", with a variety of human rights abuses.<ref name=\"eumap\" />\n\nRomani in European cities are often accused of crimes such as [[pickpocketing]]. In 2009, a documentary by the [[BBC]] called ''Gypsy Child Thieves'' showed Romani children being kidnapped and abused by Romani gangs from Romania. The children were often held locked in sheds during the nights and sent to steal during the days.<ref name=\"BBC Gypsy Gangs\" /> However, ''[[Chachipe]]'', a charity which works for the human rights of Romani people, has claimed that this programme promoted \"popular stereotypes against Roma which contribute to their marginalisation and provide legitimacy to racist attacks against them\" and that in suggesting that [[begging]] and [[child exploitation]] was \"intrinsic to the Romany culture\", the programme was \"highly damaging\" for the Romani people. However, the charity accepted that some of the incidents that were detailed in the programme in fact took place.<ref name=IRR1>{{cite web|title=BBC documentary about Roma children sparks outrage|url=http://www.irr.org.uk/news/bbc-documentary-about-roma-children-sparks-outrage/|publisher=Institute for Race Relations|accessdate=2 May 2015|date=17 December 2009|author=Miranda Wilson}}</ref>\n\nThe documentary speculated that in [[Milan]], [[Italy]] a single Romani child was able to steal as much as \u20ac12,000 in a month; and that there were as many as 50 of such abused Romani children operating in the city. The film went on to describe the link between poverty, discrimination, crime and exploitation.<ref name=\"BBC Gypsy Gangs\">{{cite news| url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/8226580.stm | work=BBC News | first=Sam | last=Bagnall | title=How Gypsy gangs use child thieves | date=2 September 2009}}</ref>\n\nA United Nations study<ref>{{cite book|title=Avoiding the Dependence Trap: A Regional Human Development Report|url=http://roma.undp.sk/online.php|isbn=92-1-126153-8|publisher=United Nations Development Programme|date=December 2002|first=Andrey|last=Ivanov|chapter=7|chapterurl=http://roma.undp.sk/reports_contents.php?parent_id=1&id=229|access-date=29 December 2008|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20081205182000/http://roma.undp.sk/online.php|archive-date=5 December 2008|url-status=dead|df=dmy-all}}</ref> found that Romani people living in European countries are arrested for robbery much more often than other groups. [[Amnesty International]]<ref>{{cite web|title=Anti-Roma racism in Europe |first=Julie |last=Denesha |publisher=Amnesty International |url=http://web.amnesty.org/wire/February2002/Europe_Roma |date=February 2002 |accessdate=26 August 2007 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20071012191514/http://web.amnesty.org/wire/February2002/Europe_Roma |archivedate=12 October 2007 |df=dmy }}</ref> and Romani rights groups such as the ''Union Romani'' blame widespread [[institutionalised racism]] and persecution.<ref>{{cite web|title=Rromani People: Present Situation in Europe|url=http://www.unionromani.org/pueblo_in.htm#situacion|publisher=Union Romani|accessdate=26 August 2007| archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20070820014003/http://www.unionromani.org/pueblo_in.htm| archivedate= 20 August 2007 | url-status= live}}</ref> In July 2008, a [[Business Week]] feature found the region's Romani population to be a \"missed economic opportunity\".<ref>{{cite web|author=S. Adam Cardais |url=http://www.businessweek.com/globalbiz/content/jul2008/gb20080728_953451.htm?chan=globalbiz_europe+index+page_top+stories |title=Businessweek.com |publisher=Businessweek.com |date=28 July 2008 |accessdate=17 May 2012}}</ref> Hundreds of people from [[Ostravice]], in the [[Beskydy]] mountains in Czech Republic, signed a petition against a plan to move Romani families from [[Ostrava]] city to their home town, fearing the Romani invasion as well as their schools not being able to cope with the influx of Romani children.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://zpravy.aktualne.cz/village-rallies-against-roma-influx/r~i:article:619339/|title=Village rallies against Roma influx &#124; Aktu\u00e1ln\u011b.cz|date=15 October 2008|website=Aktu\u00e1ln\u011b.cz - V\u00edte, co se pr\u00e1v\u011b d\u011bje}}</ref>\n\nIn 2009, the UN's anti-racism panel charged that \"Gypsies suffer widespread racism in European Union\".<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2009/apr/23/eu-roma-racism-discrimination|title=Gypsies suffer widespread racism in European Union|date=23 April 2009|newspaper=Guardian |accessdate=26 August 2010 | location=London | first=Ian | last=Traynor| archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20100809025320/http://www.guardian.co.uk/world/2009/apr/23/eu-roma-racism-discrimination| archivedate= 9 August 2010 | url-status= live}}</ref> The EU has launched a program entitled [[Decade of Roma Inclusion]] to combat this and other problems.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.romadecade.org/|title=\u671f\u9593\u5de5\u30d0\u30a4\u30d6\u30eb\u3010\u30d0\u30a4\u30c8\u30fb\u8ee2\u8077\u6c42\u4eba\u691c\u7d22\u306e\u30b3\u30da\u30eb\u3011|website=Romadecade.org|accessdate=24 January 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20051126163332/http://www.romadecade.org/|archive-date=26 November 2005|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\n====Austria====\nOn 5 February 1995, [[Franz Fuchs]] killed four Romani in [[Oberwart]] with a [[pipe bomb]] [[improvised explosive device]] which was attached to a sign that read \"Roma zur\u00fcck nach Indien\" (\"Romani back to [[India]]\"). It was the worst racial terror attack in post-war Austria, and was Fuchs's first fatal attack.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1995/02/21/world/attack-on-austrian-gypsies-deepens-fear-of-neo-nazis.html|title=Attack on Austrian Gypsies Deepens Fear of Neo-Nazis|first=Alan|last=Cowell|date=21 February 1995|via=NYTimes.com}}</ref>\n\n====Bulgaria====\n[[File:Sap34.jpg|thumb|left|Antiziganist protests in [[Sofia]], 2011]]\n\nIn 2011 in Bulgaria, the widespread anti-Romanyism culminated in [[2011 Bulgaria antiziganist protests|anti-Roma protests]] in response to the murder of Angel Petrov on the orders of Kiril Rashkov, a Roma leader in the village of [[Katunitsa]]. In the subsequent trial, the killer, Simeon Yosifov, was sentenced to 17 years in jail.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/SB10001424052970204226204576599331889606992 |title=Anti-Roma Protests Escalate - WSJ.com |publisher=Online.wsj.com |date=29 September 2011 |accessdate=17 May 2012}}</ref> As of May 2012, an appeal was under way.\n\nProtests continued on 1 October in Sofia, with 2000 Bulgarians marching against the Romani and what they viewed to be the \"impunity and the corruption\" of the political elite in the country.<ref name=\"BBC10-1\">{{cite news|title=Bulgarian rally links Roma to organised crime|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-europe-15140291|work=[[BBC News]]|date=1 October 2011|accessdate=2 October 2011}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Boyko Borisov EPP 2014.jpg|thumb|Bulgarian prime minister [[Boyko Borissov|Borissov]] referred to Roma as \"bad human material\"<ref name=\"ndt1.com\">[http://www.ndt1.com/article.php/20090205212634848 \u0418\u0437\u043a\u0430\u0437\u0432\u0430\u043d\u0435 \u043d\u0430 \u0411\u043e\u0439\u043a\u043e \u0411\u043e\u0440\u0438\u0441\u043e\u0432 \u0432 \u0427\u0438\u043a\u0430\u0433\u043e&nbsp;\u2013 \u0435\u043c\u0438\u0433\u0440\u0430\u043d\u0442\u0441\u043a\u0430 \u0432\u0435\u0440\u0441\u0438\u044f] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110714162327/http://www.ndt1.com/article.php/20090205212634848 |date=14 July 2011 }} Chicago press conference transcription in Bulgarian</ref><ref name=\"Chicago audio record\">[http://www.segabg.com/data/BBorisovChicago.mp3 Chicago audio record] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110906034411/http://www.segabg.com/data/BBorisovChicago.mp3 |date=6 September 2011 }} ('''Dead Link''')</ref><ref name=\"telegraph.co.uk\">[https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/worldnews/europe/bulgaria/4531391/Mayor-of-Sofia-brands-Roma-Turks-and-retirees-bad-human-material.html Mayor of Sofia brands Roma, Turks and retirees 'bad human material'], Telegraph.co.uk, 6 February 2009</ref><ref name=\"novinite.com\">[http://www.novinite.com/view_news.php?id=100987 Sofia Mayor to Bulgarian Expats: We Are Left with Bad Human Material Back Home] Sofia Mayor to Bulgarian Expats: We Are Left with Bad Human Material Back Home</ref>]]\n[[Volen Siderov]], leader of the far-right [[National Union Attack|Ataka]] party and presidential candidate, spoke to a crowd at the Presidential Palace in Sofia, calling for the death penalty to be reinstated as well as Romani ghettos to be dismantled.<ref name=\"BBC10-1\"/>\n\nMany of the organized protests were accompanied by ethnic clashes and racist violence against Romani. The protesters shouted racist slogans like \"Gypsies into soap\" and \"Slaughter the Turks!\"<ref name=\"nytimes.com\">[https://www.nytimes.com/2011/09/28/world/europe/anti-roma-demonstrations-spread-across-bulgaria.html?_r=0 Anti-Roma Demonstrations Spread Across Bulgaria], The New York Times</ref> Many protesters were arrested for public order offenses.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.dnevnik.bg/bulgaria/2011/09/27/1163572_mvr_za_protestite_za_katunica_sred_nai-agresivnite/|title=\u0411\u044a\u043b\u0433\u0430\u0440\u0438\u044f - \u041c\u0412\u0420 \u0437\u0430 \u043f\u0440\u043e\u0442\u0435\u0441\u0442\u0438\u0442\u0435 \u0437\u0430 \u041a\u0430\u0442\u0443\u043d\u0438\u0446\u0430: \u0421\u0440\u0435\u0434 \u043d\u0430\u0439-\u0430\u0433\u0440\u0435\u0441\u0438\u0432\u043d\u0438\u0442\u0435 \u0431\u044f\u0445\u0430 12-13-\u0433\u043e\u0434\u0438\u0448\u043d\u0438 - Dnevnik.bg|work=www.dnevnik.bg}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.trud.bg/Article.asp?ArticleId=1055699|title=\u0422\u0440\u0443\u0434|website=\u0422\u0440\u0443\u0434|access-date=13 July 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131224111208/http://www.trud.bg/Article.asp?ArticleId=1055699|archive-date=24 December 2013|url-status=dead|df=dmy-all}}</ref> The news media labelled the protests as anti-Romani [[Pogroms]].<ref name=\"nytimes.com\"/>\n\nFurthermore, in 2009, Bulgarian prime minister [[Boyko Borissov|Borissov]] referred to Roma as \"bad human material\".<ref name=\"ndt1.com\"/><ref name=\"Chicago audio record\"/><ref name=\"telegraph.co.uk\"/><ref name=\"novinite.com\"/> The vice-president of the [[Party of European Socialists]], [[Jan Marinus Wiersma]] claimed that he \"has already crossed the invisible line between [[right-wing populism]] and extremism\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.socialistgroup.eu/gpes/public/detail.htm?id=116844&section=NER&category=NEWS |title=Challenge to EPP over leader's statement on bad human material |publisher=Socialistgroup.eu |date=6 February 2009 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120323050511/http://www.socialistgroup.eu/gpes/public/detail.htm?id=116844&section=NER&category=NEWS |archivedate=23 March 2012 }}</ref>\n\nIn 2019 pogroms against the Roma community in [[Gabrovo]] broke out after 3 young Romani have been caught stealing in a shop<ref>https://intellinews.com/bulgarian-pm-s-intervention-fails-to-stop-anti-roma-protests-in-gabrovo-159595/</ref>. The following wave of riots saw incidents of violence and arson of two houses where Roma people were living, leading to the majority of the towns Roma community fleeing over night leaving behind their homes to be lynched. Roma rights NGO said that gendarmerie were deployed near places where there were Roma houses, but the police had \u201cshown frustration, urging more Gabrovo Roma to spend the next few days with relatives in other municipalities\u201d. Many Roma have never returned as their homes were burned down and their property destroyed.<ref>https://sofiaglobe.com/2019/04/13/many-roma-have-fled-gabrovo-as-bulgarian-town-braces-for-another-no-to-aggression-protest/</ref>\n\n====Czech Republic====\n[[File:Z\u00e1kaz vstupu potuln\u00fdch cik\u00e1n\u016f a tul\u00e1k\u016f.jpg|thumb|Sign banning entry of itinerant Gypsies and rovers, 1920s]]\n{{Further|Romani people in the Czech Republic}}\nRoma make up 2\u20133% of population in the [[Czech Republic]]. According to \u0158\u00ed\u010dan (1998), Roma make up more than 60% of Czech prisoners and about 20\u201330% earn their livelihood in illegal ways, such as procuring prostitution, trafficking and other property crimes.<ref>{{cite book|last=\u0158\u00ed\u010dan|first=Pavel|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=qtgmAAAAMAAJ&q=pavel+%C5%99%C3%AD%C4%8Dan+s+romy+%C5%BE%C3%ADt+budeme&dq=pavel+%C5%99%C3%AD%C4%8Dan+s+romy+%C5%BE%C3%ADt+budeme&hl=cs&ei=9V52TcqJK5SI4Aac0tyCCA&sa=X&oi=book_result&ct=result&resnum=1&ved=0CCgQ6AEwAA|title=S Romy \u017e\u00edt budeme \u2013 jde o to jak: d\u011bjiny, sou\u010dasn\u00e1 situace, ko\u0159eny probl\u00e9m\u016f, nad\u011bje spole\u010dn\u00e9 budoucnosti|publisher=Port\u00e1l|year=1998|isbn=80-7178-250-5|location=Praha|pages=58\u201363}}</ref> Roma are thus more than 20 times overrepresented in Czech prisons than their population share would suggest.\n\nAccording to 2010 survey, 83% of Czechs consider Roma asocial and 45% of Czechs would like to expel them from the Czech Republic.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://zpravy.idnes.cz/cesi-propadaji-anticikanismu-kazdy-druhy-tu-romy-nechce-zjistil-pruzkum-1qx-/domaci.asp?c=A101209_161615_domaci_js|title=\u010ce\u0161i propadaj\u00ed anticik\u00e1nismu, ka\u017ed\u00fd druh\u00fd tu Romy nechce, zjistil pr\u016fzkum|author=Ji\u0159\u00ed \u0160\u0165astn\u00fd|date=8 February 2012|publisher=Zpravy.idnes.cz|accessdate=17 May 2012}}</ref> A 2011 poll, which followed after a number of brutal attacks by Romani perpetrators against majority population victims, revealed that 44% of Czechs are afraid of Roma people.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.tyden.cz/rubriky/domaci/romsky-bloger-nekteri-romove-se-chovaji-jako-blazni_216270.html|title=Romsky bloger nekteri romove se chovaji jako blazni|language=Czech|accessdate=1 November 2011}}</ref> The majority of the [[Czech people]] do not want to have Romanis as neighbours (almost 90%, more than any other group<ref>{{cite web|url=https://translate.google.com/translate?u=http%3A%2F%2Fwww.romea.cz%2Findex.php%3Fid%3Dservis%2Fz2005_0318&hl=cs&ie=UTF8&sl=cs&tl=en|title=Czech don't want Roma as neighbours|language=Czech|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120201133920/http://translate.google.com/translate?u=http%3A%2F%2Fwww.romea.cz%2Findex.php%3Fid%3Dservis%2Fz2005_0318&hl=cs&ie=UTF8&sl=cs&tl=en|archive-date=1 February 2012|accessdate=15 April 2007|df=dmy-all}}</ref>) seeing them as thieves and social parasites. In spite of long waiting time for a child adoption, Romani children from orphanages are almost never adopted by Czech couples.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.radio.cz/en/article/88089|title=What is keeping children in orphanages when so many people want to adopt? \u2013 07-02-2007 \u2013 Radio Prague|publisher=Radio.cz|accessdate=17 May 2012}}</ref> After the [[Velvet Revolution]] in 1989 the jobs traditionally employing Romanis either disappeared or were taken over by immigrant workers.\n\nThe Romanis are at the centre of the agenda of far-right groups in the Czech Republic, which spread anti-Romanyism. Among highly publicized cases was the [[V\u00edtkov arson attack of 2009]], in which four right-wing extremists seriously injured a three-year-old Romani girl. The public responded by donating money as well as presents to the family, who were able to buy a new house from the donations, while the perpetrators were sentenced to 18 and 22 years in prison.\n \nIn January 2010, Amnesty International launched a report titled ''Injustice Renamed: Discrimination in Education of Roma persists in the Czech Republic''.<ref>[https://www.amnesty.org/en/documents/eur71/003/2009/en/ ''Injustice Renamed: Discrimination in Education of Roma persists in the Czech Republic''] Amnesty International report, January 2010</ref> According to the [[BBC]], it was Amnesty's view that while cosmetic changes had been introduced by the authorities, little genuine improvement in addressing discrimination against Romani children has occurred over recent years.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/europe/8456882.stm|title=Amnesty says Czech schools still fail Roma Gypsies|date=13 January 2010|work=BBC News|accessdate=14 January 2010|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100114052029/http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/europe/8456882.stm|archivedate=14 January 2010}}</ref>\n\nThe 2019 [[Pew Research Center|Pew Research poll]] poll found that 66% of Czechs held unfavorable views of Roma.\n\n====Denmark====\nIn [[Denmark]], there was much controversy when the city of [[Helsing\u00f8r]] decided to put all Romani students in special classes in its [[Public school (government funded)|public school]]s. The classes were later abandoned after it was determined that they were discriminatory, and the Romanis were put back in regular classes.<ref>{{cite web\n| date = 18 January 2006\n| url = http://www.dr.dk/Regioner/Kbh/Nyheder/Politik/20060118073049.htm\n| title = Roma-politik igen i s\u00f8gelyset\n| publisher = DR Radio P4\n| language = Danish\n}}</ref>\n\n====France====\n{{Further|French Romani repatriation}}\nFrance has come under criticism for its treatment of Roma. In the summer of 2010, French authorities demolished at least 51 illegal Roma camps and began the process of repatriating their residents to their countries of origin.<ref>{{cite news | url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-europe-11020429|title=France sends Roma Gypsies back to Romania | date=20 August 2010 | publisher=BBC |accessdate=22 August 2010| archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20100821223510/http://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-europe-11020429| archivedate= 21 August 2010 | url-status= live}}</ref> The French government has been accused of perpetrating these actions to pursue its political agenda.<ref>{{cite news|title=France Begins Controversial Roma Deportations |date=19 August 2010 |url=http://www.spiegel.de/international/europe/0,1518,712701,00.html |work=Der Spiegel |accessdate=20 August 2010 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100820123925/http://www.spiegel.de/international/europe/0%2C1518%2C712701%2C00.html |archivedate=20 August 2010 |url-status=live }}</ref>  In July 2013, [[Jean-Marie Le Pen]], a very controversial far-right politician and founder of the [[National Front (France)|National Front]] party, had a lawsuit filed against him by the European Roma and Travellers Forum, SOS Racisme and the French Union of Travellers Association after he publicly called France's Roma population \"smelly\" and \"rash-inducing\", claiming his comments violated French law on inciting racial hatred.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.ibtimes.co.uk/roma-travellers-group-sue-far-right-leader-491937|title=Jean-Marie Le Pen Sued for Calling Roma Gypsies 'Smelly'|newspaper=International Business Times|author=Gianluca Mezzofiore|date=18 July 2013|accessdate=20 July 2014}}</ref>\n\n====Germany====\nAfter 2005 Germany deported some 50,000 people, mainly Romanis, to Kosovo. They were asylum seekers who fled the country during the [[Kosovo War]]. The people were deported after living more than 10 years in Germany. The deportations were highly controversial: many were children and obtained education in Germany, spoke German as their primary language and considered themselves to be Germans.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2005/05/19/international/europe/19kosovo.html|title=Germany Sending Gypsy Refugees Back to Kosovo|work=[[The New York Times]]|date=19 May 2005}}</ref>\n\n====Hungary====\nHungary has seen escalating violence against the Romani people. On 23 February 2009, a Romani man and his five-year-old son were shot dead in [[Tat\u00e1rszentgy\u00f6rgy]] village southeast of [[Budapest]] as they were fleeing their burning house which was set alight by a petrol bomb. The dead man's two other children suffered serious burns. Suspects were arrested and are currently on trial.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://index.hu/belfold/2011/03/25/egy_megdobbento_gyilkossagsorozat_reszletei/|title=Egy megd\u00f6bbent\u0151 gyilkoss\u00e1gsorozat r\u00e9szletei|date=25 March 2011|accessdate=25 March 2011|publisher=Index}}</ref>\n\nIn 2012, [[Vikt\u00f3ria Moh\u00e1csi]], 2004\u20132009 Hungarian [[Member of European Parliament]] of Romani ethnicity, asked for asylum in Canada after previously requesting police protection at home from serious threats she was receiving from hate groups.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.romea.cz/english/index.php?id=detail&detail=2007_3142|title=Hungarian Roma activist, former member of European Parliament emigrates to Canada|work=romea.cz}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.politics.hu/20130616/hungarian-mep-to-canada-asylum-seeker-a-romas-long-trek/|title=Hungarian MEP to Canada asylum seeker: A Roma\u2019s long trek|work=Politics.hu|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131230234856/http://www.politics.hu/20130616/hungarian-mep-to-canada-asylum-seeker-a-romas-long-trek/|archive-date=30 December 2013|access-date=28 December 2013}}</ref>\n\n====Italy====\n{{see also|Anti-Roma sentiment in Italy}}\nIn 2007 and 2008, following the brutal rape and subsequent murder of a woman in Rome at the hands of a young man from a local Romani encampment,<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2007/nov/02/italy.international |title=Italian woman's murder prompts expulsion threat to Romanians |newspaper=The Guardian |date=2 November 2007 | location=London | first=John | last=Hooper}}</ref> the Italian government started a crackdown on illegal Roma and Sinti campsites in the country.\n\nIn May 2008 Romani camps in Naples were attacked and set on fire by local residents.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/low/world/europe/7423165.stm |title=Italy condemned for 'racism wave'|first=Unknown|last=Unknown|date=28 May 2008|work=BBC News|publisher=BBC}}</ref> In July 2008, a high court in Italy overthrew the conviction of defendants who had publicly demanded the expulsion of Romanis from [[Verona]] in 2001 and reportedly ruled that \"it is acceptable to discriminate against Roma on the grounds that they are thieves\".<ref name=\"legalpredj\">[https://www.theguardian.com/world/2008/jul/01/italy Italy: Court inflames Roma discrimination row] ''[[The Guardian]]'' Retrieved 17 July 2008</ref> One of those freed was [[Flavio Tosi]], Verona's mayor and an official of the anti-immigrant [[Lega Nord]].<ref name=\"legalpredj\" /> The decision came during a \"nationwide clampdown\" on Romanis by Italian prime minister [[Silvio Berlusconi]]. The previous week, Berlusconi's interior minister [[Roberto Maroni]] had declared that all Romanis in Italy, including children, would be fingerprinted.<ref name=\"legalpredj\" />\n\nIn 2011 the development of a National Inclusion Strategy Rom Dei Sinti and Caminanti <ref>{{cite web|url=http://ec.europa.eu/justice/discrimination/files/roma_italy_strategy_it.pdf|format=PDF|title=Strategia Nazionale D'Inclusione Dei Rom, Dei Sinti e Dei Caminanti Attuazione Comunicazione Commissione Europea N.173/2011|website=Ec.europa.eu|accessdate=24 January 2018}}</ref> under the supervision of European Commission has defined the presence of Romani camps as an unacceptable condition.\nAs already underlined by many international organizations, the prevalent positioning of the RSC communities in the c.d \"nomad camps\" fuels segregation and hinders every process of social integration / inclusion; but even where other more stable housing modalities have been found, forms of ghettoization and self-segregation are found, which hinder the process of integration / social inclusion.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://ec.europa.eu/justice/discrimination/files/roma_italy_strategy_it.pdf|page=15|format=PDF|title=Strategia Nazionale D'Inclusione Dei Rom, Dei Sinti e Dei Caminanti Attuazione Comunicazione Commissione Europea N.173/2011|website=Ec.europa.eu|accessdate=24 January 2018}}</ref>\n\n====Romania====\n{{Further|Romani people in Romania|Slavery in Romania}}\nRoma make up 3.3% of population in [[Romania]]. Prejudice against Romanis is common amongst the Romanians, who characterize them as thieves, dirty and lazy.<ref name=\"enar\">Delia-Luiza Nit\u0103, [http://cms.horus.be/files/99935/MediaArchive/national/Romania%20-%20SR%202008.pdf ENAR Shadow Report 2008: Racism in Romania], [[European Network Against Racism]]</ref> A 2000 EU report about Romani said that ''in Romania... the continued high levels of discrimination are a serious concern...and progress has been limited to programmes aimed at improving access to education''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://ec.europa.eu/employment_social/fundamental_rights/pdf/pubst/roma04_en.pdf |title=The Situation of Roma in an Enlarged European Union |publisher=European Commission |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090305133536/http://ec.europa.eu/employment_social/fundamental_rights/pdf/pubst/roma04_en.pdf |archivedate=5 March 2009 |df=dmy }}</ref> A survey of the Pro Democra\u0163ia association in Romania revealed that 94% of the questioned persons believe that the [[Romanian nationality law|Romanian citizenship]] should be revoked to the ethnic Romani who commit crimes abroad.<ref>[http://www.evz.ro/detalii/stiri/romii-vor-fapte-nu-vorbe-891619.html Evenimentul Zilei. 7 April 2010]. Evz.ro. Retrieved on 2012-01-15.</ref>\n\nIn 2009-2010, a media campaign followed by a parliamentarian initiative asked the Romanian Parliament to accept a proposal to change back the official name of country's Roma (adopted in 2000) to ''\u021aigan'', the traditional and colloquial [[Romanian language|Romanian]] name for Romani, in order to avoid the possible confusion among the international community between the words Roma, which refers to the Romani ethnic minority, and Romania.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://jurnalul.ro/campaniile-jurnalul/tigan-in-loc-de-rom/propunere-jurnalul-national-tigan-in-loc-de-rom-145427.html|title=Propunere Jurnalul Na\u0163ional:|website=Jurnalul.ro|accessdate=24 January 2018}}</ref> The Romanian government supported the move on the grounds that many countries in the European Union use a [[names of the Romani people|variation of the word ''\u021aigan'']] to refer to their Gypsy populations. The Romanian upper house, the Senate, rejected the proposal.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://content.time.com/time/world/article/0,8599,2035862,00.html|title=Romania's Government Moves to Rename the Roma|first=Rupert Wolfe|last=Murray|date=8 December 2010|website=Content.time.com|accessdate=24 January 2018|via=content.time.com}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.balkaninsight.com/en/article/disputes-over-proper-word-for-romania-s-minority|title=Romania Declines to Turn Roma Into 'Gypsies'|website=Balkaninsight.com|accessdate=24 January 2018}}</ref>\n\nSeveral anti-Romani [[riot]]s occurred in recent decades, notable of which being the [[H\u0103d\u0103reni riots]] of 1993, in which a mob of Romanians and Hungarians, in response to the killing of a Romanian by a Gypsy, burnt down 13 houses belonging to the Gypsies, lynched three Gypsies and forced 130 people to flee the village.<ref name=\"hadareni\">[https://query.nytimes.com/gst/fullpage.html?res=9F0CE6D8133AF934A15753C1A965958260&sec=&spon=&pagewanted=all \"Hadareni Journal; Death Is a Neighbor, and the Gypsies Are Terrified\"], in ''[[The New York Times]]'', 27 October 1993</ref>\n\nIn [[Baia Mare]], Mayor [[C\u0103t\u0103lin Chereche\u0219]] announced the building of a 3 metre high, 100 metre long concrete wall to divide the buildings in which the Gypsy community lives from the rest of the city and bring \"order and discipline\" into the area.<ref>[http://www.setimes.com/cocoon/setimes/xhtml/en_GB/features/setimes/features/2011/07/18/feature-04 \"Roma community segregation still plaguing Romania\"], ''Setimes'', 18 July 2011</ref>\n\nThe [[manele]], their modern music style, was prohibited in some cities of Romania in public transport<ref>{{cite web|title=Prim\u0103ria de decis: Manelele lui Gu\u0163\u0103 \u015fi Salam sunt interzise la Gala\u0163i|url=http://www.adevarul.ro/locale/galati/Manelele_lui_Guta_si_Salam-interzise_la_Galati_0_216578447.html|work=Stiri din Galati|publisher=Adev\u0103rul Holding|accessdate=29 July 2012|author=Corina Mis\u0103il\u0103, Vali Trufa\u015fu|date=28 February 2010}}</ref> and taxis,<ref>{{cite web|title=Interzis la manele \u00een taxi!|url=http://www.libertatea.ro/detalii/articol/interzis-la-manele-in-taxi-282232.html|work=Liber Tatea|publisher=Ringier Romania Toate|accessdate=29 July 2012|language=Romanian|date=31 March 2010}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Fumatul \u015fi manelele, interzise \u00een taxiurile bra\u015fovene|url=http://www.adevarul.ro/life/Fumatul-manelele-interzise-taxiurile-brasovene_0_42595952.html|work=Adev\u0103rul.ro|publisher=Adev\u0103rul Holding|accessdate=29 July 2012|author=Sebastian Dan|language=Romanian|date=14 March 2007}}</ref> that action being justified by bus and taxi companies as being for passengers' comfort and a neutral ambience, acceptable for all passengers. However, those actions had been characterised by Speranta Radulescu, a professor of ethno-musicology at the [[Bucharest Conservatory]], as \"a defect of Romanian society\".<ref>{{cite news|title=\"Manele\", the Most Contested Music of Today|url=http://www.rri.ro/art.shtml?lang=1&sec=27&art=217582|accessdate=23 June 2012|newspaper=Radio Romania International|date=6 February 2012|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120624063402/http://www.rri.ro/art.shtml?lang=1&sec=27&art=217582|archive-date=24 June 2012|url-status=dead}}</ref> There were also a few criticisms of Professor Dr. Ioan Bradu Iamandescu's experimental study, which linked the listening of \"manele\" to an increased level of aggressiveness and low self-control and suggested a correlation between preference for that music style and low cognitive skills.<ref>{{cite web|title=Prof. dr. Ioan Bradu Iamandescu: \"Pe muzic\u0103 baroc\u0103, neuronii cap\u0103t\u0103 un ritm specific geniilor\"|url=http://www.adevarul.ro/life/sanatate/Prof-_dr-_Ioan_Bradu_Iamandescu-_-Pe_muzica_baroca-neuronii_capata_un_ritm_specific_geniilor_0_551345213.html|work=Adev\u0103rul.ro|publisher=Adev\u0103rul Holding|accessdate=29 July 2012|author=Mariana Minea|language=Romanian|date=10 September 2011}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Cum se comporta creierul cand asculta manele|url=http://stirileprotv.ro/stiri/social/cum-se-comporta-creierul-cand-asculta-manele.html|work=Stirileprotv.ro|publisher=Stirileprotv.ro|accessdate=29 July 2012|language=Romanian}}</ref>\n\nIn 2009, pop singer [[Madonna (entertainer)|Madonna]] defended Romani people during her [[concert]] in Bucharest.<ref>[http://www.mtv.com/news/1619705/madonna-booed-after-standing-up-for-gypsies-in-romania/ Madonna Booed After Standing Up For Gypsies in Romania]</ref>\n\n====Sweden====\nRoma are one of the five official national minorities in Sweden.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://sweden.se/society/national-minorities-in-sweden/|title=National Minorities in Sweden|publisher=Swedish Institute|website=sweden.se|accessdate=8 April 2020}}</ref>\n\nIn a survey commissioned by the [[Equality Ombudsman]] in 2002/2003, Roma described the discrimination they experience in their daily lives. 90 percent stated that they perceive Sweden to a certain or high degree as a racist country. The same amount agreed to a certain or high degree to the statement that the country has a attitude view towards Roma. 25 percent did neither feel as a part of the Swedish population nor accepted in the Swedish society. And 60 percent said that they have been called derogatory or discriminatory terms related to their ethnic background at least once in the last two years.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.do.se/globalassets/publikationer/rapport-diskriminering-romer-sverige.pdf|date=2004|title=Diskriminering av Romer i Sverige. Rapport fr\u00e5n DO:s projekt \u00e5ren 2002 och 2003 om \u00e5tg\u00e4rder f\u00f6r att f\u00f6rebygga och motverka etnisk diskriminering av Romer|publisher=Ombudsmannen mot etnisk diskriminering|website=do.se|accessdate=8 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n====Slovakia====\n{{Further|Romani people in Slovakia}}\n\nAccording to the last census from 2011, Roma make up 2.0% of the population in [[Slovakia]].\n\nThree Slovakian Romani women have come before the [[European Court of Human Rights]] on grounds of having been forcefully sterilised in Slovakian hospitals. The sterilisations were performed by [[tubal ligation]] after the women gave birth by Caesarean section. The court awarded two of the women costs and damages while the third case was dismissed because of the woman's death.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.hrlc.org.au/forced-sterilisation-of-roma-women-is-inhuman-and-degrading-but-not-discriminatory|title=Forced sterilisation of Roma women is inhuman and degrading but not discriminatory|last=Kinsella|first=Naomi|website=Hrlc.org.au|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://archive.is/20130405150900/http://www.hrlc.org.au/forced-sterilisation-of-roma-women-is-inhuman-and-degrading-but-not-discriminatory|archive-date=5 April 2013|accessdate=10 February 2013}}</ref> A report by the [[Center for Reproductive Rights]] and the Centre for Civil and Human Rights has compiled more than 100 cases of Roma women in Slovakia who have been sterilised without their [[informed consent]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://reproductiverights.org/en/document/body-and-soul-forced-sterilization-and-other-assaults-on-roma-reproductive-freedom|title=Body and Soul: Forced Sterilization and Other Assaults on Roma Reproductive Freedom|publisher=Center for Reproductive Rights|accessdate=11 February 2013}}</ref>\n\nRoma people suffer serious discrimination in Slovakia. Roma children are segregated in school and do not receive the level of education as other Slovakian children. Some are sent to schools for children with mild mental disabilities. As a result, their attainment level is far below average. Amnesty International\u2019s report \"Unfulfilled promises: Failing to end segregation of Roma pupils in Slovakia\" describes the failure of the Slovak authorities to end the discrimination of Roma children on the grounds of their ethnicity in education. According to a 2012 United Nations Development Programme survey, around 43 per cent of Roma in mainstream schools attended ethnically segregated classes.\n\nRoma people are the victims of ethnically driven violence and crime in Slovakia. According to monitoring and reports provided by the European Roma Rights Center (ERRC), racist violence, evictions, threats, and more subtle forms of discrimination have increased over the past years in Slovakia. Although today the situation is a little better as of now (2020), the ERRC considers the situation in Slovakia to be one of the worst in Europe. The 2019 [[Pew Research Center|Pew Research]] poll found that 76% of Slovaks held unfavorable views of Roma.\n\nRomani people receive new housing from municipalities and regional administrations for free every year, however people complain that some of them end up being destroyed by Romani people themselves. After the destruction, in some cases it has happened that the residents receive new housing, without being criminally prosecuted for destroying state property.{{Citation needed|date=March 2020|reason=This claim needs a reliable source; Claims follow typical antiziganism stereotypes without evidence or research. Sus.}}\n====United Kingdom====\nAccording to the LGBT rights organisation and charity [[Stonewall (charity)|''Stonewall'']], anti-Romanyism is prevalent in the UK, with a distinction made between Romani people and [[Irish Travellers]] (both of whom are commonly known by the [[exonym]] \"[[Gypsy (term)|gypsies]]\" in the UK), and the so-called \"travellers [and] modern Gypsies\".<ref>{{cite book|author1=[[Gill Valentine]]|author2=Ian McDonald|title=Understanding Prejudice: Attitudes towards minorities|publisher=[[Stonewall (charity)|Stonewall]]|page=14|url=http://www.stonewall.org.uk/documents/pdf_cover__content.pdf|accessdate=10 January 2015|format=PDF|quote=\"They were also criticised in cultural terms for not belonging to a community and allegedly having a negative impact on the environment: for example, they are unsightly, dirty or unhygienic. A clear distinction was also made between Romany Gypsies, respected for their history and culture, and travellers or modern Gypsies.\"}}</ref> In 2008, the media reported that Gypsies experience a higher degree of racism than any other group in the UK, including asylum-seekers. A Mori poll indicated that a third of UK residents admitted openly to being prejudiced against Gypsies.<ref name=\"shields1\">{{cite news| url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/home-news/no-blacks-no-dogsno-gypsies-860873.html | location=London | work=The Independent | first=Rachel | last=Shields | title=No blacks, no dogs, no Gypsies | date=6 July 2008}}</ref>\n\nThousands of retrospective planning permissions are granted in Britain in cases involving non-Romani applicants each year, and that statistics showed that 90% of planning applications by Romanis and travellers were initially refused by [[Local government in the United Kingdom|local councils]] compared with a national average of 20% for other applicants, disproving claims of preferential treatment favouring Romanis.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cre.gov.uk/gdpract/g_and_t_facts.html |title=Gypsies and Irish Travellers: The facts |publisher=Commission for Racial Equality|url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20071011112335/http://cre.gov.uk/gdpract/g_and_t_facts.html |archivedate=11 October 2007 |df=dmy }}</ref>\nTravellers argued that the root of the problem was that many traditional stopping places had been barricaded off and that legislation passed by the previous Conservative government had effectively criminalised their community. For example, removing local authorities' responsibility to provide sites leaves the travellers with no option but to purchase unregistered new sites themselves.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/insideout/southeast/series8/week_three.shtml|work=[[Inside Out (2002 TV programme)|Inside Out]] \u2013 South East|date=19 September 2005|title=Gypsies|publisher=BBC}}</ref>\n\nIn August 2012, Slovakian television network [[TV JOJ]] ran a report about cases of Romani immigrant families with Slovakian or Czech citizenship, whose children were forcibly taken away by the British authorities. It has sparked Romani protests in towns such as [[Nottingham]]. The authorities refused to explain the reasons for their actions to the Slovak reporters. One of the mothers alleged that she was allowed visitation with her newborn baby only in an empty room; as there was no furniture, she was forced to change her baby's dirty nappies on the floor, which was reflected negatively in a social workers' report. Then, when she would not change the diapers on a subsequent occasion following this experience, failure to change them was reflected negatively in the report as well. TV JOJ also alleged that in another case, a biological mother suffered a nervous breakdown because her children were being taken away, which was seen as proof that she was not able to take care for them and they were then put up for adoption.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.novinky.cz/zahranicni/evropa/276852-britske-urady-udajne-bez-priciny-odebiraji-deti-ceskym-a-slovenskym-romum.html|work=novinky.cz|date=23 August 2005|title=Britsk\u00e9 \u00fa\u0159ady \u00fadajn\u011b bez p\u0159\u00ed\u010diny odeb\u00edraj\u00ed d\u011bti \u010desk\u00fdm a slovensk\u00fdm Rom\u016fm [British authorities allegedly take away children from Czech and Slovak Romanis without any reason]|publisher=novinky.cz|language=Czech}}</ref> The problem was further escalated after reports that some Slovak children would be put up for adoption either in the UK or elsewhere, especially after a British court rejected the request of a grandmother, living in Slovakia, for legal custody of her grandchildren.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://blogs.wsj.com/emergingeurope/2012/09/19/slovak-government-challenges-u-k-foster-care-ruling/|work=Wall Street Journal|date=19 September 2012|title=Slovak Government Challenges U.K. Foster-Care Ruling|publisher=Wall Street Journal}}</ref> This dispute has sparked protests in front of the British embassy in Bratislava, with protesters holding signs such as \"Britain \u2013 Thief of Children\" and \"Stop Legal Kidnappers\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.teraz.sk/fotodennik/protest-pred-britskou-ambasadou-v-brati/24557-fotografia.html#/fotodennik/fotografia/24557|work=teraz.sk|date=18 September 2012|title=Protest pred britskou ambas\u00e1dou v Bratislave|publisher=teraz.sk|language=Slovak}}</ref> According to Slovak media, over 30 Romani children were taken from their parents in Britain. The Slovak government voiced its \"serious concern\" over the readiness of British authorities to remove children from their \"biological parents\" for \"no sound reason\" and further stated its readiness to challenge the policy in front of the [[European Court of Human Rights]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/comment/9545361/Foreign-government-may-take-UK-to-European-court-over-its-illegal-child-snatching.html|work=Daily Telegraph|date=15 September 2012|title=Foreign government may take UK to European court over its 'illegal' child-snatching|publisher=Daily Telegraph|location=London|first=Christopher|last=Booker}}</ref>\n\n=====England=====\nIn 2002 [[Conservative Party (UK)|Conservative Party]] politician, and Member of Parliament (MP) for [[Bracknell (UK Parliament constituency)|Bracknell]] [[Andrew MacKay]] stated in a [[House of Commons of the United Kingdom|House of Commons]] debate on unauthorised encampments of Gypsies and other Travelling groups in the UK, \"They [Gypsies and Travellers] are scum, and I use the word advisedly. People who do what these people have done do not deserve the same human rights as my decent constituents going about their ordinary lives\".<ref>The Gypsy Debate: Can Discourse Control? Joanna Richardson 2006 Imprint academic ch 1 p1.</ref><ref>{{cite book|last=Craig|first=Gary|title=Understanding 'Race' and Ethnicity: Theory, History, Policy, Practice|year=2012|publisher=The Policy Press|isbn=9781847427700|page=153|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=0XTCfyKHqC0C&pg=PA153 |author2=Karl Atkin |author3=Ronny Flynn |author4=Sangeeta Chattoo}}</ref> MacKay subsequently left politics in 2010.<ref>{{cite web|title=Andrew MacKay Former Conservative MP for Bracknell|url=https://www.theyworkforyou.com/mp/andrew_mackay/bracknell|work=[[They Work For You]]|publisher=[[mySociety]]|accessdate=29 July 2012}}</ref>\n\nIn 2005, [[Doncaster Borough Council]] discussed in chamber a Review of Gypsy and Traveller Needs<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.doncaster.gov.uk/db/chamber/default.asp?Nav=Report&ReportID=6091 |title=introduction 2.22 |publisher=Doncaster.gov.uk |date=1 December 2006 |accessdate=17 May 2012 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120901022623/http://www.doncaster.gov.uk/db/chamber/default.asp?Nav=Report&ReportID=6091 |archive-date=1 September 2012 |url-status=dead }}</ref> and concluded that Gypsies and Irish Travellers are among the most vulnerable and marginalised ethnic minority groups in Britain.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.doncaster.gov.uk/db/chamber/default.asp?Nav=Report&ReportID=6091 |title=The Council Chamber |publisher=Doncaster.gov.uk |date=1 December 2006 |accessdate=17 May 2012 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120901022623/http://www.doncaster.gov.uk/db/chamber/default.asp?Nav=Report&ReportID=6091 |archive-date=1 September 2012 |url-status=dead }}</ref><ref>Gypsies and Travellers: A strategy for the CRE, 2004 \u2013 2007</ref>\n\nA Gypsy and Traveller support centre in [[Leeds]], [[West Yorkshire]], was vandalised in April 2011 in what the police suspect was a [[hate-crime]]. The fire caused substantial damage to a centre that is used as a base for the support and education of gypsies and travellers in the community.<ref>{{cite web|last=Bellamy |first=Alison |url=http://www.yorkshireeveningpost.co.uk/news/latest-news/central-leeds/month_closure_for_leeds_traveller_arson_attack_centre_1_3320995 |title=Month closure for Leeds traveller arson attack centre |work=[[Yorkshire Evening Post]] |date=25 April 2011 |accessdate=17 May 2012}}</ref>\n\n=====Scotland=====\nThe Equal Opportunities Committee of the [[Scottish Parliament]] in 2001<ref>{{cite journal|last=Clark|first=Colin|title=Defining Ethnicity in a Cultural and Socio-Legal Context: The Case of Scottish Gypsy-Travellers|journal=[[Scottish Affairs]] Scotland's Longest Running Journal on Contemporary Political and Social Issues|date=Winter 2006|issue=54|pages=39\u201367|url=http://www.scottishaffairs.org/onlinepub/sa/clark_sa54_winter06.html|accessdate=26 December 2012|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131113070454/http://www.scottishaffairs.org/onlinepub/sa/clark_sa54_winter06.html|archive-date=13 November 2013|url-status=dead}}</ref> and in 2009<ref>{{cite web|title=Ethnic Status|url=http://www.scotland.gov.uk/Topics/People/Equality/gypsiestravellers/ethnic|work=The Scottish Government|publisher=The Scottish Government|accessdate=26 December 2012|date=22 January 2010}}</ref> confirmed that widespread marginalisation and discrimination persists in Scottish society against gypsy and traveller groups. A 2009 survey conducted by the Scottish Government also concludes that Scottish gypsy and travellers had been largely ignored in official policies. A similar survey in 2006 found discriminatory attitudes in Scotland towards gypsies and travellers,<ref name=\"scotland.gov.uk\">{{cite web|title=Attitudes to Discrimination in Scotland 2006: Scottish Social Attitudes Survey \u2013 Research Findings|url=http://www.scotland.gov.uk/Publications/2007/12/04093547/1|work=The Scottish Government|publisher=The Scottish Government|accessdate=26 December 2012|author=Scottish Government Social Research|date=4 December 2007}}</ref> and showed 37 percent of those questioned would be unhappy if a relative married a gypsy or traveller while 48 percent found it unacceptable if a member of the gypsy or traveller minorities became primary school teachers.<ref name=\"scotland.gov.uk\"/>\n\nA report by the [[University of the West of Scotland]] found that both Scottish and UK governments had failed to safeguard the rights of the Roma as a recognized ethnic group and did not raise awareness of Roma rights within the UK.<ref>{{cite web|title=Report on the Situation of the Roma Community in Govanhill, Glasgow|url=http://www.bemis.org.uk/resources/gt/scotland/report%20on%20the%20situation%20of%20the%20roma%20community%20in%20govanhill,%20Glasgow.pdf|work=Report on the Situation of the Roma Community in Govanhill, Glasgow|publisher=University of the West of Scotland|accessdate=26 December 2012|author=Lynne Poole|author2=Kevin Adamson|format=PDF|year=2008}}</ref> Additionally, an Amnesty International report published in 2012 stated that Gypsy Traveller groups in Scotland routinely suffer widespread discrimination in society,<ref name=\"amnesty.org.uk\">{{cite web|title=Caught in the Headlines \u2013 Scottish Media Coverage of Scottish Gypsy Travellers|url=http://amnesty.org.uk/uploads/documents/doc_22449.pdf|work=Caught in the Headlines \u2013 Scottish Media Coverage of Scottish Gypsy Travellers|publisher=Amnesty International in Scotland|accessdate=26 December 2012|author=Amnesty International in Scotland|author2=Napier University MSc Journalism|format=PDF|date=2 April 2012}}</ref> as well as a disproportionate level of scrutiny in the media.<ref>{{cite web|title=Gypsies/Travellers in Scotland: The Twice Yearly Count \u2013 No. 16: July 2009|url=http://www.scotland.gov.uk/Publications/2010/08/18105029/9|work=The Scottish Government|publisher=The Scottish Government|accessdate=26 December 2012|format=PDF|date=30 August 2010}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Gypsy/Traveller Numbers in the UK \u2013 A General Overview|url=http://www.article12.org/pdf/GYPSY%20TRAVELLER%20NUMBERS%20IN%20THE%20UK.pdf|work=Article12.org|publisher=YGTL \u2013 Article 12 in Scotland|accessdate=26 December 2012|author=Beth Cadger|year=2009|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131217221614/http://www.article12.org/pdf/GYPSY%20TRAVELLER%20NUMBERS%20IN%20THE%20UK.pdf|archive-date=17 December 2013|url-status=dead}}</ref> Over a four-month period as a sample 48 per cent of articles showed Gypsy Travellers in a negative light, while 25\u201328 per cent of articles were favourable, or of a neutral viewpoint.<ref name=\"amnesty.org.uk\"/> Amnesty recommended journalists adhere to ethical codes of conduct when reporting on Gypsy Traveller populations in Scotland, as they face fundamental human rights concerns, particularly with regard to health, education, housing, family life and culture.<ref name=\"amnesty.org.uk\"/>\n\nTo tackle the widespread prejudices and needs of Gypsy/Traveller minorities, in 2011, the Scottish Government set up a working party to consider how best to improve community relations between Gypsies/Travellers and Scottish society.<ref>{{cite web|title=Working Party Strategy|url=http://www.scotland.gov.uk/Topics/Built-Environment/Housing/16342/management/gt/wpstrategy|publisher=The Scottish Government|accessdate=26 December 2012|date=22 March 2011}}</ref> Including young Gypsies/Travellers to engage in an on-line positive messages campaign, contain factually correct information on their communities.<ref>{{cite web|title=Finance and Sustainable Growth|url=http://www.scottish.parliament.uk/S4_ChamberDesk/WA20110727.pdf|work=Scottish Parliament \u2013 Scottish Executive|publisher=Scottish Parliament|accessdate=26 December 2012|format=PDF|date=27 July 2011}}</ref>\n\n=====Wales=====\nIn 2007 a study by the newly formed [[Equality and Human Rights Commission]] found that negative attitudes and prejudice persists against Gypsy/Traveller communities in Wales.<ref name=\"equalityhumanrights.com\">{{cite web|title=Who Do You See? \u2013 Living together in Wales|url=http://www.equalityhumanrights.com/uploaded_files/download_who_do_you_see_publication_english.pdf|work=Equality and Human Rights Commission|publisher=Equality and Human Rights Commission|accessdate=26 December 2012|format=PDF|year=2008|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120610021426/http://equalityhumanrights.com/uploaded_files/download_who_do_you_see_publication_english.pdf|archive-date=10 June 2012|url-status=dead}}</ref> Results showed that 38 percent of those questioned would not accept a long-term relationship with, or would be unhappy if a close relative married or formed a relationship with, a Gypsy Traveller. Furthermore, only 37 percent found it acceptable if a member of the Gypsy Traveller minorities became primary school teachers, the lowest score of any group.<ref name=\"equalityhumanrights.com\"/> An advertising campaign to tackle prejudice in Wales was launched by the [[Equality and Human Rights Commission|Equality and Human Rights Commission (EHRC)]] in 2008.<ref>{{cite web|title=Kirby faces up to anti-Gypsy feeling in Wales|url=http://www.travellerstimes.org.uk/list.aspx?c=00619ef1-21e2-40aa-8d5e-f7c38586d32f&n=f52bed58-5368-408f-b50f-b543344a1b60|work=Travellers' Times|publisher=The Rural Media Company|accessdate=26 December 2012|author=Jake Bowers|format=Audio upload and article|date=21 October 2008|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130607110214/http://www.travellerstimes.org.uk/list.aspx?c=00619EF1-21E2-40AA-8D5E-F7C38586D32F&n=F52BED58-5368-408F-B50F-B543344A1B60|archive-date=7 June 2013|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\n=====Northern Ireland=====\nIn June 2009, having had their windows broken and deaths threats made against them, 20 Romanian Romani families were forced from their homes in [[Lisburn Road]], [[Belfast]], in [[Northern Ireland]]. Up to 115 people, including women and children, were forced to seek refuge in a local [[church hall]] after being attacked. They were later moved by the authorities to a safer location.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.irishtimes.com/newspaper/opinion/2009/0618/1224249058810.html|title=Racist attacks on Roma are latest low in North's intolerant history|date=18 June 2009|publisher=irishtimes.com|accessdate=18 June 2009}}</ref> An [[Anti-racism|anti-racist]] rally in the city on 15 June to support Romani rights was attacked by youths chanting [[neo-Nazi]] slogans. The attacks were condemned by [[Amnesty International]]<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.amnesty.org.uk/news_details.asp?NewsID=18257 |title=Amnesty International |publisher=Amnesty.org.uk |date=17 June 2009 |accessdate=17 May 2012}}</ref> and political leaders from both the [[Unionism in Ireland|Unionist]] and [[Irish nationalism|Nationalist]] traditions in Northern Ireland.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.google.com/hostednews/ap/article/ALeqM5iDji7_Kp0M1B_ADrZ0T9-dBi-xpwD98SI4HG0|title=Romanian Gypsies attacked inIreland|last=Morrison|first=Peter|last2=Lawless|first2=Jill|first3=Meera |last3=Selva |first4=Nardine |last4=Saad |first5=Alina |last5=Wolfe Murray|date=17 June 2009|agency=Associated Press|accessdate=18 June 2009| archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20090623081024/https://www.google.com/hostednews/ap/article/ALeqM5iDji7_Kp0M1B_ADrZ0T9-dBi-xpwD98SI4HG0| archivedate= 23 June 2009 | url-status= live}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/uk_news/northern_ireland/8110950.stm|title=Protest held over racist attacks|date=20 June 2009|work=BBC News|accessdate=20 June 2009| archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20090622034016/http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/uk_news/northern_ireland/8110950.stm| archivedate= 22 June 2009 | url-status= live}}</ref>\n\nFollowing the arrest of three local youths in relation to the attacks, the church where the Romanis had been given shelter was badly vandalised. Using 'emergency funds', Northern Ireland authorities assisted most of the victims to return to Romania.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/uk/2009/jun/23/belfast-church-vandalised-racist-attacks-romanians|title=Vandals attack Belfast church that sheltered Romanian victims of racism|last= McDonald|first=Henry|date=23 June 2009|work=guardian.co.uk|accessdate=23 June 2009 | location=London| archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20090626063353/http://www.guardian.co.uk/uk/2009/jun/23/belfast-church-vandalised-racist-attacks-romanians| archivedate= 26 June 2009 | url-status= live}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/uk_news/northern_ireland/8114234.stm|title=Romanians leave NI after attacks|date=23 June 2009|publisher=BBC News website|accessdate=23 June 2009| archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20090624091208/http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/uk_news/northern_ireland/8114234.stm| archivedate= 24 June 2009 | url-status= live}}</ref>\n\n===Non-EU countries===\n\n====Canada====\nWhen Romani [[refugee]]s were allowed into Canada in 1997, a protest was staged by 25 people, including [[neo-Nazi]]s, in front of the motel where the refugees were staying. The protesters held signs that included, \"Honk if you hate Gypsies\", \"Canada is not a Trash Can\", and \"G.S.T. \u2013 Gypsies Suck Tax\". (The last is a reference to Canada's unpopular [[Goods and Services Tax (Canada)|Goods and Services Tax]], also known as GST.) The protesters were charged with promoting hatred, and the case, called ''[[R. v. Krymowski]]'', reached the [[Supreme Court of Canada]] in 2005.<ref>''[[R. v. Krymowski]]'' [2005] 1 S.C.R. 101.</ref>\n\nOn 5 September 2012, prominent Canadian conservative commentator [[Ezra Levant]] broadcast a commentary \"The Jew vs. the Gypsies\" on ''[[J-Source (website)|J-Source]]'' in which he accused the [[Romani people]] of being a group of criminals: \"These are gypsies, a culture synonymous with swindlers. The phrase gypsy and cheater have been so interchangeable historically that the word has entered the English language as a verb: he [[:wikt:gyp|gypped]] me. Well the gypsies have gypped us. Too many have come here as false refugees. And they come here to gyp us again and rob us blind as they have done in Europe for centuries.\u2026 They\u2019re gypsies. And one of the central characteristics of that culture is that their chief economy is theft and begging.\"<ref name=jsource>{{cite news|title=Hate crime investigation launched surrounding Ezra Levant's Roma broadcast|url=http://j-source.ca/article/hate-crime-investigation-launched-surrounding-ezra-levant%E2%80%99s-roma-broadcast|accessdate=25 October 2012|newspaper=J-Source (website)|publisher=[[The Canadian Journalism Foundation]]|date=24 October 2012}}</ref>\n\n====Kosovo====\nFrom the end of the [[Kosovo War]] in June 1999, about 80% of [[Kosovo]]'s{{ref label|status|a|}} Romanis were expelled, amounting to approximately 100,000 expellees.<ref name=cahn>{{Citation|author=Claude Cahn |year=2007 |title=Birth of a Nation: Kosovo and the Persecution of Pariah Minorities |journal=[[German Law Journal]] |volume=8 |issue=1 |issn=2071-8322 |url=http://www.germanlawjournal.org/pdfs/Vol08No01/PDF_Vol_08_No_01_81-94_SI_Cahn.pdf |mode=cs1 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150215183028/http://www.germanlawjournal.org/pdfs/Vol08No01/PDF_Vol_08_No_01_81-94_SI_Cahn.pdf |archivedate=15 February 2015 |df=dmy }}</ref>{{rp|82}} For the 1999\u20132006 period, the [[European Roma Rights Centre]] documented numerous crimes perpetrated by Kosovo's ethnic Albanians with the purpose to purge the region of its Romani population along with other non-Albanian ethnic communities. These crimes included murder, abduction and illegal detention, torture, rape, arson, confiscation of houses and other property and forced labour. Whole Romani settlements were burned to the ground by Albanians.<ref name=cahn/>{{rp|82}} Romanis remaining in Kosovo are reported to be systematically denied fundamental human rights. They \"live in a state of pervasive fear\"<ref name=cahn/>{{rp|83}} and are routinely intimidated, verbally harassed and periodically attacked on racist grounds by Albanians.<ref name=cahn/>{{rp|83}} The Romani community of Kosovo is regarded to be, for the most part, annihilated.<ref name=cahn/>{{rp|93}}\n\nAt [[Roma in United Nations refugee camps, Kosovska Mitrovica|UN internally displaced persons' camps in Kosovska Mitrovica for Romanis]], the refugees were exposed to lead poisoning.<ref>{{cite web |author=Gesellschaft fuer bedrohte Voelker \u2013 Society for Threatened Peoples |url=http://www.gfbv.de/inhaltsDok.php?id=435&stayInsideTree=1 |title=Lead Poisoning of Roma in Idp Camps in Kosovo |publisher=Gfbv.de |accessdate=17 May 2012 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110719033156/http://www.gfbv.de/inhaltsDok.php?id=435&stayInsideTree=1 |archive-date=19 July 2011 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\n====Norway====\nIn [[Norway]], many Romani people were forcibly sterilized by the state until 1977.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.newint.org/features/2008/01/01/roma/|title=The eternal minority|publisher=New Internationalist|first=Eleanor|last=Harding|date=January 2008|accessdate=15 April 2008| archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20080430212911/http://www.newint.org/features/2008/01/01/roma/| archivedate= 30 April 2008 | url-status= live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/?id=j5TdqodY_QwC&pg=PA173&lpg=PA173&dq=Norway+roma+sterilisation|title=The Nordic peace|contribution=The non-autonomous minority groups in the Nordic countries|last=Hannikainen|first=Lauri|last2=\u00c5kermark|first2=Sia Spiliopoulou|pages=171\u2013197|editor-last=Clive|editor-first=Archer|editor2-last=Joenniemi|editor2-first=Pertti|year=2003|location=Aldershot|isbn=978-0-7546-1417-3|publisher=Ashgate|postscript=<!--None-->}}</ref>\n\nAnti-Romanyism in Norway flared up in July 2012, when roughly 200 Romani people settled outside [[:no:Sofienberg kirke|Sofienberg church]] in Oslo and were later relocated to a building site at [[\u00c5rvoll]], in northern Oslo. The group was subjected to [[hate crime]]s in the form of stone throwing and fireworks being aimed at and fired into their camp. They, and Norwegians trying to assist them in their situation, also received [[death threat]]s.<ref>{{cite web|title=Folk er folk-leder sier han har f\u00e5tt flere drapstrusler|url=http://www.aftenposten.no/nyheter/iriks/Folk-er-folk-leder-sier-han-har-fatt-flere-drapstrusler-6943346.html|accessdate=31 July 2012}}</ref> [[Siv Jensen]], the leader of the right-wing [[Progress Party (Norway)|Progress Party]], also advocated the expulsion of the Romani people resident in Oslo.<ref>{{cite news|title=Jensen: \u2013 Nok er nok, sett opp buss, send dem ut|url=http://www.nrk.no/nyheter/norge/1.8244413|accessdate=26 December 2012|newspaper=NRK|date=15 July 2012|last1=Solvang|first1=Fredrik|last2=Haga Honnings\u00f8y|first2=Kirsti|language=Norwegian}}</ref>\n\n====Switzerland====\nA Swiss right-wing magazine, Weltwoche, published a photograph of a gun-wielding Roma child on its cover in 2012, with the title \"The Roma are coming: Plundering in Switzerland\". They claimed in a series of articles of a growing trend in the country of \"criminal tourism for which eastern European Roma clans are responsible\", with professional gangs specializing in burglary, thefts, organized begging and street prostitution.<ref name=\"irishtimes1\">{{cite news|author=Email Us |url=https://www.irishtimes.com/newspaper/world/2012/0412/1224314639219.html |title=Magazine under fire for racist Roma cover \u2013 The Irish Times \u2013 Thu, 12 April 2012 |newspaper=The Irish Times |date=12 April 2012 |accessdate=17 May 2012}}</ref> The magazine immediately came under criticism for its links to the right-wing populist [[Swiss People's Party|People's Party (SVP)]], as being deliberately provocative and encouraged racist stereotyping by linking ethnic origin and criminality.<ref name=\"irishtimes1\"/> Switzerland's Federal Commission against Racism is considering legal action after complaints in Switzerland, Austria and Germany that the cover breached antiracism laws.\n\nThe Berlin newspaper ''[[Tagesspiegel]]'' investigated the origins of the photograph taken in the slums of [[Gjakova]], [[Kosovo]], where Roma communities were displaced during the [[Kosovo War]] to hovels built on a toxic landfill.<ref>{{cite web|author=von Andrea Dernbach |url=http://www.tagesspiegel.de/medien/streit-um-roma-reportage-raubzuege-beim-fotografen/6498056.html |title=Streit um Roma-Reportage: Raubz\u00fcge beim Fotografen \u2013 Medien \u2013 Tagesspiegel |language=de |publisher=Tagesspiegel.de |accessdate=17 May 2012}}</ref> The Italian photographer, Livio Mancini, denounced the abuse of his photograph, which was originally taken to demonstrate the plight of Roma families in Europe.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.presseurop.eu/en/content/news-brief/1799581-anti-roma-front-page-provokes-controversy |title=Anti-Roma front page provokes controversy &#124; Presseurop (English) |publisher=[[Presseurop]] |accessdate=17 May 2012}}</ref>\n\n==== New Zealand ====\n''The Great Replacement'' manifesto by [[Christchurch mosque shootings|Christchurch mosques shooter]] [[Brenton Harrison Tarrant]] described [[Roma people|Roma/Gypsies]] as among one of the non-Europeans alongside [[Black people|African]], [[Indian people|Indian]], [[Turkish people|Turkish]], and [[Semitic people|Semitic]] ([[Jews|Jewish]] and [[Arabs|Arab]]) peoples that the shooter wanted to be removed from [[Europe]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.ilfogilo.it/userUpload/The_Great_Replacementconvertito.pdf|title=The Great Replacement|quote=\"The invaders must be removed from European soil, regardless whether they came or when they came. Roma, African, Indian, Turkish, Semitic, or other\"|access-date=March 24, 2019|date=March 15, 2019}}</ref>\n\n==== United States ====\n=====Elsie Paroubek Affair (1911)=====\nIn [[Chicago]] in 1911, the highly-publicised disappearance of the five-year old [[Elsie Paroubek]] was immediately blamed on \"Gypsy child kidnappers\". The public was alerted to reports that \"Gypsies were seen with a little girl\" and many such reports came in. Police raided a \"Gypsy\" encampment near 18th and South Halstead in Chicago itself and they later expanded the searches and raids to encampments throughout the state of [[Illinois]], to locations as widespread as [[Round Lake, Illinois|Round Lake]], [[McHenry, Illinois|McHenry]], [[Volo, Illinois|Volo]] and [[Cherry Valley, Illinois|Cherry Valley]] - but they found no trace of the missing girl. The police attributed her capture to \"the natural love of the wandering people for blue-eyed, yellow-haired children\".<ref name=\"romanyrye\">{{Citation |newspaper=Los Angeles Times |page=I6 |title=Think Gypsies Have His Girl: Father & A Policeman on the Trail of Nomads.  |url=https://pqasb.pqarchiver.com/latimes/access/348133382.html?dids=348133382:348133382&FMT=ABS&FMTS=ABS:AI&type=historic&date=Apr+15%2C+1911&author=&pub=Los+Angeles+Times&desc=THINK+GYPSIES+HAVE+HIS+GIRL.&pqatl=google |date=April 15, 1911}}</ref> Lillian Wulff, age 11 - who had actually been kidnapped by some Romanis four years earlier - came forward to offer his assistance, leading the police to conduct further fruitless raids, as well as convincing them to detain the supposed \"King of the Gypsies\", Elijah George - who, however,\"failed to give them the desired information\", and was released. Elijah George was detained in [[Argyle, Wisconsin]], and this served to spread the anti-Romani hysteria outside Illinois.\n\nThe police finally abandoned this line of investigation. Still, when the girl's body was finally found, her distraught father Frank Paroubek charged: \"I am sure the gypsies stole my girl and then when they knew we were after them, they killed her and threw her body into the canal.\" The anti-Romani agitation might have been exacerbated by the fact that the missing girl was a [[Czech Americans|Czech American]], and the Czech American community massively mobilized to participate in the searches and support her family. This might have had the inadvertent result of importing the prejudices which were prevalent in Czech society to America.\n\n=====Present Situation=====\nAt the present time, because the Roma population in the [[United States]] has quickly assimilated and Roma people are not often portrayed in US popular culture, the term \"Gypsy\" is typically associated with a trade or lifestyle instead of being associated with the Romani ethnic group. While many Americans consider ethnic costumes offensive (such as [[blackface]]), many Americans continue to dress up as gypsy characters for [[Halloween]] or other events. Additionally, some small businesses, particularly those in the [[fortune-telling]] and psychic reading industry,<ref>{{cite web|title=Real Stories From Victims Who've Been Scammed |url=http://www.gypsypsychicscams.com/realstories.html |publisher=gypsypsychicscams.com |accessdate=26 August 2007 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070826075723/http://www.gypsypsychicscams.com/realstories.html |archivedate=26 August 2007 |url-status=dead }}</ref> use the term \"Gypsy\" to describe themselves or their enterprises, even though they have no ties to the Roma people. Some do, however, as perhaps up to a million Americans, have Romani ancestry (see [[Romani Americans]]), but they are usually of partial Romani descent.\n\nWhile some scholars argue that appropriation of the Roma identity in the United States is based on misconceptions and ignorance rather than anti-Romanyism,<ref>{{cite book |last=Sutherland |first=Anne |year=1986 |title=Gypsies: The Hidden Americans |publisher=Waveland Press |page=86 |isbn=978-0-88133-235-3}}</ref> Romani advocacy groups decry the practice.<ref>{{cite web |website=Voice of Roma |title=Breaking 'Gypsy' Stereotypes |date=23 March 2010 |url=http://www.voiceofroma.com/culture/gyp_vs_rom.shtml}}</ref>\n\n==Environmental struggles==\n{{More citations needed section|date=December 2012}}\n{{see also|Environmental racism in Europe}}\n\nEnvironmental issues which were caused by [[Cold War]]-era industrial development have disproportionately impacted the Roma, particularly those Roma who live in Eastern Europe. Most often, the traditional nomadic lifestyle of the Roma causes them to settle on the outskirts of towns and cities, where amenities, employment and educational opportunities are often inaccessible. As of 1993, [[Hungary]] has been identified as one country where this issue exists: \"While the economic restructuring of a command economy into a western style market economy created hardships for most Hungarians, with the national unemployment rate heading toward 14 percent and per capita real income falling, the burdens which are imposed on Romanis are disproportionately great.\"<ref name=\"Feher, 1993\">Feher, Gyorgy. 1993. ''Struggling for Ethnic Identity: The Gypsies of Hungary''. Library of Congress Card Catalogue: USA.</ref>\n\nPanel buildings ([[panel\u00e1k]]) in the Chanov ghetto near [[Most (Most District)|Most]], [[Czech Republic]] were built in the 1970s for a high-income clientele, the authorities introduced a model plan, whereby Roma were relocated to these buildings, from poorer areas, to live among Czech neighbors. However, with the rising proportion of Roma moving in, the Czech clients gradually moved out in a kind of [[white flight]], eventually leaving a district in which the vast majority of residents were Roma.<ref name=\"janousek\">{{Citation\n| last = Janou\u0161ek\n| first = Artur\n| author-link =\n| publication-date =\n| date =  18 September 2007\n| title = Hr\u016fza \u00dasteck\u00e9ho kraje: s\u00eddli\u0161t\u011b Chanov\n| periodical = iDnes.cz\n| series =\n| publication-place =\n| place =\n| publisher =\n| volume =\n| issue =\n| pages =\n| page =\n| at =\n| url = http://zpravy.idnes.cz/hruza-usteckeho-kraje-sidliste-chanov-dx9-/domaci.asp?c=A070918_090742_domaci_itu\n| issn =\n| pmid =\n| pmc =\n| doi =\n| oclc =\n| accessdate =13 March 2011\n| ref =\n|language=cs}}</ref> A poll in 2007 marked the district as the worst place in the [[\u00dast\u00ed nad Labem Region]].<ref name=\"janousek\"/> Buildings were eventually stripped of any valuable materials and torn down. The removal of materials was blamed on the Roma who had last inhabited the building.<ref>{{Citation\n| last = \u010cTK\n| first =\n| author-link = Czech News Agency\n| date = 23 June 2006\n| title = V Chanov\u011b se bude bourat i druh\u00fd vybydlen\u00fd panel\u00e1k\n| periodical = ceskenoviny.cz\n| series =\n| publication-place =\n| place =\n| publisher = Czech News Agency\n| volume =\n| issue =\n| pages =\n| page =\n| at =\n| url = http://www.ceskenoviny.cz/zpravy/v-chanove-se-bude-bourat-i-druhy-vybydleny-panelak/494893&id_seznam=\n| issn =\n| pmid =\n| pmc =\n| doi =\n| oclc =\n| accessdate =13 March 2011\n| ref =\n|language=cs}}</ref> Despite a total rental debt in excess of \u20ac3.5 million, all of the tenants in the remaining buildings continue to be provided with water and electricity,<ref>{{Citation\n| last = Sl\u00ed\u017eov\u00e1\n| first = Radka\n| author-link =\n| publication-date = 25 February 2010\n| title = Chanov jde do lep\u0161\u00edch \u010das\u016f\n| periodical = sedmicka.cz\n| series =\n| publication-place =\n| place =\n| publisher =\n| volume =\n| issue =\n| pages =\n| page =\n| at =\n| url = http://www.sedmicka.cz/chomutov-jirkov-litvinov-most/clanek?id=130307\n| issn =\n| pmid =\n| pmc =\n| doi =\n| oclc =\n| accessdate =13 March 2011\n| ref =\n|language=cs}}</ref> unlike the situation in many other European countries.\n[[File:LunikIX.jpeg|thumb|Roma settlement [[Lun\u00edk IX]] near [[Ko\u0161ice]], Slovakia.]] When newly built in the 1980s, some flats in this settlement were assigned to Roma who had relocated from poverty-stricken locations in a government effort to integrate the Roma population. Other flats were assigned to families of military and law-enforcement personnel. However, the military and police families gradually moved out of the residences and the living conditions for the Roma population deteriorated. Ongoing failures to pay bills led to the disconnection of the water supply and an emergency plan was eventually created to provide running water for two hours per day to mitigate against the bill payment issue. Similarly to Chanov, some of these buildings were stripped of their materials and were eventually torn down; again, the Roma residents were identified as the culprits who were to blame for the theft of the materials.<ref>{{cite web\n| last = Prokop\n| first = Dan\n| authorlink =\n| title = Ko\u0161ice zbouraj\u00ed \"vybydlen\u00e9\" panel\u00e1ky na romsk\u00e9m s\u00eddli\u0161ti Lun\u00edk\n| work = idnes.cz\n| publisher =\n| date = 28 September 2008\n| url = http://zpravy.idnes.cz/kosice-zbouraji-vybydlene-panelaky-na-romskem-sidlisti-lunik-p6p-/zahranicni.asp?c=A080805_163403_zahranicni_dp\n| doi =\n| accessdate =13 March 2011|language=cs}}</ref><ref>\n{{cite web\n| title = LUN\u00cdK IX.: B\u00fdvanie na s\u00eddlisku je kritick\u00e9, obyvate\u013eom zriadili konto na pomoc\n| work = tvnoviny.sk\n| date = 18 March 2010\n| url = http://tvnoviny.sk/spravy/krimi/lunik-ix-byvanie-na-sidlisku-je-kriticke-obyvatelom-zriadili-konto-na-pomoc.html\n| accessdate = 13 March 2011\n| language = sk\n| archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20110725105554/http://tvnoviny.sk/spravy/krimi/lunik-ix-byvanie-na-sidlisku-je-kriticke-obyvatelom-zriadili-konto-na-pomoc.html\n| archive-date = 25 July 2011\n| url-status = dead\n}}\n</ref><ref>{{cite web\n| last = Teichmanov\u00e1\n| first = Ladislava\n| authorlink =\n| title = Na Lun\u00edku IX a v Demeteri dlhuj\u00fa za vodu 133 000 \u20ac\n| work = webnoviny.sk\n| publisher =\n| url = http://www.webnoviny.sk/slovensko/na-luniku-ix-a-v-demeteri-dlhuju-za-vo/21765-clanok.html\n| doi =\n| accessdate =13 March 2011|language=sk}}</ref><ref>{{cite web\n| last = \u010cTK\n| authorlink = Czech News Agency\n| title = Na ko\u0161ick\u00e9m romsk\u00e9m s\u00eddli\u0161ti Lun\u00edk IX. zase te\u010de voda\n| work = romove.radio.cz\n| date = 5 May 2005\n| url = http://romove.radio.cz/cz/clanek/20588\n| accessdate =13 March 2011| archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20110306005122/http://romove.radio.cz/cz/clanek/20588| archivedate= 6 March 2011 | url-status= live|language=cs}}</ref>\n\nThe various legal hindrances to their traditional nomadic lifestyle have forced many travelling Roma to move into unsafe areas, such as ex-industrial areas, former landfills or other waste areas where pollutants have affected rivers, streams or groundwater. Consequently, Roma are often unable to access clean water or sanitation facilities, rendering the Roma people more vulnerable to health problems, such as [[disease]]s. Based in [[Belgium]], the Health & Environment Alliance has included a statement with regard to the Roma on one of its pamphlets: \"Denied environmental benefits such as water, sewage treatment facilities, sanitation and access to natural resources, and suffer from exposure to environmental hazards due to their proximity to hazardous waste sites, incinerators, factories, and other sources of pollution.\"<ref name=\"Environmental Health\">{{cite web|title= Environmental Justice: Listening to Women and Children|publisher=Environmental Health|url= http://www.env-health.org/IMG/pdf/cepl_final-2.pdf}}</ref> Since the [[Revolutions of 1989|fall of communism]] and the privatisation of the formerly state owned water-supply companies in many areas of central and eastern Europe, the provision of decent running water to illegal buildings which are often occupied by Roma became a particularly sensitive issue, because the new international owners of the water-supply companies are unwilling to make contracts with the Roma population and as a result, \"water-borne diseases, such as [[diarrhoea]] and [[dysentery]]\" became \"an almost constant feature of daily life, especially for children\".\n\nAccording to a study that was conducted by the [[United Nations Development Program]], the percentage of Roma with access to running water and sewage treatment within Romania and the Czech Republic is well below the national average in those countries. Consequently, a proliferation of skin diseases among these populations, due to the low quality of housing standards, including [[scabies]], [[pediculosis]], [[pyoderma]], [[mycosis]] and [[ascariasis]], has occurred; respiratory health problems also affect the majority of the inhabitants of these areas, in addition to increasing rates of [[hepatitis]] and [[tuberculosis]].{{Citation needed|date=December 2012}}\n\nAdditionally, the permanent settlement of Roma in residential areas is often met with hostility by non-Roma or the exodus of non-Roma, a reaction which is similar to [[white flight]] in the [[United States]].<ref name=\"Harper, 2009\">{{cite web|title=Environmental Justice and Roma Communities in Central and Eastern Europe|url=http://works.bepress.com/cgi/viewcontent.cgi?article=1001&context=krista_harper|work=Environmental Justice and Roma Communities in Central and Eastern Europe|publisher=University of Massachusetts \u2013 Amherst|accessdate=26 December 2012|author=Krista M. Harper PhD|author2=Tamara Steger, PhD|author3=Richard Fil\u010d\u00e1k, PhD|format=PDF|date=July 2009}}</ref> Moreover, local councils have issued bans against Roma, who are frequently evicted.{{Citation needed|date=December 2012}}\n\n==In popular culture==\n\n* In \"The Big Clan\" episode of the television show \"[[Dragnet (1967 TV series)|Dragnet]],\" originally broadcast on February 8, 1968, Sgt. Friday (Jack Webb) indicates the gypsies are a criminal organization.\n* In the 2006 mockumentary ''[[Borat]]'', [[Sacha Baron Cohen]]'s character explains that his home town has \"a tall fence for keeping out Gypsies and Jews\"; the scene featuring this town was filmed in [[Moroeni|Glod]], a Roma village in central Romania. He makes many more anti-Romani statements throughout the film.\n* ''[[The Adventures of Tintin]]'' comic ''[[The Castafiore Emerald]]'' criticises anti-Romanyism.  After [[Captain Haddock]] invites a group of Roma to move onto his property, they are falsely accused of stealing [[Bianca Castafiore]]'s priceless [[emerald]]. [[Tintin (character)|Tintin]] objects to other characters who express their suspicion and uncovers the real culprit to have been a [[magpie]].\n* In several adaptations of [[Victor Hugo]]'s ''[[The Hunchback of Notre Dame]]'' such as the [[The Hunchback of Notre Dame (1996 film)|1996 Disney version]], [[Claude Frollo]] is portrayed as having a strong, genocidal hatred of gypsies, although this characteristic is not so evident in the original novel.\n* Many instances of Anti-Romanyism are described in Kristian Novak's 2016 novel ''Ziganin but the most beautiful''.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Krmpoti\u0107|first1=Marinko|title=\"Ciganin al' najljep\u0161i\" Kristijana Novaka: Mra\u010dna tema za \u010ditateljsko u\u017eivanje / Novi list|url=http://www.novilist.hr/Kultura/Knjizevnost/Ciganin-al-najljepsi-Kristijana-Novaka-Mracna-tema-za-citateljsko-uzivanje|website=[[Novi list]]|accessdate=3 May 2018|language=hr-HR|date=1 August 2017}}</ref>\n*The 2000 [[Guy Ritchie]] crime drama [[Snatch (film)|''Snatch'']] shows anti-[[Irish Travellers|Irish Traveller]] sentiment among Britons.\n\n==See also==<!-- Please respect alphabetical order -->\n* [[Afrophobia]]\n* [[\u00c0 la zingara]]\n* [[Antisemitism]]\n* [[Aporophobia]]\n* [[Caste]]\n* [[Cultural assimilation]]\n* [[Discrimination]]\n* [[Discrimination law]]\n* [[Environmental racism in Europe]]\n* [[Human Rights]]\n* [[Institutionalized discrimination]]\n* [[Indophobia]]\n* [[Racism]]\n* [[Second-class citizen]]\n* [[Sinophobia]]\n\n==Notes==\n{| style=\"margin-left:13px; line-height:150%\"\n|align=\"right\" valign=\"top\"|a.&nbsp;&nbsp;\n|{{note|status}}{{Kosovo-note}}\n|}\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n* [http://www.humanrightsfirst.org/discrimination/pages.aspx?id=85 Human Rights First Report on Violence Against Roma]\n* [http://www.coe.int/t/dg3/romatravellers/documentation/discrimination/knudsen_en.asp Council of Europe webpage on anti-Romanyism]\n* [http://www.ezaf.org/ European Centre for Antiziganism Research]\n* [http://www.osce.org/odihr/18148.html OSCE/ODIHR portal on Roma and Sinti issues]\n* [http://www.errc.org/ European Roma Rights Centre]\n\n{{Anti-cultural sentiment}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Anti-national sentiment]]\n[[Category:Anti-Romanyism| ]]\n[[Category:Genocides]]\n[[Category:Romani]]\n[[Category:Racism in the United Kingdom]]\n", "name_user": "Arjayay", "label": "safe", "comment": "Reword - you can't be \"among one\"", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Antiziganism"}
